<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Aqueduct-Quake     06-15 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aqueduct-Quake,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aqueduct Flowing Again Following Quake Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Aqueduct, which supplies half
of Southern California's water, was re-opened Tuesday following
repairs to fix damage from an earthquake last week, officials said.
   Three of 14 pumps at the A.D. Edmonston Pumping Plant in the
Tehachapi Mountains began pumping water to the 440-mile waterway at
3 p.m. and another two came on line at 4 p.m., said Dave Taylor,
dispatcher for the state water project.
   Repairs were still being made to other circuit breakers at the
plant, he said, but it was unknown when they would be complete.
   All water deliveries north of the plant were undisturbed during
the shutdown. But deliveries to the south had been coming from
water already in storage.
   The quake, measuring 5.2 on the Richter scale, hit the Garlock
fault near Gorman, 60 miles north of downtown Los Angeles. It was
followed by two aftershocks, measuring 4.0 and 3.4 respectively.
   The pumping station is located in the Tehachapi Mountans, 75
miles northwest of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
