<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece-Turkey     06-15 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Turkey,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Rules Out Troop Withdrawal From Cyprus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOULIAGMENI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish Premier Turgut Ozal on
Tuesday ruled out any withdrawal of Turkish troops from the divided
Mediterranean island of Cyprus unless there is a complete
settlement of Greek-Turkish disputes.
   ``I would like to see a solution to the Cyprus problem, but it
should be a complete one,'' Ozal told reporters on the second day
of his three-day visit to Greece. ``There should be a bicommunal,
bizonal, federated state (in Cyprus) and I think it has to take
some time.''
   His remarks dashed Greek hopes he would make a gesture to
improve relations by reducing the Turkish military presence in
Cyprus.
   Greek officials say there are about 30,000 Turkish soldiers in
northern Cyprus, where the Turkish-Cypriot community declared a
breakaway republic in 1983. The Turkish government says it has
19,000 troopers in Cyprus.
   Cyprus was divided into separate Greek-Cypriot and
Turkish-Cypriot sectors when Turkey invaded the island in 1974
following a brief coup by Greek-Cypriot national guard leaders who
planned to unite the island with Greece.
   The Cyprus problem, sidelined at two earlier Greek-Turkish
summit meetings this year in Switzerland and Belgium, has emerged
as the key issue in Ozal's talks with Greek Premier Andreas
Papandreou at a seaside hotel here outside Athens.
   Papandreou has proposed a demilitarization of the island and the
establishment of a joint Greek-Cypriot and Turkish-Cypriot police
force under U.N. auspices.
   He also links a settlement on Cyprus with dropping Greek's
objection to Turkey's application to join the European Economic
Community.
   The Turkish premier said he believes the complex web of
Greek-Turkish disputes could be solved with ``courage and
creativity.''
   The two NATO allies came close to war last year over
oil-drilling rights in the Aegean sea. They also have quarrels over
Aegean airspace, the military status of some Greek islands and
Greek-owned property in the Turkish city of Istanbul.
</TEXT>
