<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhoneApology     06-15 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phone Apology,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Telephone Co. Apologizes To Elderly Left Without Service For Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A telephone company that left elderly
residents of a housing project without service for a month
apologized by serving them a catered lunch and giving them tote
bags and a rebate on their bills.
   ``There is no good excuse for what happened. We simply didn't
get the job done in time,'' Jack Briggs, assistant to New England
Telephone Co.'s vice president for Massachusetts, told residents of
Rose Manor at Monday's lunch.
   Briggs, whose apology drew a round of applause from the
residents, said the copmpany hadn't provided enough time to add
phone lines to accommodate 54 new housing units before the units
opened last month.
   While the telephone company ate crow, about 35 elderly residents
dined on creamed chicken or beef bourguignon. Briggs also handed
out promotional canvas tote bags and told the residents their
accounts would be credited for the cost of their telephone
installation fee, which ranged from $35 to $50.
   Briggs said the company had at first considered sending flowers,
but decided on the lunch and personal apology. ``People have really
been very nice,'' he said.
   Telephone service was installed on June 2, he said.
   ``It's a great relief to all of us,'' said resident Carmen Ochs.
``And the lunch is very good.''
   Another resident, Elizabeth Wood, said she was stricken with
pneumonia before the phones were installed, and had to flag down a
passing maintenance man to summon an ambulance to take her to the
hospital.
</TEXT>
