<DOCNO> AP880615-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CBSWoes     06-15 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Woes,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Affiliates Rap Lack of Network Promotion; News Videos Unveiled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fast-paced videos touting the skills of CBS
News correspondents are part of a new promotional campaign
announced Tuesday in response to affiliates' complaints of a lack
of focus at the network.
   The promos, designed as video resumes, are to begin airing on
Wednesday. One shows anchor Dan Rather covering a flood, on the
front line in Vietnam, in Moscow, India, Cuba and elsewhere.
   ``Before Dan Rather went to the front desk, he went to the front
line,'' the announcer says.
   CBS President Laurence Tisch and CBS Broadcast Group president
Gene Jankowski have admitted during an affiliates' gathering at the
Century Plaza Hotel over the past several days that poor promotion
has hurt CBS.
   During a reportedly tempestuous closed-door meeting Sunday
between CBS executives and affiliate station chiefs, the network
was repeatedly assailed for lacking a focused strategy to improve
its lagging ratings.
   ``There were more brass knuckles in there than I've seen in a
long time,'' on participant told Daily Variety after emerging from
the five-hour meeting, which last 90 minutes more than scheduled.
   ``If there is a three-to-five year plan, we don't have a sense
of it,'' said Leslie G. Arrie, vice president and general manager
of CBS affiliate WIVB of Buffalo, N.Y.
   Among the moves announced during the affiliates meeting was the
departure of Warren Spellman, the in-house chief of CBS
advertising-promotion department. He will be replaced by Michael
Mischler, the advertising and promotion vice president for King
World, the syndicator of such top game shows as ``Jeopardy'' and
``Wheel of Fortune.''
   Tisch and Jankowski said CBS had no plans to fire its outside
advertising agency of Backer, Spielvogel, Bates Inc.
   ``We didn't do a good job,'' said Tisch of the network's past
promotional efforts, but added: ``The ad agency wasn't the
problem.''
   Tisch told affiliates that the network had ``spent the
equivalent'' of $300 million annually in advertising time to
promote its programs. ``The efficiency of that expenditure could be
greatly improved,'' he said.
</TEXT>
