<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ElectionsRdp 10thLd-Writethru a0431 06-15 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elections Rdp, 10th Ld - Writethru, a0431,0856</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates figures; should stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   North Dakotans rejected a lottery for the second time in 18
months Tuesday, while Virginians chose Democrat L.F. Payne Jr. as
their newest congressman and a conservative L.L. Bean heiress lost
her bid for a U.S. House nomination from Maine.
   With 77 percent of the North Dakota vote in, the lottery was
opposed by 41,505 voters or 59 percent and favored by 28,391 voters
or 41 percent.
   ``It would seem to me (the vote is) a decisive expression of the
will of the people, and I would hope that the proponents would
accept the decision of the voters of North Dakota,'' said former
Gov. Arthur Link.
   But backers said the lottery question probably would be on the
general election ballot in November.
   Payne, developer of a ski and golf resort, defeated the
Republican candidate, former White House aide Linda Arey, in a
special election in the southside 5th District. He succeeds Rep.
W.C. ``Dan'' Daniel, a conservative Democrat who died of a heart
attack in January while serving his 10th term.
   With all the vote counted, Payne had 55,406 votes or 59 percent
to Ms. Arey's 38,086 votes or 41 percent.
   In Maine's southern 1st District, Linda Bean-Jones was edged by
senatorial aide Edward S. O'Meara for the GOP nomination to oppose
Democratic Rep. Joseph E. Brennan, a former two-term governor.
   With 96 percent of the vote counted, O'Meara had 15,313 votes or
52 percent and Bean-Jones had 14,102 votes or 48 percent.
   ``Recounts don't seem to pay off,'' Bean-Jones said. ``I'm still
going to be around. We're not going to disappear. I feel I have a
role to play in politics.''
   South Carolina also had congressional primaries, and in the only
challenge to an incumbent, three-term Democratic Rep. Robin Tallon
easily turned back retired postal worker Luther Lighty in the 6th
District. With 98 percent of the vote in, Tallon had 64,548 votes
or 89 percent and Lighty had 8,262 votes or 11 percent.
   Besides the lottery vote, North Dakotans also had the
last-in-the-nation presidential primary. But because of its late
date, no Democrats bothered to file and on the Republican side, the
ballot listed only Vice President George Bush _ who long has had
the nomination wrapped up _ and Mary Jane Rachner, a retired
teacher who says the spirits of her late mother and grandmother
told her to run for president.
   With 16 GOP delegates at stake, Bush was piling up 94 percent of
the vote.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The North Dakota lottery was defeated in November 1986, the
first time a state had failed to approve a state-run lottery.
Twenty-six states and the District of Columbia currently have
lotteries.
   Backers said a lottery would raise $7 million in new revenue for
the state, which is struggling through a depressed economy.
   ``The atmosphere this time is a lot better,'' said Gorman King
Sr., a Mandan businessman who has led the drive for a lottery.
   Link, a longtime foe of state-sanctioned gaming, found himself
joined in opposition by some of North Dakota's existing charitable
gaming operators, who feared a lottery would cut into their
business.
   Bean-Jones, granddaughter of outdoors outfitter L.L. Bean and
founder of a defunct conservative publication known as The Maine
Paper, tapped her personal wealth for her first political race,
spending $455,000 out of her own pocket. O'Meara, a longtime
district aide to Sen. William S. Cohen, spent between $60,000 and
$65,000.
   Because of a tradition of neutrality in primaries, the moderate
O'Meara was unable to draw active support from top Republicans,
although his rhetoric that at times suggested the soul of the state
party was at stake.
   Bean-Jones stressed her business background as a real estate
agent and entrepreneur, contrasting it against O'Meara's years as a
government insider.
   Last week she was quoted in the Kennebec Journal in Augusta as
calling the minimum wage an ``oppressive'' law that keeps people
from working and saying she would vote to abolish the $3.35
standard. She later issued a statement saying she thought she had
been asked about a pending bill to increase the minimum wage, but
her statement did not disclaim her comments in the story.
   In Virginia, neither Ms. Arey, 43, nor Payne, 42, was well known
in the 5th 10th District, and neither had sought elective office
previously.
   Vice President George Bush came to campaign for Ms. Arey on
Sunday in Danville, a textile and tobacco center. Payne stressed
his ties to the state's Democratic Party and received backing from
Gov. Gerald L. Baliles.
   Ms. Arey and Payne both had their party's nominations to compete
for the seat again in November, but it was considered likely that
the loser in Tuesday's election would withdraw from the race.
   In South Carolina, Tallon beat Lighty two years ago with 90
percent of the vote. Former Rep. John Jenrette, convicted in the
Abscam scandal, had considered entering the race, but decided to
sit it out.
</TEXT>
