<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Presbyterians 1stLd-Writethru a0761 06-15 0981</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presbyterians, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0761,0999</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Adopt Heavily Revised Nuclear Statement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with five grafs to update with statement adopted. Picks
up 5th graf pvs ``Conservatives within.'' Subs grafs 11-12 begng
``Following Tuesday's'' with 10 grafs of detail on later action.
Picks up 13th graf pvs ``Earlier Tuesday...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presbyterians overwhelmingly adopted a major
statement on Christian responsibilities in a nuclear age Tuesday
after lengthy revisions to mollify members who feared the church
was embracing civil disobedience.
   The General Assembly of the 3 million-member Presbyterian Church
(U.S.A.) broke into applause at the announcement of the 502-68
vote. Adoption of ``Christian Obedience in the Nuclear Age'' ended
a process that began in 1983 when congregations asked the church
how to deal with tax resisters.
   Also Tuesday, the Rev. James E. Andrews was narrowly elected to
a second four-year term as stated clerk of the General Assembly. He
defeated Harriet Nelson, a lay leader from California, 323-298.
   Andrews, 59, said he had been ``sent a message'' by the narrow
margin to heal the divisions in the denomination stemming from its
formation in the 1983 merger of the United Presbyterian Church
(U.S.A.) and the Presbyterian Church (U.S.).
   In other action, the assembly recommended a higher minimum wage
and called for a national dialogue on the status of Americans
Indians. It also began moving through suggested actions on
abortion, pornography, health costs and religious freedom in an
effort to pass resolutions before the nine day meeting ends
Wednesday.
   Conservatives within the denomination have blamed declining
membership on what they perceive to be increasingly liberal stances
by the church's bureaucracy under Andrews. There also have been
complaints that the church was not attentive enough to evangelism.
   On Saturday, a committee nominated Nelson among seven candidates
for the post, surprising many who expected the panel to nominate
two people, including Andrews. In nominating Mrs. Nelson, the Rev.
J. Randolph Taylor called Andrews ``a reminder of our divided
past'' and said the ``church needs a sense of newness.''
   Andrews, who was stated clerk of the smaller PCUS from 1973 to
1983, said he thought the vote showed the delegates believed his
``faults are correctable.'' He promised he would be ``very active
in ... bringing in various viewpoints, various factions together in
a denomination that's growing up.''
   He also said many of the church's problems reflect the
difficulty of consolidating the old Atlanta headquarters of the
PCUS and the New York headquarters of the UPCUSA in Louisville, Ky.
Most of the move is expected to be complete by the end of this year.
   Nelson, who comes from the UPCUSA, did not comment on the vote
but said prior to the election that she would do whatever the
church asked of her.
   The stated clerk is the chief constitutional officer of the
church and represents the church in ecumenical bodies, oversees the
preparation for and operation of the annual assembly and runs a
staff of 65 people with a budget of about $7 million. The post
carries a salary of $62,000 a year.
   The heavily revised document on Christian obediance in a nuclear
age lays out ways the church can deal with government resisters but
stresses that normal behavior is to obey civilian authorities. The
paper also says nuclear war is immoral, and nuclear deterrence ``as
an adequate, permanent means to national security ... is not
morally defensible.''
   Groups working on the paper reviewed the policy statement and
recommendations line-by-line, revising it throughout to indicate
obeying the government ``is normally the case.''
   However, recognizing ``God alone is Lord of the conscience,''
the paper says, ``Under certain circumstances, however,
non-cooperation with, or disobedience to, duly constituted
authorities has been deemed an appropriate Christian response.''
   The paper was revised to delete language that suggested the
church provide financial support for members who refuse to pay
taxes in protest against military spending.
   Nevertheless, the paper requests church agencies to set up a
voluntary Fund for Obedience to a Higher Authority ``for the
assistance of those who suffer financial loss or difficulty as a
result of acts of conscience.''
   The paper also was changed to include a statement that military
service can be an acceptable response to conscience.
   The adoption came after several committee members told the
assembly they had intended to vote against the paper, but had
changed their minds as the deliberations went on.
   Fountain Odom of Charlotte, N.C., a one-time unsuccessful Senate
candidate, told the assembly he first felt the paper was the
``epitome of naive simplicity.'' But Odom said the final document
``is true to the gospel, (and) allows strong, divergent emotional
views'' within the church.''
   With no discussion, the assembly adopted a lengthy discussion of
pornography that concludes it is fundamentally caused by sexism.
The recommendations reiterate the church's call for the enactment
of the Equal Rights Amendment.
   The statement also directs church officials to return to the
assembly in two years with a recommended public policy statement.
In the meantime, the church's Mission Responsibility Through
Investment Committee is to investigate the pornography industry, to
determine whether church assets are invested with companies that
profit from pornography, including telephone services.
   Earlier Tuesday, the assembly voted to set up a ``national
dialogue'' on American Indians in response to President Reagan's
comments in Moscow saying the U.S. government had ``humored''
native Americans by establishing reservations.
   The assembly also recommended a hike in the minimum wage from
$3.35 per hour to ``its historical level of 50 percent of the
average non-supervisory, non-agricultural wage and provide for
regular increases that will keep the minimum wage at an adequate
level to lift people out of poverty.''
   Congress currently is considering legislation that would raise
the minimum wage to $4.65 an hour, the first increase since 1981.
Such an increase would meet the 50 percent criterion called for by
the Presbyterians.
</TEXT>
