<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     06-15 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Saying Nyet To Grain For Vodka, Da For Livestock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle, pigs and chickens in the Soviet Union
have a record amount of grain to eat, but vodka makers are going to
have to keep on skimping, says an Agriculture Department analyst.
   ``Domestic use of grain for feed is estimated at a record 132
million (metric) tons, reflecting the continued Soviet policy of
boosting livestock production,'' according to Christian J. Foster
of the department's Economic Research Service.
   The latest USDA estimates show Soviet total grain production
this year at 215 million tons, up from 211.4 million tons in 1987
and 210.1 million tons in 1986 _ an unprecedented string of bumper
harvests for the Soviet Union.
   By far the largest use of grain in the Soviet Union _ as it is
in the United States _ is for livestock feed.
   The 132 million tons of grain expected to be used as feed in
1988-89 compares with 47 million tons for human food, 25 million
tons for seed, and only 5 million tons for industrial purposes,
which includes the manufacture of vodka. Also, an estimated 25
million tons will be lost to spoilage and other post-harvest causes.
   Industrial use of Soviet grain peaked at around 6 million tons
in the late 1970s and again as recently as 1984.
   Foster said Soviet industrial use of grain ``remains below the
1984 peak because of decreased vodka production'' as part of Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's anti-alcoholism campaign.
   ``Soviet production of vodka in 1987 declined for the third
consecutive year, down 16 percent from 1986 and 58 percent from
1980,'' Foster said in the June issue of Agricultural Outlook
magazine. ``Both wheat and rye are used in making vodka. Barley is
used in beer.''
   But Foster added that as the Soviet Union's official state
production of alcoholic beverages has dropped, illegal distilleries
have proliferated.
   ``In 1987, more than 500,000 people were fined or arrested for
the illegal production of alcohol,'' he said. ``The number of fines
and arrests is up 13 times from 1984.''
   Foster added: ``Because of public tensions over the reduction in
vodka for sale, Soviet authorities have decided to increase alcohol
production _ mainly beer, wine and brandy _ in 1988.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility says dry conditions have forced wheat and some other grain
crops to mature rapidly in most of the eastern half of the country.
   Moreover, the lack of soil moisture hampered seed germination
and growth of corn and other row crops during the week of June
6-12, the facility said Tuesday in its weekly report.
   ``Hot temperatures in the early part of the week depleted soil
moisture and caused plants to begin wilting in some areas,'' the
report said.
   Overall, winter wheat was 93 percent headed, 5 percentage points
ahead of the 5-year average for this time of the season. Harvest,
which has begun in the Delta and Southeast areas, was estimated to
be 9 percent completed, slightly ahead of normal.
   The facility, which is operated jointly by the Agriculture and
Commerce departments, reports on weather and general conditions of
crops but makes no production estimates.
   ``Spring wheat was mostly fair to poor in the northern Great
Plains,'' the report said. ``Soybeans were 90 percent seeded, 15
points above the previous week and 10 percent above average.
Dryness hampered germination and growth. Plants began wilting in
some Corn Belt states.''
   Corn planted for this year's harvest was in ``mostly fair to
good'' condition by June 12 ``but varied by areas, depending on
available moisture,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply expanded acreage of U.S. rice may
lead the way for a general increase in world rice production this
year, according to an Agriculture Department report.
   If indicated plantings are borne out and yields are in line with
past trends, U.S. rice production could be around 157 million
hundredweight this year, up 23 percent from 1987, the department's
Economic Research Service said Tuesday.
   Assuming a return to normal weather in Asia, foreign production
could rise 7 percent in 1988-89, the agency said. In that case,
global rice consumption would be expected to increase substantially
following last year's decline, the first since 1971-72.
   ``Global trade probably will rise in 1988-89 as exportable
supplies become more plentiful,'' the report said. ``While the
United States stands to benefit from the growth in consumption and
trade, competition for world markets in 1989 may intensify.''
</TEXT>
