<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Crash     06-15 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Crash,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cautious Response From Regulators Praised By Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial regulators from the Reagan
administration are finally hearing kind words for their go-slow
response to the October stock market crash after enduring two
grueling sessions before critical lawmakers.
   House Agriculture Committee Chairman Kika de la Garza, D-Texas,
on Tuesday praised the members of an administration working group
on stock market reform for their ``political courage'' in
recommending, for the most part, preservation of the status quo.
   The regulators, led by Treasury Undersecretary George D. Gould,
offer few dramatic changes in federal oversight of the nation's
stock, futures and options markets. And, they reject calls from
some members of Congress for more unified regulation of the markets.
   The group _ which includes the heads of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the Federal Reserve Board and the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission _ issued their report on May 16. In two
hearings immediately following the release _ one in the House and
one in the Senate, few in Congress had anything good to say about
it.
   Senate Banking Committee Chairman William Proxmire, D-Wis., who
wants a committee headed by the Fed chairman to coordinate
intermarket issues, denounced the panel's findings as ``pitiful.''
   House finance subcommittee Chairman Edward Markey, D-Mass., who
would transfer jurisdiction over stock index futures from the CFTC
to the SEC, said the administration took a ``horse and buggy
approach'' to regulatory reform.
   Markey's panel oversees the SEC, while Proxmire's committee has
jurisdiction over both the Fed and the SEC.
   However, members of both the House and Senate agriculture
committees, which oversee the CFTC, have staunchly defended that
agency's autonomy. When the CFTC's jurisdiction was expanded in
1982 to include stock index futures as well as traditional futures
contracts for commodities like oil and pork bellies, the
agriculture committees' jurisdictions were expanded as well.
   De la Garza characterized previous debate over market crash as
an exercise in ``fingerpointing'' and ``turf battles,'' and said,
``We want to make sure neither we nor any other congressional
committee is trying to fix something that isn't broken.
   ``I commend the members of the working group for having the
political courage to tell those who would legislate for
legislation's sake that such a course of action would be both
unnecessary and unwise,'' he said.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder, who has dissented from some of the
administration group's stands, came under sharp questioning from
several committee members.
   Unlike the other regulators, Ruder would expand his own agency's
authority to cover stock index futures. He also would temporarily
raise margins on futures contracts to dampen the wide price swings
that have characterized the market in recent months.
   Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., said CFTC regulation of futures
during the crash generated far fewer complaints than SEC regulation
of the options markets. He told Ruder ``maybe you ought to take a
look at your own shop'' before seeking wider power.
   Ruder replied that English was ``comparing apples with
oranges.'' Contracts are traded on only about 20 stock indexes,
while there are hundreds of options traded on individual stocks, he
said.
</TEXT>
