<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WelfareOverhaul     06-15 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Welfare Overhaul,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Objections Stall Welfare Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Senate convenes 9:15 a.m. EDT for other work; top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progress on a Senate welfare bill designed to
alter radically the way the nation helps its poor stalled behind
closed doors as the Reagan administration sought to mold the
measure to its liking.
   Senators and staff aides met with White House representatives
throughout the day Tuesday, trying to avert a veto fight at the end
of an arduous journey toward a welfare system oriented more toward
work than income maintenance.
   A compromise was on the table at the end of the day, but there
was no indication of whether the administration was going to go
along.
   ``It's not very clear what will satisfy the administration, and
that makes it very difficult,'' Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., said at
one point in the negotiations.
   Senators were prepared for a floor fight if the negotiations
failed.
   ``We're either going to wind it up ... or go out there and start
battling it out,'' said Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas.
   The five-year, $2.6 billion Family Security Act would require
states to set up broad new education, training and employment
programs. They would have to enroll as many welfare parents as they
could afford, concentrating at least half their resources on those
who are or are likely to be long-term recipients.
   Building on the theme of parental responsibility, the bill also
requires extensive state efforts to determine paternity and
automatic wage withholding immediately upon the awarding of child
support.
   The administration was trying to win greater state latitude in
experimenting with innovative welfare plans and a guarantee that a
certain percentage of welfare recipients would participate in the
new jobs and education program.
   The bill, written by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., is
sponsored by 64 of the 100 senators and, according to an aide, at
least two others support it.
   Before going to the White House, the Senate bill will have to be
reconciled with a similar but much more expensive House bill passed
last December. It is unclear whether either the Senate or the House
could muster the two-thirds majority needed to override a
presidential veto.
   Moynihan said Tuesday that the administration had dropped its
opposition to a new requirement that states make welfare benefits
available to poor two-parent families for at least six months in a
year. Twenty-six states already provide year-round coverage.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., said senators were discussing a
mandatory 10 percent or 15 percent participation rate for welfare
recipients in the jobs and education program, rising eventually to
25 percent. The administration wanted to go higher than that, he
said.
   The nation's governors oppose mandatory participation rates
because they say that would force them to focus on people who are
easy to help and provide services that are less than comprehensive
_ totally contrary to the bill's purported focus on those apt to
become long-term welfare clients.
   Moynihan said the governors had told him, ``Don't make us get
into faking the statistics. We want to get into the hard cases.''
</TEXT>
