<DOCNO> AP880615-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Taxes     06-15 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taxes,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Tax Legislation May Be Limited To Technical
Corrections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress seldom lets a year pass without
writing a tax bill, and this year apparently will be no different.
But budget restraints are likely to reduce the number of new tax
breaks considerably.
   However, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, says any tax bill that passes this year
is sure to include special relief for farmers from the federal tax
on diesel fuel.
   Despite a need to correct some mainly technical errors in the
big 1986 tax overhaul, there is no certainty that any tax measure
will pass this year. But Rostenkowski said he feels better about
the prospects after separate meetings Tuesday with Democrats and
Republicans on his committee.
   ``I'm encouraged that they want to write a technical-corrections
bill,'' Rostenkowski told reporters. ``We have a responsibility to
write a technical-corrections bill.''
   He said he expects the committee to start work on a bill next
week under rules requiring, because of budget constraints, that any
amendment offering tax relief to a specific group be paid for in
the same legislation by raising taxes on someone else.
   The only tax break that Rostenkowski said is sure to be in the
bill would relieve farmers from a requirement that they pay the
federal tax on diesel fuel used for off-the-road purposes and then
apply to the government at the end of the year for a rebate. More
than half the members of the House have signed a bill to wipe out
that requirement.
   The Senate Finance Committee has voted to extend the repeal to
state and local governments as well.
   The technical-corrections bill _ and whatever amendments the
House and Senate agreed to attach to it _ likely would be the only
tax legislation that has a chance of passing Congress this year.
   The tight budget and an agreement between the White House and
Congress on reducing the deficit are apt to reduce sharply the
number of amendments that are tacked onto the bill.
   Rostenkowski said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the
Finance Committee, is ``encouraged that he can hold a very
well-disciplined bill together on the floor of the Senate'' _ that
is, that he could protect it against serious amendment.
   Rostenkowski said there is considerable support on his committee
for extending for one or two years some tax breaks that have
expired or are scheduled to end later this year. These include a
tax exemption for revenue bonds that help first-time homebuyers; a
credit for increased research and development; and a tax credit
that encourages employers to hire the poor.
   Any tax bill is likely to face amendment by lawmakers who want
to reduce the tax on capital gains, which are profits from the sale
of stocks, land and other assets.
   This issue is complicated by the fact that advocates of a
reduction _ including Vice President George Bush _ contend such a
move would increase tax collections by encouraging investment.
Opponents deny it.
   Another hot issue is a ``taxpayer bill of rights,'' aimed at
curbing alleged excesses of the Internal Revenue Service. The
Finance Committee has approved a version, but Ways and Means
members have been cool to the idea.
   Efforts likely will be made to enact some kind of tax incentive
to encourage parents to save for educating their children.
   And there is considerable support for making permanent a 1987
change that relieved mutual fund shareholders from a tax on
``phantom income,'' a portion of operating expenses passed along to
shareholders as income.
   Rostenkowski said he would be happy to settle for about $2
billion worth of new tax relief in the package, the same figure
that Reagan administration officials have mentioned. But he
acknowledged he and the administration probably would not agree on
what the $2 billion would be spent for.
   He said he and his staff will draw up a list of suggestions for
raising the revenue needed to pay for any new tax relief. That list
almost certainly would include a new tax on single-premium
life-insurance policies, under which generally upper-income
investors buy large policies against which they may borrow tax-free.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
