<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     06-15 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Continues Assault On Administration Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, denouncing President
Reagan for allowing Coast Guard cuts, continued his tough talk on
drugs while his campaign stepped up the search for a running mate.
   The Massachusetts governor visited the New Bedford waterfront on
Tuesday and denounced Reagan for allowing budget cuts that forced a
55 percent reduction in Coast Guard patrols.
   Dukakis was continuing his focus on drug and crime matters
today. He had meetings set with New York law enforcement officials
and with new state police recruits.
   The governor also planned to meet with his anti-crime council
and announce the latest additions to the state's violent fugitives
list.
   After a meeting with leaders of a local drug task force aboard
the Coast Guard cutter Vigilant on Tuesday, Dukakis said the
commander told him the vessel would be out of service for at least
three months because of the cuts, part of a budget-cutting
compromise between Reagan and Congress.
   ``If this ship is tied up here for the next three or four
months, that's not waging a war,'' he said. ``How can we talk about
waging a war?''
   Dukakis said if elected, he would restore the Coast Guard
funding.
   ``Of course Congress shares the responsibility,'' he said when
asked about the compromise agreement. ``But the leadership has to
come from the White House.''
   He called Coast Guard patrols the nation's ``first line of
defense'' in the drug war.
   ``We need them. The nation needs them, and this boat is going to
be tied up here the next three months,'' Dukakis said. ``That just
doesn't make any sense.''
   Dukakis was at the southeastern Massachusetts port to salute
about 100 police officers who completed a training program for
street-level drug investigations.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis' campaign chairman, Paul Brountas, remained
in Washington to continue the search for a running mate.
   Campaign and Capitol Hill aides said Brountas would spend the
next few days in Washington consulting with party leaders and
others, including two senators often mentioned as potential running
mates _ John Glenn of Ohio and Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
   Brountas has said he will consult with Dukakis after the
meetings to trim the list of potentials and have background checks
conducted on the remaining candidates.
   Dukakis will begin a three-day campaign swing through the South
on Thursday. During that trip he expects to pick up the endorsement
of former rival Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee, also considered by
some as a potential Dukakis running mate.
</TEXT>
