<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Wins Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC offered a slate of reruns and had its
lowest overall rating of the season, but still kept top spot while
the second game of the NBA finals helped boost CBS to the No. 2
position in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   The top-rated shows for the week that ended Sunday were
``Cheers,'' ``A Different World,'' ``The Cosby Show,'' and ``Night
Court,'' all on NBC.
   ``The CBS Sunday Movie _ That Secret Sunday,'' placed fifth. The
rest of the top 10 were ``Golden Girls'' and ``L.A. Law,'' NBC;
``NBA Finals, Game Two,'' and ``60 Minutes,'' a tie for CBS; and
``The Hogan Family'' and ``NBC Monday Night Movies,'' a tie for NBC.
   ``The CBS Evening News'' regained its No. 1 position with a 9.0
rating after being edged out for six weeks by ABC's ``World News
Tonight,'' which finished with an 8.9 rating. ``NBC Nightly News''
was third with an 8.5 rating.
   NBC finished first overall with an average rating for the week
of 15.8, followed by CBS with 13.2 and ABC with 12.5.
   The cumulative rating of 41.5 is a drop from the season average
of 43.1, as longer daylight hours and outside activities lure
viewers out of their living rooms.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's estimated 88.6
million households with televisions.
   The lowest-rated prime time network shows last week were: ``Tour
of Duty,'' ``ABC Monday Night Baseball,'' ``Houston Knights,'' Days
and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' ``Ohara,'' ``Cronkite at Large,''
``High Mountain Rangers,'' ``Our House,'' ``Disney Sunday Movie,''
and ``Probe.''
</TEXT>
