<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MissingBank     06-15 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Missing Bank,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would-be Robbers Find Their Bank Isn't There Anymore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHENIX CITY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two would-be bank robbers rushed into
what used to be the First Alabama Bank, ordered employees into what
used to be a teller's station and finally realized the building now
houses an accountant's office.
   Police said the masked gunmen fled the building Monday, leaving
behind the black bag they intended to fill with cash.
   ``They got mud on their faces and no money,'' police Capt. Doug
Lee said.
   The accounting firm of Ninas Easter Co. has been in the former
bank since last month, and has had several visitors walk in
thinking the bank was still there.
   H. Russell Ninas said the two men pulled open drawers looking
for money until they realized their mistake.
   ``I kept telling them this is not a bank,'' Ninas said.
   Though the firm has its own signs in front of the building,
Ninas said he is considering adding a sign to say: ``This is not a
bank.''
   The two intruders were not captured, police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
