<DOCNO> AP880615-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     06-15 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Major Policy Shift, Ortega Lifts Price, Wage Controls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major policy shift, President
Daniel Ortega has lifted wage and price controls and instituted
massive austerity measures in an attempt to salvage the
war-battered economy.
   Speaking on nationwide television Tuesday night, he called the
crisis ``deep and serious'' and said the economy can survive only
through the adoption of a series of measures ``similar to those
taken by capitalist countries.''
   Ortega's leftist Sandinista regime had been tightening controls
over the economy since it seized power in a 1979 revolution.
   Virtually all prices have been fixed by the government, and
employers have been barred from raising salaries without government
permission.
   From now on, Ortega said, employers and workers will agree on
wages independently and prices will be regulated only by market
conditions.
   He said the government occasionally will announce nominal
guidelines on prices of some basic products to keep them from going
up too quickly. It will also remove a host of subsidies, with the
exception of public transportation and cooking oil, soap, rice and
sugar _ all of which are in short supply.
   To reduce an estimated annual inflation rate of 4,000 to 5,000
percent, Ortega said the government will restrict credit and
closely regulate interest rates to reduce the money supply and
force businessmen to reinvest profits.
   To reduce the foreign balance of payments deficit, Ortega
announced 30 percent cuts across-the-board in defense imports,
imports for farm and ranch production, and diplomatic expenditures
abroad.
   Nicaragua has a foreign debt of more than $6 billion. Soviet
bloc infusions of about $400 million a year fail to cover the
country's trade deficit. Exports this year are expected to total
$270 million while imports, excluding Soviet bloc weapons, are
totaling $700 million.
   The amount of Soviet bloc weapons imported annually has not been
made public, but Ortega has said the 6{-year war with U.S.-backed
Contra rebels has cost the country $3 billion in property damage
and lost production.
   For the past five years, more than half the national budget has
been devoted to defense spending. From 1980 to the end of 1987,
inflation caused the average urban worker's purchasing power to
drop almost 90 percent.
   Ortega made the announcement Tuesday at a meeting of 1,200
Sandinista labor leaders, managers of state-owned enterprises and
other government officials. He said that even though the Sandinista
``revolution is socialist-oriented, we cannot think of abolishing
private property.''
   He called Nicaragua's present economy ``a free market one, in a
revolutionary state that is socialist-oriented.''
   Ortega blamed the battered economy on the war and an economic
blockade imposed by the United States shortly after the Sandinistas
began establishing close economic and military ties with the Soviet
Union and its allies.
   Meanwhile, the Sandinistas are continuing to push for more
negotiations to achieve a lasting peace.
   A cease-fire, initially in force for 60 days beginning April 1
and later tacitly extended by both sides, appeared to be holding.
   Because of the war, thousands of people have fled fertile lands
for the cities and many young peasants who normally would work on
farms were forced to fight for either the Contras or the
Sandinistas.
   In April, the government began laying off 20,000 public
employees in hopes they would turn to agriculture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BaptistConvention Bjt   06-15 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baptist Convention, Bjt,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Baptists Keep Fundamentalist President And Conservative
Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fundamentalists tightened their grip
on the Southern Baptist Convention by electing another conservative
president, who said he hopes to mend the division in the nation's
largest Protestant denomination.
   The Rev. Jerry Vines, who narrowly defeated a moderate Tuesday,
said the denomination has turned rightward because of ``strong
grass-roots feelings on the part of our people.''
   Vines also told a news conference he hoped ``we can move in the
direction of healing'' the bitter conflict between conservative and
moderate Southern Baptists.
   Meanwhile, a moderate group, the Southern Baptist Alliance, said
Vines' election left them ``disenfranchised.''
   ``Diversity is rejected and dishonored,'' said a statement from
the group, headed by the Rev. John Thompson of Jackson, Miss.
``Fundamentalist, authoritarian, hierarchical and right-wing
political ideology'' now prevailed, it said.
   Vines defeated the Rev. Richard Jackson by 15,804 to 15,112. But
similarly close votes in the past have not deterred extension of
the fundamentalist platform.
   Vines, 50, is co-pastor of the First Baptist Church of
Jacksonville, Fla., while Jackson, 49, is pastor of the North
Phoenix Baptist Church in Phoenix, Ariz. Each church has about
18,000 members.
   Vines' victory represents the 10th straight year fundamentalists
have gained the powerful presidency, completing a timetable set by
their strategist in 1979 for solidifying their control over the
denomination. The president serves a one-year term, but it is
traditionally renewed a second year.
   The outcome also signaled indefinite continuation of a
right-wing theological and political agenda that has accompanied
the fundamentalist dominance.
   Because of the size and nationwide influence of the
14.7-million-member denomination, the direction set here was seen
as having an impact in broader evangelical circles.
   Asked why Southern Baptist positions on social and political
issues have come to match those of the religious right, Vines cited
``grass-roots feelings'' and said members ``reflect the general
mood, the conservative directions of this time.''
   Jackson wryly discounted that explanation, saying the ``grass
roots are often quoted, but you don't hear them talking much.''
   ``I feel there is manipulation,'' he said. ``It would have been
unthinkable 20 years ago that a small group could get together and
work out plans'' for taking control of the denomination.
   The key architects of that plan, Judge Paul Pressler of Houston
and the Rev. Paige Patterson of Dallas, determined that by
successively winning the presidency, conservatives could gradually
pack ruling boards of denominational agencies and seminaries
through the appointive power of the office.
   The fundamentalist victories have been achieved under the banner
of biblical ``inerrancy'' _ that the Bible is without error,
scientically, historically and religiously.
   But they have been accompanied by conservative positions on
political and social issues, such as unsuccessfully supporting
Judge Robert Bork for the U.S. Supreme Court, and favoring capital
punishment, prayer in public schools and aid to private schools.
   Vines said he hoped the denomination would not lose members over
the conflict. ``I want to include, not exclude,'' he said.
   Asked if he would seek only like-minded people as trustees of
church institutions and agencies, he said they must be within
approved ``parameters,'' that is, biblical ``inerrantists.''
   Several seminary and other church staff members have been
pressured from their jobs by new screening processes instituted by
the fundamentalists. Among the questions asked church employees is
whether they believe Adam and Eve were real people and that
biblical miracles actually occurred.
   Vines said the political ramifications of the fundamentalist
upsurge were ``spinoffs'' from the theological concerns.
   Jackson said the split ``obviously isn't over theology,'' but
over different styles of leadership, since he accepts the Bible's
infallibilty, but he respects those holding other views.
   ``I believe we'll stay together, may God deliver us,'' he said.
``I don't want anybody to panic.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HongKong-Vietnam     06-15 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong-Vietnam,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong to End Policy of Accepting All Boat People As Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will no longer grant asylum to
all Vietnamese in an effort to stem the growing influx of boat
people, a Hong Kong official said today.
   Effective Thursday, the government will screen all Vietnamese
boat people entering the British colony's waters to determine if
they are political refugees or economic migrants, said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Boat people who left their homeland for economic reasons will be
housed in a prison-like camp on an outlying island of Hong Kong
pending an agreement with Vietnam on repatriation, the official
said.
   Chief Secretary Sir David Ford planned to announce the change of
policy today before the Legislative Council, Hong Kong's lawmaking
body.
   Hong Kong long has assumed all arriving boat people are refugees
eligible for temporary asylum. They are housed in refugee camps
pending resettlement in a third country such as the United States
or Canada.
   But local officials say many left Vietnam for economic reasons,
not to escape political persecution, and finding resettlement homes
for them has become increasingly difficult.
   About 7,800 boat people have braved the treacherous trip from
Vietnam to Hong Kong this year through Tuesday, or 12 times the
number who arrived during the corresponding period last year,
government statistics show. The number of boat people has soared to
about 16,200.
   Only 1,200 boat people left Hong Kong camps for resettlement
this year through Tuesday, up slightly from the corresponding
period last year.
   The boat people already in the colony will not be affected by
the new policy, the government official said.
   Other non-communist Southeast Asian governments recently have
changed their policy toward accepting Vietnamese boat people.
   Thailand earlier this year pushed back to sea Vietnamese boats
attempting to land and several deaths were reported. Bangkok backed
off after sharp international criticism and reopened its doors, but
insisted the new arrivals would not be eligible for resettlement.
   Malaysia announced in April it would begin turning away boat
people at some unspecified future date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
