<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-15 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Rules IRA Member Should be Deported to UK, Not Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III has ruled
that a member of the Irish Republican Army convicted of murder
should be deported to the United Kingdom, overturning a decision by
the Board of Immigration Appeals.
   Meese said Tuesday that deporting Joseph Patrick Thomas Doherty
to Ireland instead would be against U.S. interests.
   Doherty was convicted in the United Kingdom in 1981 of murder in
the ambush of a British army convoy in which a captain was killed.
   Doherty escaped from a prison in Belfast, Northern Ireland,
before sentencing, came to the United States in 1982 and has been
held in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York City since
1983 on charges he illegally entered the country using a false
passport.
   Michael Armacost, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
wrote the attorney general that a decision to deport Doherty to
Ireland could undermine Great Britain's ``confidence in the ability
of the United States to cooperate in counter-terrorism efforts.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Candidates McGovern, Goldwater Urge Israel To Deal With</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former presidential candidates in opposing
parties and usually at opposite ends of the political spectrum are
urging Israel to deal directly with Palestinians in seeking a
Middle East peace.
   Barry Goldwater and George McGovern joined in saying Israel
should recognize the ``national legitimacy'' of Arab Palestinians
and turn over territory to them in exchange for peace.
   McGovern, the losing Democratic standard bearer in 1972, and
Goldwater, the losing Republican in 1964, signed a statement
endorsing the peace proposal along with former European government
heads Garrett Fitzgerald of Ireland, Anker Jorgensen of Denmark and
Bruno Kreisky of Austria.
   Their proposal differs from the plan unsuccessfully pursued by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz and strongly implies _ but does
not specifically recommend _ creation of a Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>3-Wheeled All-Terrain Vehicles Should Be Illegal, Senators Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is not doing enough to protect
the public from all-terrain vehicles, according to a pair of
senators who have introduced legislation to require the Consumer
Product Safety to ban the sale of three-wheeled models.
   Sens. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn.,
proposed the legislation, which would also require the CPSC to
establish a procedure for owners to obtain refunds.
   The commission ``has not done an adequate job in protecting the
consumer from the inherent risks and dangers associated with
ATVs,'' D'Amato said at a press conference on Tuesday. ``It is time
for Congress to force their hand in this matter.''
   Gore said ATVs have been linked to nearly 1,000 deaths and more
than 350,000 injuries requiring medical treatment since 1982.
   Of the 2.5 million ATVs now in use, about two-thirds are
three-wheeled models.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Safety Agency Renews Trimmer Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission says
500,000 Black & Decker weed trimmers that could pose an
electrocution hazard remain in consumer hands, despite an earlier
recall.
   The safety agency issued a new warning Tuesday because of fewer
trimmers were returned under the recall than expected.
   Involved are Black & Decker Model 82209 and Model 82210
bump-feed string trimmers used on grass and weeds.
   Because of an error in wiring, the electrical wires in some of
the trimmers could be cut by the handle tube, causing a potential
for electrical shock, the agency said. Owners should stop using the
trimmers immediately and take them to a Black & Decker service
center for repair or replacement.
   People needing more information can contact Black & Decker at
1-800-533-4395 or the Safety Commission at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
