<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Fires     06-15 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Fires,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Meetings Held To Fight Arsonists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Uprising Trauma, Bjt
^By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The burning of woodlands, apparently the latest
tactic of the Palestinian uprising, has spurred an outcry among
Israeli Jews whose founding fathers prided themselves on making the
deserts bloom.
   Israelis gathered in emergency meetings across the country
Tuesday to develop ways to fight the fires in the nation's scarce
forests.
   In one of three meetings on the fire threat, police and army
officers, security agents and members of the Jewish National Fund
agreed to set up three regional centers to coordinate information
on fires.
   In the Galilee village of Kfar Tabor, Israeli Arab and Jewish
village leaders agreed to create volunteer civil guards to carry
out patrols.
   But they dismissed a proposal for joint patrols, saying that the
current tensions between Jews and Arabs could make such patrols
counterproductive.
   Since May, 28,700 acres of woodland and pasture have been
destroyed by fire, said Lenny Labensohn, a spokesman for the Jewish
National Fund, which is responsible for afforestation and land
reclamation in Israel.
   Labensohn's figure is six times the average acreage normally
lost to fire in a year.
   Labensohn and police officials say a ``significant number'' of
the fires have been set by Palestinians who oppose Israel's
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Ten Palestinians have been arrested on suspicion of setting
fires. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has called for mandatory
15-year sentences for anyone convicted of arson, and his suggestion
has been taken up by others.
   ``It is not possible to know for sure how many fires are the
work of arsonists,'' Labensohn said. ``But when we see trees
burning that we planted with our own sweat and blood, it's very
hard to take. It just causes more damage to Jewish-Arab relations.''
   Early Jewish pioneers to Israel, often acting with funds
contributed from the United States and other countries, worked to
fill swamplands and plant trees on marginal land.
   They dubbed the border between Israel and the West Bank in 1948
the ``green line,'' in part to emphasize the extent to which the
land had been cultivated.
   Jews living outside Israel planted trees in memory of deceased
relatives or Holocaust victims. American donations have planted 20
million trees in Israeli national parks, more than 10 percent of
the country's trees.
   The Israeli army has sometimes uprooted trees and olive groves
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip from which Palestinians
were suspected of throwing firebombs or stones at Israelis.
   On June 10, Israeli troops broke up a tree-planting ceremony by
left-wing Israelis in the West Bank village of Beita, scene of the
April 6 clash between the villagers and teen-age Israeli hikers in
which a Jewish girl was killed.
   The Israelis were planting trees to protest the army's uprooting
of orchards and demolition of 14 Arab houses as punishment for the
clash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
