<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0824 06-15 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0824,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of `Long Day's Journey Into Night' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs with other critics; No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defeated, drug-addled Mary Tyrone has always
been the unhappy heart of ``Long Day's Journey into Night,'' Eugene
O'Neill's harrowing tale of a family trying to come to terms with
its tortured past.
   That aspect of the play never has been made clearer than in the
compelling revival of O'Neill's masterpiece which opened Tuesday at
Broadway's Neil Simon Theater as part of the First New York
International Festival of the Arts.
   The production, directed by Jose Quintero, stars a subdued but
effective Jason Robards as James Tyrone and a haunting Colleen
Dewhurst as his doomed wife, Mary. While Robards is fine as the
parsimonious old matinee idol, it is Dewhurst who holds the play
together and mesmerizes the audience.
   In his introduction to ``Long Day's Journey into Night,''
O'Neill calls the autobiographical drama ``a play of old sorrow.''
Dewhurst personifies that sadness. You can see it the moment she
walks on stage. The woman's face is masked in a tight smile as she
tries to get through what would appear to be just another hot day
at the Tyrone summer cottage in New London, Conn.
   The outward normality of events is shattered by the
unintentional but inevitable return by father, mother and two sons
to events long past. The death of Mary's son Eugene, her addiction
to morphine and the neglect of her youngest child Edmund plunge the
family into a day and night-long battle of recriminations and
halting, painful explanations.
   Dewhurst's performance is never showy. It exudes a patrician
reserve, a sense of correctness that hints at Mary's proper
upbringing in a strict Catholic household. This propriety makes her
final breakdown all the more poignant. She turns into a lady trying
to hold on to her last bit of dignity as the real world slips away.
   Robards has tamed the blarney that sometimes obscures Tyrone's
soul. He exhibits little of the hamminess that Jack Lemmon brought
to the part in the revival New York saw two years ago.
   He takes his time getting into character, bringing Tyrone slowly
into focus. The portrait crystallizes in the play's final act
during the father's long, rambling explanation of his
poverty-stricken youth when he ``learned to be a miser.'' It is a
beautiful, quiet moment, one of the most moving in Quintero's
production.
   The revival is at its heart-breaking best during these
revelations of the past. In them, O'Neill doesn't exonerate his
characters, but instead offers the audience some explanation for
their actions as flawed human beings.
   The understanding also comes through in this production's
portrayals of the two sons. A ruddy-faced Jamey Sheridan captures
the frustration of the cynical older son, drawn like his father to
drink and bitter about the certainty that his life will not amount
to much. Campbell Scott is equally impressive as the sickly Edmund,
torn between love and rage for his parents.
   Jane Macfie delivers an effective cameo as the Irish maid
Cathleen. She resists the temptation to turn the woman into the
usual cartoon stereotype.
   The evocative living room designed by Ben Edwards resembles the
real O'Neill summer home with a panoramic view of Long Island Sound
that darkens as the day turns into a long night.
   What makes ``Long Day's Journey into Night'' special is the
completeness of its characters, real people who are painted with
unflinching honesty. Quintero has made sure that completeness comes
through on stage and with the assistance of an exceptional group of
actors, particularly Dewhurst, turned the evening into a memorable
journey.
   In other reviews:
   Clive Barnes of the New York Post called the production
``O'Neill as O'Neill should be. ... Here is American classic
theater at its greatest, and dealing with an indisputable American
classic.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel wrote, ``Strikingly mounted,
the play moves naturally and effortlessly. ... A work that can seem
labored and elephantine here soars and dips, like a lark wounded
but unable to stop singing.''
   Frank Rich of The New York Times called the production
``rewarding, if imperfect. ... But the evening is never less than
essential theatergoing.''
   He adds, ``One cannot assume that there will be another chance
to watch these three great theater artists (Quintero, Robards and
Dewhurst) explore the writer who has been their consuming passion
for virtually their entire professional careers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
