<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Market,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks At New Highs, Dollar Surges on U.S. Trade Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices reached a new high on the Tokyo stock
market Wednesday, and the U.S. dollar soared against the Japanese
yen on news of better-than-expected U.S. trade figures.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues finished a day
of brisk trading at a record 28,093.52 points, up 31.72 points or
0.11 percent from Tuesday's close.
   The Nikkei index, the Tokyo market's main barometer, reached its
previous high last Thursday, when it closed at 28,072.02.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the U.S. dollar opened at
126.36 yen and ranged between 126.10 and 126.55 yen before closing
at 126.32, up 1.27 yen from Tuesday's finish.
   It was the dollar's highest closing figure since April 13, when
it finished at 126.45.
   ``The largest factor behind the dollar's rise was the
improvement in the U.S. trade deficit in April,'' said an exchange
dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the U.S.
trade deficit narrowed in April to $9.89 billion, its lowest level
since December 1984.
   ``U.S. trade figures always affect world financial markets,
including that in Tokyo,'' said another exchange dealer.
</TEXT>
