<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Awad-Conversion     06-15 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Awad-Conversion,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab-American Vows To Return To Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab-American expelled from Israel amid
charges of sedition reiterated his intention to convert to Judaism
to gain re-entry to his homeland, but liberal rabbis said political
motivations are not enough reason for conversion.
   Mubarak Awad, who advocates non-violent Palestinian resistance
to the Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, said
Tuesday he would convert from Christianity to Judaism and seek
re-entry under Israel's Law of the Return ``if everything (else)
failed.''
   Awad is a U.S. citizen who was born in Jerusalem, where he has a
home. He was deported Monday by Israel, which accused him of
playing a key role in the Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories.
   ``I am here, but not by choice,'' he said at a news conference
arranged by the National Council of Churches. ``I was deported just
because I am a Christian. If I were a Jew, I would not be
deported.''
   Under the Law of the Return, Jews may claim Israeli citizenship.
But the privilege is not absolute; gangster Meyer Lansky, for
example, sought Israeli citizenship in 1970 but was forced to leave
two years later after allegations of his continued involvement in
organized crime.
   Pressed on the subject of conversion, which he mentioned during
his deportation battle, Awad said, ``I'll tell (a rabbi) frankly
... it's not my belief (that spurred the request). It's a political
statement that I'm persecuted because I'm a Christian.''
   Leaders of Reform Judaism on Tuesday issued a letter to 1,500
rabbis of the movement in the United States and Canada urging them
not to accommodate Awad should he seek conversion.
   ``No one can rule out the possibility of a sincere conversion in
anybody's case, but this must be proved at the end of a long period
of instruction,'' said the letter. ``Surely we need not remind you
that extraneous motivations, political motivations, are not
sufficient reason.''
   Awad said he would first pursue other avenues, including an
appeal to international public opinion. He said he planned meetings
with officials at the United Nations and in Washington, Europe, and
the Soviet Union.
   He defended his support of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, but said he did not back all the organization's
actions. ``I condemn violence from the PLO, from Israelis, from
everybody,'' he said.
   Awad said he advocated the cutting of electrical wires to
prevent Israeli settlements from being established in Arab areas,
but not in cases where settlements already existed. He also said he
opposed stone throwing, setting forest fires and other violent
tactics some Palestinians have used.
   Some tactics he has long advocated, such as tax boycotts and
commercial strikes, were adopted by leaders of the uprising in the
territories Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Awad, the 21st Arab expelled by Israel since the uprising began
Dec. 8, was deported on the ground that his three-month tourist
visa, issued when he entered Israel in August, had expired. The
Israelis refused to extend the visa, and the Israeli Supreme Court
last week rejected Awad's appeal to remain.
   Awad lived in the United States for 13 years before returning to
Jerusalem in 1983, and still owns a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio. He is
the founder of the Palestinian Center for the Study of Non-Violence
in Jerusalem. His wife, Nancy Nye, an American, said she soon will
return to Jerusalem to resume her job as principal of a Quaker
school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
