<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Escort Body of Marcos' Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 8,000 people escorted the body
of Ferdinand Marcos' mother, dead more than 40 days, to the
outskirts of Manila today in a show of support for the exiled
former president.
   It was the kickoff for a two-day motorcade to Marcos' home
province of Ilocos Norte, where Josefa Edralin-Marcos is to be
buried at an undetermined date.
   Thousands of onlookers lined an eight-mile route as the Marcos
loyalists marched from Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' suburban home to a
highway on the border of the capital. Many of the onlookers cheered
the marchers on, some heckled them, but most just watched silently.
   Dozens of cars and other vehicles that joined the cortege honked
their horns as marchers, some holding red balloons, rhythmically
blew whistles. Close to the hearse, a woman recited the Rosary
through a loudspeaker mounted on a jeep, but another loudspeaker
blaring a nationalist song drowned her out.
   The marchers shouted slogans describing President Cory Aquino as
``stupid and corrupt.'' Mrs. Aquino, citing security reasons, has
refused to allow Marcos to return to the country to attend the
funeral of his mother, who died May 4 at the age of 95.
   Marcos has lived in Honolulu since he fled the country during
the February 1986 civilian-military revolt that ended his 20-year
rule and swept Mrs. Aquino to power. Mrs. Aquino is on a six-day
trip to Switzerland and Italy.
   The loyalists distributed mimeographed statements eulogizing
Mrs. Edralin-Marcos as a ``great mother ... who served as the light
and teacher of her great son, Ferdinand Marcos.''
   It accused Mrs. Aquino of destroying Philippine tradition and
violating the commandment to love one's parents by not allowing
Marcos to return.
</TEXT>
