<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Soldier'sRemains     06-15 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier's Remains,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Soldier's Remains Return To U.S. From Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of an Air Force officer killed in
Vietnam 22 years ago said she would remove the MIA bracelet with
her son's name but wear one with the name of another missing
serviceman now that his remains are home.
   The family of Lt. Col. Vincent Chiarello tearfully accepted his
remains at Philadelphia International Airport on Tuesday and vowed
to continue to work for other families with relatives missing in
Vietnam.
   Anne Chiarello, the officer's mother, broke down during a
service performed by an honor guard. Later, during a news
conference, she said she will take off the MIA bracelet engraved
with her son's name that she has worn since 1978.
   ``I will be happy to wear one for another MIA until he comes
home,'' she said.
   ``I will stay in the National League until the very end,'' Mrs.
Chiarello said, referring to the organization working for
information about all Americans missing in Vietnam.
   ``The 22-year nightmare is over,'' said Joseph Chiarello,
brother of the Air Force intelligence officer.
   Chiarello's plane was shot down near the Laotian border over
North Vietnam on July 29, 1966, according to his sister Joanne
Cornell.
   About four months ago, the Air Force told the family the
Vietnamese government was returning the remains of 20 American
soldiers, including Chiarello's.
   However, on March 3, the remains of only 17 soldiers were
returned along with identification cards for Chiarello and two
others.
   Tom Engkilterra, a coordinator with the National League, said at
the time the remains returned to the United States, only four or
five soldiers had been identified.
   Identification of Chiarello finally came through an exhaustive
study of the remains and comparisons with dental, military and
family records.
   ``The findings were so definite,'' said Mrs. Cornell. ``We felt
we must accept this. We feel beyond a shadow of a doubt these are
my brother's remains.''
   Chiarello's relatives said they will try to help other families
with missing loved ones.
   ``We beseech the Vietnamese government ... to act expeditiously
on behalf of all these families,'' Joseph Chiarello said.
   Engkilterra said there were ``2,400 stories out there that need
to be told so this doesn't become a one-day event.''
   When the family learned that Vincent's remains were to be
returned, they received a tremendous amount of ``loving concern and
support'' from relatives and friends, including Vincent's friends
from college, Mrs. Cornell said.
   ``The outpouring has been so warm and wonderful,'' she said.
   About the time the family learned the remains would be returned,
the Vietnamese released findings of an investigation that concluded
the plane exploded in the air and the bodies fell to the ground
between two villages, Phuc San and Dong Bang, about 20 miles
southwest of Hanoi.
   The family will attend a Mass at Saint Bede's Catholic Church in
suburban Holland on Saturday. Later that day, the officer will be
buried at the Newtown Cemetery in Newtown.
</TEXT>
