<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-15 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Record High, Dollar Up With U.S. Trade Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News of an improvement in the U.S. trade deficit
boosted the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index to a new high in brisk
trading today and strengthened the U.S. dollar against the Japanese
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at a
record 28,093.52 points, up 31.72 or 0.11 percent from Tuesday's
close. The Nikkei index, the market's main barometer, reached its
previous high last Thursday when it closed at 28,072.02.
   Volume on the exchange was a heavy 2.6 billion shares, up
sharply from Tuesday's volume of 930 million.
   ``The latest U.S. trade report promped wide-ranging buying
interest,'' said an official at Nomura Securities Co., Japan's
largest securities company.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the trade
deficit narrowed in April to $9.89 billion, its lowest level since
December 1984.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at
126.36 yen and ranged between 126.10 and 126.55 yen before closing
at 126.32, up 1.27 yen from Tuesday's finish. It was the dollar's
highest closing figure since April 13, when it finished at 126.45.
   A total of $7.729 billion changed hands today, more than three
times the volume Tuesday.
   ``The largest factor behind the dollar's rise was the
improvement in the U.S. trade deficit in April,'' said an exchange
dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
