<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland     06-15 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Bank President Promoted to Politburo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party promoted to the ruling
Politburo the national bank president, a strong advocate of
economic reform who opposes the price increases that fueled last
month's widespread labor unrest.
   In the second shake-up in six months, a Central Committee
meeting on Tuesday also gave key posts to two Politburo members who
have been mentioned as possible successors to Polish leader Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   The strikes between April 25 and May 10 comprised the country's
worst labor unrest in six years. Jaruzelski, the first party
secretary, has acknowledged that efforts to reform the foundering
economy have been disappointing.
   Wladyslaw Baka, president of the National Bank of Poland, was
elected to the 15-member Politburo in a secret ballot and elected a
member and a secretary of the 230-member Central Committee, which
the Politburo oversees.
   Baka favors economic reform but is known to have spoken against
the across-the-board price increases that were adopted as part of
the reform package.
   Mieczyslaw Rakowski and Foreign Minister Marian Orzechowski, two
Politburo members who could succeed Jaruzelski if he decides to
step down, were given added posts as Central Committee secretaries.
   Rakowski was elected to the Politburo during the last leadership
shake-up on Dec. 15. The former newspaper editor will be in charge
of party propaganda and the media, according to an official source.
   Orzechowski, foreign minister since 1985, has said the adverse
attention given strikes in Poland was undermining the country's
position in the world. He was given charge of the Central
Committee's ideological commission, replacing Henryk Bednarski, who
resigned.
   He was also given the chairmanship of a commission to prepare a
party conference on ideology, tentatively expected early next year.
   Two Politburo members resigned: Marian Wozniak, who had been in
charge of economic policy, and Wlodzimier Mokrzyszczak, who had
been in charge of internal party discipline.
   Stanislaw Ciosek resigned as a Central Committee secretary but
was named an alternate non-voting member of the Politburo. Another
non-voting Politburo member, Stanislaw Bejger, the Gdansk party
chief, resigned. Two previous Central Committee secretaries also
resigned, Jozef Baryla and Tadeusz Porebski.
   Party spokesman Jerzy Majka said at a news conference after the
plenum that the Central Committee urged consultation with groups
that consider themselves independent or opposition.
   But Majka said there could be no dialogue with those he said
want to worsen the domestic situation or are paid by a foreign
power, a reference to the banned trade union Solidarity.
   Jaruzelski said economic reform should be speeded up and that
delays and negligence within the party were partly to blame for the
slow pace of reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
