<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     06-15 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memo: Meese Friend Told Wedtech Officials to Clam Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close friend of Attorney General Edwin Meese
III warned Wedtech officials not to boast about the company's
Washington connections, according to a letter read at Rep. Mario
Biaggi's racketeering trial.
   ``The less said about our `clout,' the better,'' said the June
1, 1985, memo from E. Robert Wallach. It was produced Tuesday by
defense attorney Dominic Amorosa, who then cross-examined
ex-Wedtech president Anthony Guariglia about its significance.
   ``The clout he's talking about included Misters Meese, Nofziger,
and Bragg, didn't it?'' asked Amorosa, referring to ex-White House
adviser Lyn Nofziger and Nofziger's consulting partner Mark Bragg.
   ``Yes,'' Guariglia replied. The memo also made mention of the
``special treatment'' Wedtech, a defense contractor, had received
from government agencies, Guariglia said.
   Earlier, Guariglia had testified that in its efforts to
guarantee lucrative government contracts, Wedtech had attempted to
lobby National Security Adviser Robert McFarlane through Wallach.
   The assertions were later denied by McFarlane's attorney.
   ``The person in question is not Robert McFarlane. At no time,
directly or indirectly, was Mr. McFarlane contacted by the Wedtech
company or any of its representatives on Wedtech's behalf,'' said
McFarlane attorney Peter Morgan.
   Amorosa, representing Biaggi's son and co-defendant, Richard,
introduced the memo and several other letters from Wallach during a
contentious cross-examination of Guariglia.
   Wallach is under indictment on federal racketeering charges that
say he took payoffs from Wedtech officials to influence Meese and
other public officials.
   Guariglia and other company officials have testified they paid
$800,000 to Wallach to influence the attorney general. They have
said Wallach told them he got the attorney general to intercede on
the company's behalf for a series of contracts worth $143 million
to build pontoons: floating, portable docks.
   Amorosa, trying to link Wedtech's contracts to the efforts of
Wallach rather than the defendants, quizzed Guariglia about their
relationship _ focusing on an illegal $150,000 payoff for his
lobbying that was funneled through a third party.
   ``He knew you were a crook, and you knew he was a crook,
right?'' the lawyer asked.
   Guariglia paused before answering in a loud voice, ``Yes.''
   The witness is the last of four ex-Wedtech officials who have
pleaded guilty to corruption charges to testify at the trial in
exchange for leniency. Guariglia, 37, has said he faces up to 10
years in prison despite his plea in the case involving the
now-bankrupt company.
   During the cross-examination, Amorosa and Assistant U.S.
Attorney Mary T. Shannon squared off several times in the
sweltering courtroom, with the prosecutor at one point attributing
her anger to the heat.
   Biaggi, his son and the others _ Wedtech founder John Mariotta,
ex-Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon, attorney Bernard Ehrlich,
Small Business Administration Regional Administrator Peter Neglia
and Neglia friend Ronald Betsoare _ are accused of converting
Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise for the payment of bribes to
obtain no-bid government contracts.
</TEXT>
