<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Turkey     06-15 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Turkey,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek, Turkish Leaders Agree to Meet Again on Cyprus, Aegean
Conflicts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOULIAGMENI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of Greece and Turkey
failed to resolve conflicts over Cyprus and the Aegean Sea, but
they agreed to meet again to discuss these and other longstanding
disputes.
   Premier Turgut Ozal planned to return to Turkey today after two
days of private talks with Greek Premier Andreas Papandreou at a
heavily guarded seaside hotel.
   They planned to resume their dialogue in the Turkish capital of
Ankara later this year, officials said. No date was set for the
meeting, but Turkish officials said it probably will be held in
October.
   ``Today's climate was positive ... filled with goodwill. All
these types of meetings are a step forward,'' said Greek spokesman
Yiannis Roubatis. Turkish Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz said:
``It's useful to continue the dialogue.''
   But a $20 million Greek-Turkish banking agreement due to be
signed on Tuesday was delayed at the last minute, apparently
because of Greek reluctance to be seen making any concessions.
   The agreement for a joint venture between Greece's state-owned
Ionian Bank and Turkey's Housing Bank would have been the first
substantive product of improved Greek-Turkish relations.
   Papandreou and Ozal launched the negotiations at a meeting in
January at the Swiss ski resort of Davos.
   Ten months earlier, Greece and Turkey had come close to war over
oil-drilling rights in the Aegean seabed.
   They also have longstanding disputes over Aegean airspace, the
military status of some Greek islands and Greek-owned property in
the Turkish city of Istanbul.
   Ozal said he didn't intend to pull any of the 30,000 Turkish
troops out of the northern sector of the divided Mediterranean
island of Cyprus. He also stuck to his demand for a two-zone
federated state on Cyprus.
   Papandreou wants the Turkish troops out of Cyprus before peace
talks begin. He also links a Cyprus settlement with lifting a Greek
veto on Turkey's application to join the European Economic
Community.
   Cyprus has been divided into northern Turkish Cypriot and
southern Greek Cypriot sectors since Turkish troops invaded in 1974
after an Athens-led coup aimed at uniting the island with Greece.
   Ozal took a more conciliatory approach to the issue of
Greek-owned assets in Istanbul. He cited a new Turkish government
decree that enables Greek citizens to make investments in Turkey
using funds raised from selling their Istanbul property.
   Many Greeks who formerly lived in Istanbul want to sell their
assets, but they were discouraged by a Turkish ruling that such
funds must remain in blocked bank accounts.
   More than 200,000 Istanbul Greeks left the city when
Greek-Turkish relations deteriorated in the 1950s and 1960s.
</TEXT>
