<DOCNO> AP880615-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     06-15 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Rejecting Military Training Battle Riot Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students
protesting compulsory military training fought riot police with
firebombs and rocks today after troopers moved in to break up the
protest.
   Fierce fighting erupted at Chungang University in Seoul when
lines of riot police in green combat fatigues and black visored
helmets marched onto the campus firing volleys of tear gas.
   Masked students hurled firebombs that exploded in showers of
flaming gasoline and pelted police with rocks and broken bricks.
Troopers behind riot shields fired choking tear gas and hurled
rocks back at the radicals.
   ``Boycott military training'' and ``Yankee go home,'' students
yelled as they battled police for several hours.
   Several students were hit by tear gas shells, but no serious
injuries were reported.
   Radical students also clashed with riot police at a college in
the central city of Taejon to protest a government ban on a radical
march to the communist North Korean border last week. Police drove
students off with tear gas.
   About 10 radical students staged a dawn attack today with
firebombs on an office of the governing Democratic Justice Party in
Seoul, police said. The students hurled firebombs at the
fifth-floor office from the street, but missed.
   South Korea has been hit during the past month by a wave of
violent protests by radical students who demand the overthrow of
the government and reunification of the divided Korean peninsula.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority on college campuses,
have failed to attract public support.
   About 1,000 radical students from five Seoul colleges gathered
at Chungang today to demand an end to compulsory military training
for college students. They were preparing to march into the street
when police moved onto the campus to block the radicals.
   Radical leaders denounced the government of President Roh
Tae-woo and the United States and said military training was
``preparation of machinery for the Yankees.''
   Student speakers at a rally before the clash demanded an end to
military training and the expulsion of the 42,000 U.S. troops based
in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   All male college students in South Korea are required to undergo
weekly military training along with periodic instruction sessions
at military barracks. Radicals say the training is part of a
military conspiracy to create tension with the north.
   Radical students want immediate reunification of the Korean
peninsula, divided since the end of World War II. They contend that
the United States enforces partition to rule the south as a colony.
   Major street clashes erupted in Seoul last Friday when riot
police blocked thousands of radical students trying to march to the
border for talks with North Korean students on reunifying the
peninsula.
   The two Koreas are bitter enemies. The north invaded the south
in 1950 to start the Korean War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
