<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CigaretteSuit     06-15 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Suit,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco Suit Verdict Reverberates throughout Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lead attorney in a landmark cigarette
liability suit said his partial victory leaves tobacco companies
open to racketeering charges, but industry lawyers gleaned another
message: If you puff, you pay.
   Those were two of the reactions Tuesday as the verdict in the
case of Antonio Cipollone, who on Monday won the first judgment
against a tobacco company in 30 years, continued to reverberate
throughout the industry.
   Tobacco companies went on the offensive, holding a news
conference to attack the fairness of the judge in the 4{-month
case. Meanwhile, stock prices dipped even though analysts played
down long-term effects of the verdict.
   In a separate decision Tuesday, a federal appeals court rejected
a couple's $107 million claim against R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.,
ruling that warning labels on cigarette packages are sufficient to
inform people about the dangers of smoking.
   Monday's landmark verdict found that Liggett Group Inc. failed
to warn the public about smoking's dangers before labels were
required in 1966 and granted damages for violating a promise, or
``express warranty,'' in advertisements that cigarettes were safe.
   Plaintiffs, who were awarded $400,000, were able to claim at
least a partial victory for the first time in 30 years of cigarette
liability lawsuits.
   However, the U.S. District Court jury in Newark cleared Liggett
and two other cigarette-makers, Lorillard Inc. and Philip Morris
Inc., of conspiring to mislead the public about the risks of
smoking.
   No punitive damages were awarded in the case brought by
Cipollone and his wife, Rose, who was 58 when she died of lung
cancer in 1984 after smoking cigarettes made by the three companies
for 40 years.
   The jury mostly blamed Mrs. Cipollone for contracting her
disease.
   Even so, Marc Z. Edell, the lead attorney for Cipollone, said
Tuesday the case suggested how to improve the chances of winning a
judgment on a broader, more damaging conspiracy charge: charging
the companies with a civil claim under the Racketeer-Influenced
Corrupt Organization statute.
   The federal statute says a company can be found liable if it is
found to be an enterprise engaged in a pattern of racketeering
activity.
   A jury that focused more on a pattern of acts would lessen the
plaintiff's burden to show the smoker's own behavior contributed to
the disease, Edell told a news conference.
   In a separate news conference in New York, tobacco company
lawyers said they regarded the verdict as fundamentally a victory
because it reinforced the industry's defense _ that Mrs. Cipollone
made a decision to smoke knowing the risks.
   ``The jury returned a resounding message that individuals who
make informed choices have responsibility for those choices,'' said
Philip Morris' general counsel, Murray Bring.
   Tobacco company lawyers also attacked the fairness of Judge H.
Lee Sarokin and released a detailed rebuttal of previously secret
industry documents introduced by anti-smoking forces during the
trial.
   ``It is clear from any person looking at his rulings that they
were preferential and unwarranted'' and against the rules of
procedure, Stevens said of the judge. ``We could not have had a
more extreme adversary.''
   Sarokin's law clerk said the judge would not comment because the
case was still pending before him.
   Edell said the companies claimed victory for public relations
reasons, to encourage industry investors and discourage other
lawyers from pursuing such cases.
   Liggett attorneys have promised an appeal of the damages award.
   Tobacco stocks dropped Tuesday with Liggett Group falling 50
cents a share to $7.62{.
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc., the nation's biggest tobacco company,
fell $1.75 to $83.25 and Loews Corp., parent of Lorillard, slipped
25 cents to $65.12{.
   RJR Nabisco Inc. dropped $1 to $47 and American Brands Inc. rose
25 cents to $45.12{. RJR Nabisco and American Brands were not party
to the suit.
   But analysts expected a recovery after an initial slump.
   ``We think it's a victory for the industry,'' said Kurt A.
Feuerman of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``It's a shot in the arm
for anti-tobacco forces, but it's largely symbolic.''
</TEXT>
