<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CBSWoes     06-15 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS Woes,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS News Stars Highlight Final Day Of Conference By No. 3 Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anchorman Dan Rather and other CBS news
personalities showed up to bolster executives' spirits at a
sometimes angry affiliates meeting, as word came that the No. 3
network plans to revamp its ``eye'' logo.
   The convention for the network's 206 affiliates, which ended
Tuesday, featured some harsh closed-door attacks on the string of
scheduling failures that mired CBS in third place this past season,
behind No. 1 NBC and No. 2 ABC.
   It was the first last-place finish among the big three networks
in CBS' history.
   ``This has not been a polite conference,'' said Howard Stringer,
president of CBS News.
   Meanwhile, CBS said it would unveil a new ``state of the art''
version of its trademark CBS ``eye'' logo along with new theme
music to identify the network, according to a story published in
today's editions of The Washington Post.
   The Post quoted the network, in a statement issued at the
affiliates' meeting, as saying the ``new, contemporary CBS logo
(is) designed to appeal to younger viewers while still pleasing
current viewers.''
   The network said the new logo and music could premiere by July
4, but that no definite date has been set, according to the Post.
   Amid complaints from worried station chiefs of a lack of focus,
CBS also said at the meeting it will launch a campaign to promote
Rather and its news correspondents and begin using cable to sell
itself in promotional spots.
   CBS President Laurence Tisch and CBS Broadcast Group President
Gene Jankowski said during the conference that poor promotion has
hurt CBS.
   ``We didn't do a good job,'' Tisch said of previous promotional
efforts.
   Rather, who was greeted with extended applause, introduced
several of the network's best-known journalists.
   ``I bring you warm welcomes from the men and women of CBS
News,'' Rather told the affiliates. ``I'm proud to be here with all
of you and I'm proud of all of you.''
   Others at the conference Tuesday were Harry K. Smith, Kathleen
Sullivan, Leslie Stahl, Ed Bradley, Diane Sawyer and Meredith
Vieira. They all took a turn onstage as their various news programs
were presented along with plans to improve them.
   Stringer introduced the journalists by noting that Rather and
the ``CBS Evening News'' won the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings war last
week, snapping a six-week run by ``ABC World News Tonight,''
anchored by Peter Jennings.
   The enthusiastic reaction to Rather contrasted with some
sentiments expressed at earlier meetings when station chiefs
complained about Rather's combative interview with Vice President
George Bush in January and his angry departure from the set of the
``CBS Evening News'' in August.
   Meanwhile, the news promos unveiled showed such things as Rather
in the field covering a flood, on the front line in Vietnam, in
Moscow, India, Cuba and elsewhere.
   ``Before Dan Rather went to the front desk, he went to the front
line,'' the ad announcer said.
   The promos were scheduled to begin airing today.
</TEXT>
