<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Army     06-15 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Army,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Announces Formation Of Rapid Response Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese army has established a rapid response
unit called the Fist Battalion to give more punch to China's
military under a reform program begun after an embarrassing
mini-war with Vietnam in 1979.
   The battalion will be able to parachute into deserts, deep
forest or marshland and conduct guerrilla warfare, the Xinhua News
Agency said today, quoting a report in Tuesday's Liberation Army
Daily.
   The battalion will also be able to reach any place inside China
in less than 20 hours to respond to emergencies, the official news
agency said.
   It did not say whether the unit might also be sent outside China
if national interests are at stake.
   The report also did not disclose the size of the unit or say
when it was formed, but the paper published two pictures dated 1986
showing members parachuting and drilling on a snow-covered hill in
China's northeast.
   Since faring badly in a brief border war with Vietnam in 1979,
China's military has undergone a major overhaul. Manpower has been
cut by 1 million, to 3 million troops, and greater emphasis has
been put on holding battle drills and upgrading troops' technical
skills.
   A 56,000-strong marine corps was set up in 1980 as a division of
the navy's South China Sea Fleet. Its mission is to defend coastal
areas and the Xisha (Paracels) and Nansha (Spratleys) island chains
in the South China Sea that also are claimed by Vietnam and several
other East Asian nations.
   The official China Daily recently reported that the marines are
stepping up their training and acquiring new equipment. It gave no
other details.
   Today's report said the Fist Battalion may set an example for
ordinary battalions to follow in a program to reform training
exercises.
   The Liberation Army Daily quoted a veteran parachuter as saying
the force was comparable to parachute units in the world's most
advanced countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0715EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissCalifornia     06-15 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miss California,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contestant Plotted Disruption For More Than A Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college student says she dieted, took voice
lessons and spent $5,000 during the 18 months that she plotted to
disrupt the Miss California pageant and ``expose the lies they
promote.''
   Michelle Anderson, Miss Santa Cruz in Monday's contest, pulled
from her bra a white silk banner reading ``Pageants Hurt All
Women'' just as the winner, Marlise Ricardos, was to be announced.
   Other participants yanked the banner from her, and security
guards promptly removed Miss Anderson from the San Diego Civic
Center's stage.
   ``I wanted to go behind the scenes of pageants and expose the
lies they promote, such as women like to be judged by men, or like
to duct tape their breasts ... or starve to be thin,'' Anderson
told a news conference Tuesday.
   She said the message beauty pageants give women is that to be
beautiful, they have to be thin, blond and young.
   ``Women suffer severe indignities to try to be beautiful
according to these standards,'' she said.
   Anderson, 21, a junior at the University of California, Santa
Cruz majoring in community studies, said her protest cost her the
Miss Santa Cruz title and a $3,000 scholarship.
   ``She really took us in,'' said Donna Williams, the executive
director of the Santa Cruz pageant. ``I think I'm a pretty wise
person. We've known her for two years, and I never had an inkling.''
   Victoria Garcia, a spokeswoman for the Miss California pageant,
said the pageant was helpless to prevent future protests from what
she termed a ``plant.''
   ``I know it broke the heart of the people running the Santa Cruz
pageant. They put so much time and effort in coaching, searching
for the right person. She (Anderson) cheated another person out of
a scholarship,'' Ms. Garcia said.
   Anderson said the idea for the stunt came during a protest
planning session with former model Ann Simonton, whose Santa
Cruz-based group, MediaWatch, has staged a number of pageant
demonstrations.
   The plan was for Anderson to get to the largest audience before
sharing her message, the women said. If she'd won the Miss
California pageant, she would have kept silent until reaching the
Miss America pageant.
   It took Anderson two tries to capture the Miss Santa Cruz title.
She was the second runner-up in 1987.
   According to Anderson, who said she is working on a book about
her pageant experiences, contestants must suspend their studies and
spend an enormous amount of time and money on getting their bodies
and talent in shape. Most spend far more than they win, she said.
   Anderson said she spent $5,000, lost 15 pounds, bleached her
hair, exercised and took voice lessons.
   She said she doesn't regret her actions, even though she is
sorry for hurting pageant organizers in Santa Cruz.
   ``But they're doing the wrong thing for women,'' Anderson said,
``and I'm more interested in standing up for women than being nice
and socially acceptable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
