<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-15 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Gold Higher In Early European Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
and and dealers predicted it would continue to climb following the
improvement in the U.S. trade deficit. Gold prices also rose.
   Dealers said Tuesday's trade figures for April, showing the
deficit had narrowed unexpectedly to $9.89 billion from a revised
$11.70 billion in March, had boosted bullish sentiment on the
dollar.
   Gerhard Roggemann, treasurer of J.P. Morgan GmbH in Frankfurt,
said: ``We are still bullish on the dollar.''
   Several traders said they expected the market to try to test
1.75 marks sometime today. But another trader in Milan argued that
the West German Bundesbank would almost certainly intervene if the
dollar moved above 1.75 marks.
   In early trading, the dollar was selling at 1.7484 marks, up
from 1.7460 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.27 yen to a closing 126.32. Later, in
London, it was quoted slightly lower at 126.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates:
   _ 1.4637 Swiss francs, up from 1.4615
   _ 5.89475 French francs, up from 5.8840
   _ 1.96335 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9600
   _ 1,298.50 Italian lire, up from 1,292.50
   _ 1.2192 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2162
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.7862 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7925 late Tuesday.
   Bullion dealers said the market was confused by bullion's
non-reaction to the U.S. trade figures.
   Normally, bullion prices would have been expected to tumble, but
gold fell only slightly after the figures were announced and then
recovered.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $449.70 a troy ounce and
at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $450.30. Both were up from Tuesday's late bid
of $448.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $450.40, up from $448.00 late
Tuesday.
   The Hong Kong Chinese Silver and Gold Society, which quotes
rates for the metal in Hong Kong, was closed today for the
association's elections. The society will reopen on Thursday.
   Silver was quoted in London Wednesday at a bid price of $7.04 a
troy ounce, up from late Tuesday's $6.91.
</TEXT>
