<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Iran 1stLd-Writethru a0565 06-15 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Iran, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France And Iran To Re-establish Diplomatic Ties Thursday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-last, bgng, `Gordji, officially ...,' with 5
grafs to UPDATE with 5 grafs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France and Iran said today they will re-establish
diplomatic relations Thursday after a break of nearly a year. The
move had been expected after the May release of last three French
hostages held in Lebanon.
   The two countries severed relations July 17 after the Iranian
Embassy refused to turn over Wahid Gordji, wanted for questioning
by French authorities in connection with a series of terrorist
bombings in 1986 that killed 11 people and wounded more than 150.
   The impending exchange of ambassadors was announced by a Foreign
Ministry spokesman in Paris, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
and Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   IRNA, monitored in Cyprus, said ambassadors will be dispatched
``shortly.'' It gave no other details.
   On May 4, pro-Iranian kidnappers in Lebanon freed Frenchmen
Marcel Fontaine, 45, and Marcel Carton, 62, both diplomats, and
journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann, 44.
   Iran said at the time that it had intervened ``for humanitarian
reasons'' to secure the hostages' release. It also said it agreed
to mediate the release because Jacques Chirac, then France's prime
minister, had responded ``positively'' to Iranian demands.
   The conditions centered on the repayment of a billion-dollar
loan made by Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi of Iran before the Islamic
revolution in 1979. Within two weeks of the hostages' release,
Socialist Prime Minister Michel Rocard announced that relations
would be restored.
   Rocard, the newly appointed premier, said, ``My government and
the president do not intend to pass judgment on the conditons under
which these negotiations took place.''
   Gordji, officially listed as an embassy translator without
diplomatic immunity, took refuge in the embassy in late June. He
was allowed to leave France after two other French hostages,
Jean-Louis Normandin and Roger Auque, both journalists, were freed
in Beirut on Nov. 27.
   Eighteen foreigners remain missing in Lebanon and are believed
held by pro-Iranian zealots. They are nine Americans, three
Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Indian, an Irishman and two
men of unidentified nationality.
   Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, is the longest held captive. He was taken hostage
March 16, 1985.
   A total of 10 French hostages were freed from Lebanon during the
two years that Chirac's government was in power. One hostage,
researcher Michel Seurat, died in captivity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
