<2ND_LINE>PM-Rhino Breeding,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baton Rouge Zoo Taking Part In Program To Save Rhinos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zookeepers hope Marvin, a 5,000-pound
rhinoceros, will get the right message when he is introduced on
Father's Day weekend to two female rhinos who have failed to
reproduce since their arrival in 1974.
   Marvin's visit to the Greater Baton Rouge Zoo from Knoxville,
Tenn., for the next few months is part of a breeding program
sponsored by the American Association of Zoological Parks and
Aquariums to replenish the endangered species.
   George Felton, zoo director and past president of AAZPA, said
Marvin would be introduced Friday to Hatari and Wagasa, whose
previous male companion was sent to the Knoxville zoo in May as
part of the exchange program.
   Marvin is a proven sire, having fathered 13 rhino calves at
other zoos, Felton said.
   At Friday's introduction, Thomas Babin, a father of 15 named
locally as Senior Father of the Year, will present a 6-foot
Father's Day card to Marvin.
   Marvin's trip here by special trailer truck was paid for with a
$50,000 grant from the Armstrong Tire Co., which uses the rhino as
a trademark.
</TEXT>
