<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NortonSimon-Art     06-15 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Norton Simon-Art,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norton Simon Withdraws Offer to Give Artwork to UCLA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired industrialist Norton Simon has
withdrawn his offer to donate his coveted $750 million art
collection to the University of California, Los Angeles, the Los
Angeles Times reported today.
   UCLA had said the gift would create ``the greatest
university-based art collection in the world.''
   A one-paragraph statement indicating the offer was dropped was
issued by the Norton Simon Art Foundation following repeated
inquiries, the newspaper said.
   UCLA also announced that negotiations between the university and
Simon had stalled, but neither party would say why.
   An unidentified source told the newspaper that one obstacle was
the university's inability to remove a rental car agency near the
site of the museum planned to house the collection on UCLA's
Westwood campus.
   The Simon collection, which includes a large number of Old
Masters as well as impressionist paintings, Asian bronzes and
sculpture, also was to be maintained at its present home in the
Norton Simon Museum in Pasadena.
   Four months ago, University Chancellor Charles Young said
negotiations were ``very far along.'' On Tuesday, he declined to
comment on the foundation's statement.
   The Norton Simon statement said problems ``in both the substance
of the negotiations and in the manner in which UCLA conducted
them'' stalled talks.
   ``We negotiated diligently with Mr. Simon,'' the UCLA statement
said. ``Mr. Simon asked for a break in negotiations while he
attended to other matters, and said he would get back to us. He has
not gotten back to us.''
   Five months ago, negotiations collapsed between industrialist
Armand Hammer and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art over the
future of Hammer's collection of Old Masters, impressionist
paintings and other art.
   After the museum rejected various conditions, the chairman of
Occidental Petroleum Corp. decided not to donate his collection but
to build his own museum in Westwood.
</TEXT>
