<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Refuseniks 1stLd-Writethru a0504 06-15 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Refuseniks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Stayed Away, But Soviet Family Is Refused Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS third graf ``She said...'' to clarify.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish family again was refused permission to
emigrate, two weeks after President Reagan canceled a meeting with
them for fear of dooming their 11-year campaign to leave.
   Tanya Zieman, whose 12-year-old daughter had appealed to the
president and Mrs. Reagan for help in leaving the country, said she
received the news Tuesday evening from the Moscow City Council.
   She said the council told her the family's appeal was turned
down by a review commission of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's
nominal parliament, and that the family could reapply to emigrate
after 1992.
   During the Reagans' summit trip to Moscow two weeks ago, U.S.
sources said the American first family agonized over whether to
stop at the Ziemans' home after a top Soviet Foreign Ministry
official warned such a visit would ruin the family's chances to
emigrate.
   The Ziemans' younger daughter, Vera, who calls herself ``a
lifelong refusenik'' because her family applied to emigrate shortly
after she was born, had written the Reagans asking for their help.
   White House officials had been to the Ziemans' tiny, three-room
apartment in southwest Moscow to survey the home for a presidential
visit the week before the Reagans' May 29 arrival in Moscow.
   Soviet authorities, getting wind of the plans, sent a swarm of
workers to repave the drive, paint the apartment building, repair
the stoop, scrub the corridor walls and landscape nearby flower
beds.
   A massive security force deployed around the building the day
the Reagans arrived in the capital drew a crowd of several hundred
local residents.
   But U.S. and Soviet sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Bessmertnykh warned U.S.
Ambassador Jack F. Matlock and an accompanying White House official
that if the Reagans went through with the visit, the Ziemans would
never leave the country.
   In the end, the Reagans scrubbed the plan.
   ``They didn't want to knuckle under to intimidation, but they
didn't want to hurt the Ziemans, either,'' one source said.
   The family, headed by Yuri Zieman, a former computer specialist,
did attend a tea the Reagans gave for people the U.S.
administration considers victims of Soviet human rights abuses.
   Yuri Zieman, who lost his job when he applied to emigrate in
1977, worked as a plumber until he was stricken several months ago
by a mysterious brain ailment that has left him with double vision
and a loss of balance.
   During his hospitalization for that condition, he contracted
hepatitis, and his wife said Tuesday he remained very weak.
   Zieman has been told he is not permitted to leave the country
for security reasons, although he contends he never had access to
state secrets and has no information that could threaten Soviet
security.
   ``He had been feeling much better the last two weeks, thinking
we would be getting some good news soon'' following the Moscow
summit, Mrs. Zieman said Tuesday.
   Asked if the family would apply again for exit visas, she said,
``I'm still very much in a fighting mood.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
