<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoardingSchool     06-15 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boarding School,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Remove 29 Girls From Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities investigating allegations of
abuse at a boarding school for girls cut the home's locked gates
and removed 29 students.
   A spokesman at the private New Bethany Home for Girls called the
action Tuesday an illegal raid. All 52 girls, ranging in age from
12 to 17, were told they could leave the school, but 23 remained,
an official said.
   ``We feel this is a gross violation of civil rights,'' said Bob
Sensat, a member of the home's board. He denied allegations of
abuse.
   The state Department of Health and Human Resources obtained a
court order to search the complex and interview the girls after
receiving complaints from a runaway, said Lucky Raley, chief
criminal investigator for the Bienville Parish sheriff.
   About 30 girls flee the institution each year, the juvenile
officer said. Sheriff Aarvis Whitman calls the home a prison and
has refused to send back runaways.
   Juvenile authorities said the girls removed from the home were
placed in temporary housing.
   ``Yes, praise God!''``I'm going home, finally,'' one girl said
as tears streamed down her face.
   One girl said she received 20 ``licks'' with a paddle for having
rock music tapes and for cutting her bangs.
   DHHR officials, two state troopers and five deputies arrived
Tuesday at the school, which is situated 3.5 miles south of here
and is surrounded by a 6-foot chain link fence topped with barbed
wire.
   ``They said come on in, but you're going to have to cut the lock
to get in. So we did,'' said Raley.
   Some girls who chose to remain at the school chastised departing
students from inside the yard. ``We are staying here with the
Lord,'' one said.
   The raid was a violation of constitutional rights because of the
separation of church and state, Sensat said, adding that the state
had no right to intervene because the home receives no government
funding.
   The Rev. Mack W. Ford, pastor and director of the home, was in
South Carolina, Sensat said. Ford founded the institution in 1971.
   ``The state has no right to dictate to the church how to carry
on its ministry when we do not have any proven abuse cases. They
came in merely on assumption,'' Sensat said.
   DHHR tried to close the school in 1980 for refusing to allow an
inspection and licensing, but a judge ruled the state lacked such
authority. DHHR had received a number of complaints in 1979 about
the home's operation.
   On Friday, the Bethel Home for Children, a fundamentalist
boarding school in Lucedale, Miss., was shut down. Its proprietor,
the Rev. Herman Fountain, was arrested on charges of assulting a
police officer and inciting a riot.
   Authorities have charged that the Bethel Home abused and
neglected its students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
