<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BackpackCocaine     06-15 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Backpack Cocaine,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youngster Finds Cocaine in Backpack, Shares With Schoolmates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested the mother of a
7-year-old girl who found a plastic-wrapped chunk of cocaine in her
backpack and tasted it with eight curious playmates at lunch,
sheriff's deputies said.
   The nine pupils were treated at Canoga Park Community Hospital
for stomach aches and released.
   Maria Christina Torres, 39, a native of Colombia who has been in
the United States for 20 years and lives in Topanga Canyon, was
booked for investigation of child endangerment and released on
$100,000 bail, said Lt. Bill Gaida.
   Mrs. Torres' daughter, Angelina Valdez, found the cocaine during
lunch Monday at Canoga Park Lutheran School, 25 miles from downtown
Los Angeles, Gaida said.
   ``She thought it was medicine and her curiosity was aroused,''
Gaida said. ``She tasted it and it tasted bitter.''
   The girl passed it around to eight pupils, ages 7 to 11, Gaida
said, adding, ``All their curiosity was aroused at this point and
they all tasted it.''
   A ``real sharp'' sixth-grader saw what was going on and took the
cocaine from the youngsters and gave it to a school administrator
``who thought the material was soap and threw it in the trash,''
Gaida said.
   Later, Mrs. Torres came to school explained that she had left
soap in her child's backpack, he said.
   A school official retrieved the chunk from a wastebasket and
broke off a piece without the woman's knowledge, Gaida said. A test
determined it was a half-gram of cocaine worth about $50, the
lieutenant said.
</TEXT>
