<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Space-Fletcher     06-15 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space-Fletcher,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Shuttle Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>NASA Head Sees Next President Approving Moon Or Mars Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA Administrator James C. Fletcher said
today he is confident the next president will set a goal of having
astronauts return to the moon or fly to Mars.
   Fletcher, interviewed on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' said
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration ``is back on
track'' with a long-range goal of moving beyond the construction of
a space station and into the Solar System.
   But he said the space station is threatened by possible budget
cuts. Fletcher earlier warned that he would recommend killing the
space station program if Congress makes proposed deep cuts in the
agency's requested $11.5 billion budget for the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1.
   Fletcher said pressure to reduce spending has prevented
President Reagan from setting the goal of long manned space flights.
   ``The next step, whether we go back to the moon or go to Mars,
is to build a space station, and that is in considerable doubt
right now due to the severe budget crunch,'' he said. ``That is the
next thing the president has to focus on, and I think he will.''
   Fletcher said he expects the United States to have a space
station by the end of the century.
   ``Even if we don't get the funding this year, the next
prrsident, I'm sure, will sign up for the space station and an
appropriate goal, probably Mars of the moon,'' he said.
</TEXT>
