<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Awad     06-15 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Awad,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Rejects No-Confidence Motion Over Awad's Expulsion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli parliament today rejected a motion
of no confidence in the country's government filed by a leftist
party over the deportation of Arab-American non-violence advocate
Mubarak Awad.
   The motion was filed by the Progressive List for Peace, a mixed
Arab-Jewish party that holds two seats in the 120-member Knesset.
It was defeated by a vote of 19 to 17, Israel radio said.
   Awad, 44, a Jerusalem-born U.S. citizen, was deported Monday
after the government accused him of inciting the six-month-old Arab
uprising in the occupied territories. Israel's Supreme Court
rejected his appeal, saying he had no legal residence permit and
was in Israel on an expired tourist visa.
   Awad, who has a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio, advocates non-violent
resistance to Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
His tactics, which include general strikes, boycotts of Israeli
products and refusal to pay taxes, have been adopted by underground
leaders of the uprising.
   Legislator Roni Milo of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc told the parliament that ``if an Israeli
tourist in the United States proposed the means offered by Mubarak
Awad ... stones, firebombs, refusal to pay taxes ... he would have
been expelled to Israel within an hour.''
   ``This is the situation with Mubarak Awad and let nobody teach
us morals about it,'' said Milo, who responded to the no-confidence
motion on behalf of the government. His remarks were broadcast by
the radio.
   The motion was rejected by a combined vote of the Likud and the
right-wing Tehiya and Morasha parties against the votes of several
left-wing parties.
</TEXT>
