<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InsuranceConspiracy     06-15 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insurance Conspiracy,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten More States Accuse Top Insurers of Instigating Liability
Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. insurers conspired to stop
providing some kinds of liability coverage, touching off a
nationwide insurance crisis, 10 states claimed in lawsuits.
   The suits, filed in U.S. District Court on Tuesday, follow eight
others filed in March. They claim the crisis forced municipalities
and agencies to cut back on services and crippled businesses
throughout the country.
   The new states in the federal court action are Maryland,
Connecticut, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Colorado, Montana,
Washington, Alaska and Michigan.
   New York state Attorney General Robert Abrams said the case was
one of the largest ever undertaken by a group of states in federal
court.
   The lawsuits accused 32 insurance companies and underwriting
agencies of engaging in secret agreements that included targeting
for elimination pollution insurance and general liability for
damage discovered after expiration of a policy.
   Pennsylvania Attorney General LeRoy S. Zimmerman and New Jersey
Attorney General Cary Edwards, at a news conference in Philadelphia
on Tuesday, said they could not estimate the dollar value of the
damage claims, but that it was in the millions for their two states
alone.
   The four major insurance companies named in the suit are
Hartford Insurance Company and Aetna Casualty and Surety Company,
both of Hartford, Conn.; Allstate Insurance Co. of Northbrook,
Ill., and Cigna Corp. of Philadelphia.
   Aetna condemned the suits as ``another political move by
political office-holders who have consistently opposed any and all
effort to address the real problems of the nation's liability
system.''
   Hartford Insurance called the suits ``totally without
substance'' and expressed confidence the claims would be thrown out
of court.
   Aetna, Allstate, Cigna, and Hartford Fire Insurance Co. started
a campaign in 1984 to cut back on coverage then generally available
in the country, the suits claimed.
   The suits also alleged that the companies got major U.S. and
British reinsurers, including Lloyds of London, to threaten to
boycott any U.S. insurance company that provided broader coverage.
   The companies pressured the Insurance Services Office, a
1,400-member industry trade group, to quit distributing standard
forms in order to make it tough for companies to continue offering
certain coverage, the suits claimed.
   As a result, the suits said, property damage insurance for local
governments, nonprofit agencies such as child care centers and
various businesses suddenly became unavailable or extremely
expensive.
   ``The insurance industry finds that these attorneys general
suits are based upon a total misunderstanding of how the insurance
industry works,'' said William F. Bailey, special counsel to the
New York-based ISO.
   ``Every statement that was alleged to have been made in the
secrecy of private clubs in New York was made in open hearings in
front of state insurance commissioners,'' Bailey said. ``There was
no collusion to fix the market.''
   The 10 states who filed suit on Tuesday joined California, New
York, Massachussetts, West Virginia, Wisconsin, Minnesota and
Alabama. Texas filed suit in its own state court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
