<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FisherTreasure     06-15 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fisher Treasure,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasures From the Deep On the Auction Block</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A treasure trove of Spanish gold, silver and
emeralds that had lain unnoticed for centuries in the waters off
Florida attracted the rich, the famous and the curious at an
auction that brought $2.5 million.
   Before Tuesday's sale, treasure hunter Mel Fisher stood on the
sidewalk outside Christie's auction house greeting passers-by,
posing for photographs and wearing around his neck pounds of gold
chain he took from the ocean floor.
   ``I want to show how safe it is in New York,'' the former
Indiana chicken farmer and California dive shop operator said
before running upstairs for the auction.
   The auction was the first of a two-day sale of booty recovered
from a pair of Spanish treasure galleons that went down in a
hurricane off the Florida Keys in 1622.
   Most of the treasure _ which included gold and silver bars,
jewelry and artifacts as well as coins, emeralds and 17th-century
navigation instruments _ came from the galleons of the Nuestra
Senora de Atocha and her sister ship, the Santa Margarita. Fisher's
expedition discovered the Atocha _ which held the richest treasure
ever recovered from the sea _ in 1971 and the Margarita nine years
later.
   However, some of the auctioned artifacts were recovered by
divers working off Florida's east coast, where a Spanish fleet went
down in a hurricane in 1715.
   A 62-inch Renaissance gold chain from the Margarita attracted
the most attention and fetched $319,000 in spirited bidding. The
chain, formed from 136 oval links, went to an anonymous telephone
bidder.
   Several brass astrolabes used to navigate the ill-fated vessels
also attracted high prices.
   ``They're very, very rare things, very important,'' Anthony
Phillips, a Christie's executive said of the instruments. Several
went to European museums that the auction house declined to
identify.
   Celebrities in the crowd included Texas oil tycoon Nelson Bunker
Hunt, who said he was merely a spectator, and actress Margot Kidder.
   ``I tried for some emeralds, but missed,'' she said.
   While items such as a two-handled gold cup that brought $275,000
or a silver-gilt cup that sold for $165,000 generated the most
interest, more modest items also went up on the block, including a
fishhook-shaped gold wire that fetched $308.
   Tuesday's items were offered by backers who financed Fisher's
expeditions in exchange for a share of the proceeds.
</TEXT>
