<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Race,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wives of Brothers Have Babys on Same Day, Same Hospital, Same
Doctor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim and Geoff Hall _ avid runners who have
spent many a summer breaking each other's track records _ are used
to a little brotherly competition.
   This time, the race was on in the maternity ward at Bergan Mercy
Hospital.
   The arrival of two Hall cousins on the same day, delivered by
the same doctor, began with confusion Saturday when Geoff, 27, and
his wife, Kim, arrived at Bergan's emergency entrance.
   ``We walked in and they asked, `Are you the Hall family?' We
said `yes' and then went up to delivery,'' Geoff recalled.
   ``Jim and Kathy showed up about 15 minutes later and told the
people at the desk, `We're Kathy and Jim Hall.' And the people at
the desk said, `No, you're not; they're here.'''
   Apparently, the hospital pulled the wrong medical file when the
mothers-to-be called to warn of their arrival, Geoff said.
   It was understandable. Both mothers are 27, both first names
begin with ``K'' and they had the same doctor.
   The confusion did not end at the emergency room. Geoff said that
Tuesday when he and Kim called for their Nicholas Samuel, nurses
brought in his nephew, Daniel Jerome.
   ``In high school we were all runners, so I think Jim was kind of
racing to see whose would come first,'' Geoff said. ``He kept
popping his head in our room to check.''
   ``It was kind of a race to the finish,'' said Kathy, a
long-distance runner herself. ``But, this time Geoff won.''
   Nicholas Samuel beat his cousin's arrival by five hours and 42
minutes.
</TEXT>
