<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoneyHole     06-15 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Hole,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Geologists Use Shredded Money to Plug Drill Hole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of Ohio admits to pouring money
down a hole _ about $93,000 of it.
   State geologists recently used 200 pounds of old shredded bills
from the Federal Reserve Bank to fill in crevices in a 3-inch
diameter, 4,000-foot hole.
   The state Geological Survey began drilling the hole in a Wayne
Township quarry in October as part of an effort to map the state's
underground strata.
   Water is pumped into the hole as a lubricant and coolant for the
diamond-studded drill bit, then pumped back up, said geologist Mike
Hansen. At 1,800 feet, geologists found that the water was
disappearing, seeping into crevices.
   Doug Crowell, geologist and supervisor of the drilling program,
said drillers who had attended a seminar at Wright State University
a few years ago told him about using bills as a sealing agent.
   ``We tried some standard products and just weren't getting any
results,'' Crowell said. ``We tried the money and it worked.
Because of the high linen content, it doesn't dissolve easily and
works well as a sealer.''
</TEXT>
