<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PottyParity     06-15 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Potty Parity,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Spend More Time In Restroom Than Men, Researchers Find</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's official: women spend more time in the
restroom than men.
   Two Virginia Tech researchers, armed with stop watches and
questionnaires, found that a woman's visit to a public restroom
runs 50 percent longer than a man's.
   One reason, Savannah S. Day, a Virginia Tech professor of
housing, and Sandra K. Rawls, who used the research to earn her
doctorate, said Tuesday is that women often have youngsters in tow.
   Another factor, they said, is that women are often hindered by
large handbags and packages.
   The researchers spent several months timing more than 450 people
going in and out of restrooms at sports arenas, a conference
center, an airport and a highway rest area.
   A restroom stop by a woman averaged between 153 seconds and 181
seconds, according to their findings. The men's average was between
84 seconds and 113 seconds.
   The findings have a bearing on the legislative issue of potty
parity.
   State Rep. John A. Rollison III is planning hearings in October
on the ratio of men's restrooms to women's in public buildings.
Some claim the standard 50-50 split is not equal. Rollison said he
would like to increase the number of women's facilities.
   ``We know it's a fact that women do take longer,'' said Ms.
Rawls. ``We can proceed from there and see how best the problem can
be handled.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
