<HEAD>Settlement Reached In Concert Injury Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers who claimed they were injured
by a special effects explosion during a concert by the heavy metal
rock group Motley Crue have accepted at least $175,000 to settle
their suit, a lawyer said.
   Jim Corder, a lawyer for one of the teen-agers, said Tuesday the
band's insurer, Fireman's Fund, reached the settlement with Robbie
Miller, 17, of Athens, who lost an eye, and David Wright, 19, of
Grant, who suffered facial cuts.
   The two said they injured by dry ice or other debris that flew
from the stage during the band's 1986 ``Theater of Pain'' concert
in Huntsville.
   Corder said the agreement stipulated that the amount not be made
public. He said only that it was larger than the previous Limestone
County record of $175,000 and that most of it will go to Miller.
   The two had asked for about $1.2 million in damages. The case
went to trial earlier this year but ended in a mistrial with a
deadlocked jury.
</TEXT>
