<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Suzuki-Suit     06-15 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suzuki-Suit,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Accuses Suzuki of Racketeering Violations with Samurai Trucks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maker of the Suzuki Samurai knew the
sporty vehicles were unsafe but sold them anyway, a class-action
lawsuit charges.
   The federal suit filed Tuesday charges Suzuki conspired to
conceal the Samurai's instability in violation of the Racketeering
Influenced, Corrupt Organizations Act, a statute often employed
against organized crime.
   Consumers Union, publisher of Consumer Reports, said June 2 that
the Samurai rolls over in sudden turns at less than 40 mph and
should be banned. The $8,500 Samurai was the first car in a decade
to get a not-acceptable rating from the magazine.
   The suit, filed by Dr. Harold Kay of Wynnewood, Pa., on behalf
of all Samurai owners, contends that Suzuki and the companies
handling its public relations and advertising knew the vehicles
were ``by design and construction dangerous'' and that
``advertising and other sales representations were false and
misleading.''
   It seeks unspecified damages.
   Laura Segall, spokeswoman for Suzuki and an employee of the
defendant public relations firm Rogers and Associates, said
Tuesday, ``The bottom line we've said for the last 10 days is that
it's safe and stable.''
   The manufacturer said the the Samurai was thoroughly tested for
safety, stability and handling before it was introduced in the
United States in November 1985. Suzuki sold 154,675 Samurais
through April.
   In addition to the Consumers Union claims, the suit points to
the Center for Auto Safety's February petition to the government to
order a recall.
   It also cites National Traffic Highway Safety Administration
figures that at least 44 Samurai rollover accidents resulted in at
least 53 injuries and 16 deaths.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
