<HEAD>Thunderstorms Along Mississippi, Temperature Records Fall in Much
of U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with second day of record
temperatures expected in Northeast, rainfall amounts in Midwest and
Colorado, 30 degrees in Black Hills. Picks up in 3rd graf, `In
eastern ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened parts of the Midwest and the
West today after a heat wave baking America's northern half smashed
or tied temperature records in 34 cities from Portland, Ore., to
Portland, Maine.
   However, most areas had only a trace of rain and reports of more
than a tenth of an inch were rare, the National Weather Service
said.
   Another hot day was under way in the Northeast, and a long list
of record temperatures was expected. By 10 a.m. today, Boston
registered 89 degrees, and the temperature was expected to hit 96
this afternoon.
   In contrast, the temperature at Deerfield Lake, S.D., in the
Black Hills dropped to a crisp 30 this morning.
   Rain fell over Wisconsin, southeastern Nebraska and central
Kansas. Northwest Texas, eastern New Mexico and eastern Colorado
had scattered showers and thundershowers.
   Heavier rain fell in Wisconsin, eastern Kansas and eastern
portions of New Mexico and Colorado.
   A half-inch of rain fell in Axtell in northeast Kansas and
four-tenths of an inch in Manhattan. Fairfax, Wis., had nine-tenths
of an inch. Las Vegas, N.M., had slightly more than an inch of
rain; Wheatridge and La Junta, Colo., recorded 1{ inches and more
than half an inch during the six hours ending at 6 a.m. EDT.
   In eastern Colorado, a thunderstorm dropped up to 2 inches of
small hail near Hartsel.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the country, with clear
skies from the Gulf Coast to the Atlantic Coast and in the
north-central United States.
   On Tuesday night, severe thunderstorms swept through the upper
Mississippi Valley. In southeast Minnesota, the storms generated
winds gusting to 60 mph, downing power lines in the Pine Island and
Zumbro Falls area, and small hail which did some crop damage in
Owatonna. High winds downed trees in four northern Wisconsin
counties.
   Tuesday's hot weather broke temperature records for June 14 in
27 cities and tied them in seven cities in the Northeast, Midwest
and West.
   It was 94 degrees in Pittsburgh, where the old mark of 93 was
set in 1885. In Washington, D.C., the 103-year-old record of 94
degrees was tied. Alpena, Mich., reported a sweltering 98 degrees,
4 degrees over last year's record.
   It was 89 degrees in Portland, Ore., 1 degree over the 1961 mark
and a record-tying 84 degrees in Portland, Maine.
   Other cities experiencing record temperatures included
Baltimore, Philadelphia; Beckley, W.Va.; Providence, R.I.;
Burlington, Vt.; Cleveland; Detroit; Marquette, Mich.; and Seattle.
   While not a record, the nation's high Tuesday was 110 degrees in
Bullhead City, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in
southern and central Florida, from northwest Indiana to Illinois
and Missouri, over central Colorado and scattered widely over
northeast Minnesota and northern Nevada.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 60s and 70s from Upper
Michighan to northern Wisconsin, Minnesota, the Dakotas, western
Nebraska and northeast Colorado, along the northern Pacific Coast
and along much of the California coast; the 80s and 90s in much of
the rest of the nation; and 100 to 110 degrees in the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Custer and Redig, S.D., to 89 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 69 fair; Boston 76 fair; Buffalo 72 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 63 foggy; Cincinnati 64 fair; Cleveland 71 fair;
Detroit 70 fair; Miami 77 fair; New York 73 fair; Philadelphia 70
foggy; Pittsburgh 64 fair; Portland, Maine 63 fair; Washington 70
foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 46 fair; Chicago 73 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
77 fair; Denver 59 cloudy; Des Moines 68 partly cloudy;
Indianapolis 67 fair; Kansas City 73 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 63 fair; Nashville 73 fair; New Orleans 66 fair; St. Louis 78
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 71 cloudy; Las Vegas 84 partly cloudy; Los
Angeles 59 foggy; Phoenix 88 fair; Salt Lake City 64 fair; San
Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 68 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 70 fair; Toronto 68 fair.
</TEXT>
