<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Baby Whale,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whale Found in Surf, Brought to Sea World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newborn whale that beached itself with
its mother near Patrick Air Force Base was reported holding its own
Wednesday at Sea World marine park.
   Animal handlers were administering fluids and trying to keep the
2-foot calf stabilized.
   Survival chances are historically low for the pgymy sperm whale
species. ``A calf separated from its mother is an even more
critical problem,'' said Jack Pearson, Sea World's curator of
mammals.
   Passers-by spotted the calf swimming about 500 yards south of
its beached mother on Tuesday off the base, south of Cocoa Beach.
   ``The calf still had afterbirth and blood on it when I got
here,'' said Robert Fransisco, an Air Force structural technician
who held the calf in the surf for four hours. ``The mother was
really bleeding, too.''
   The mother's body was brought to Sea World to try to determine
the cause of death.
</TEXT>
