<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti     06-15 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Manigat Rescinds Army Order To Transfer Colonel Indicted For Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ President Leslie Manigat today
halted the transfer of high-ranking military officials, saying the
action was needed to ``avoid a major crisis'' in the country.
   Manigat rescinded an order by Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, army chief
of staff, for the transfers or retirements of certain military
leaders.
   Private radio station Haiti Inter reported Col. Jean-Claude
Paul, indicted for drug trafficking earlier this year by a grand
jury in Miami, had been relieved of his command as head of the
notorious Dessalines Army Barracks.
   The station, which quoted an unidentified military source, said
Paul had been made assistant chief of staff, a largely
administrative position.
   The source said Paul spent the night, as usual, in the
Dessalines Barracks, the radio station said.
   Soldiers from the Dessalines Barracks under Paul's command have
been blamed for widespread violence that forced the cancellation of
general elections in Haiti last November and left more than 30
people dead.
   Manigat's order was made public today in an official communique
from the National Palace signed by the president and read over the
radio.
   The statement said ``the transfer and retirement of certain
high-ranking officers and other officers decided Tuesday morning by
the commander-in-chief'' had been rescinded to ``avoid a major
crisis.'' The president ``orders a return to the former status
quo,'' the statement said.
   Namphy, the former head of the junta that ruled Haiti after
dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled in February 1986, is chief of
the armed forces.
   Paul was accused in March of conspiring to import 100 kilograms
of cocaine into the United States in December 1986. The indictment
said the traffickers used a landing strip on Paul's farm 90 miles
outside the capital, Port-au-Prince, to load and fly the shipment
to the Bahamas.
   Tuesday afternoon, as rumors of Paul's transfer spread, many
street vendors packed up early and a number of shops closed their
doors, radio stations said. In the evening more private vehicles
than usual were seached and extra military patrols were noted on
the main arteries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
