<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDSPoll     06-15 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Poll,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: AIDS Most Serious Health Problem, More U.S. Action Favored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans view AIDS as the nation's most
serious health problem, and a majority favor mandatory testing for
the virus as well as more spending on education and research,
according to a poll released Wednesday.
   The survey for the American Association of Blood Banks said
people generally believe the blood supply is safer today than five
years ago, although nearly half _ 48 percent _ still think it is
likely AIDS could be contracted through a blood transfusion.
   Half of those questioned supported making every effort to
protect the blood supply, even at the risk of much higher blood
costs or blood shortages. But officials cautioned against thinking
that all risk could be eliminated.
   ``We are concerned that Americans believe it is possible to have
a `zero risk blood supply,''' said Dr. Paul J. Schmidt, AABB
president. ``Because blood is a human tissue, it will never be
`zero risk.'''
   The telephone survey of 1,000 people selected at random was
conducted by the polling firm of Hamilton, Frederick and Schneiders
on April 19 and May 1. The margin of error was plus or minus 3
percentage points.
   Forty-eight percent said acquired immune deficiency syndrome was
the ``most serious health problem facing the country today,''
compared with 35 percent in a prior AABB survey in December 1986.
Forty-six percent said cancer was the most serious concern,
compared with 52 percent in 1986.
   Ninety-five percent favored a nationwide AIDS education program,
and 84 percent supported increasing government spending
significantly for AIDS research, even if that would cause increased
taxes or cuts in key programs.
   Seventy-eight percent favored mandatory testing for drug users,
homosexuals and prostitutes; 78 percent favored it for couples
applying for marriage licenses; and 75 percent favored mandatory
testing for employees such as health professionals, teachers and
food service workers.
   The American Association of Blood Banks is a professional
society which includes 2,400 hospital blood banks, transfusion
services and community blood centers which collect nearly half the
nation's blood supply and transfuse more than 80 percent of the
blood collected in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
