<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0464 06-15 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Wants Democrats to Back Tax Increase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson comments in top 8 grafs, picking up in
3rd graf, On Tuesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today his ``most critical''
political concern is to have the Democratic convention accept his
budget priorities, which include increasing taxes and freezing
military spending to pay for social programs.
   Now that Michael Dukakis' camp has agreed to his platform
position on South Africa, Jackson indicated he will home in on his
budget arguments.
   ``The most critical becomes this budget, a commitment to invest
in people, a commitment to reinvest in America,'' Jackson said
following a meeting with leaders of civil rights groups.
   He said Dukakis talks of helping people but has made ``far too
little commitment to offset the impact of Reagan's shortfall in
investment in urban America.''
   ``Now putting forth a commitment to dream a new dream, to choose
hope over dope, and pay for our dreams will be central to our
thrust at the platform hearings and in Atlanta.''
   Jackson has proposed a freeze on military spending and raising
taxes on the wealthy and corporations to pay for his proposals, but
the Dukakis forces have rejected those two ideas.
   He said he urged the black leaders, meeting at the invitation of
the Black Leadership Forum, to meet with Dukakis. Benjamin Hooks,
head of the NAACP, said they would seek such a meeting and would
voice concerns about budget priorities.
   Jackson also said the idea of moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel
from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, a proposal endorsed by Dukakis, would
be ``a fatal mistake'' if done outside the context of a negotiated
peace plan. He said such a move would ``create more chaos.''
   On Tuesday, Jackson repeated his contention that he ought to be
a contender for the No. 2 spot on the ticket, although he's still
not saying whether he'd accept it if an offer were extended.
   ``I have earned, my constituency has earned, consideration to be
on the ticket,'' Jackson said during a news conference following a
speech to the U.S. Conference of Mayors in Salt Lake City.
   Recent polls have indicated that having Jackson on the ticket
would hurt Dukakis more than it would help, but he brushed that
suggestion aside.
   ``Our combined efforts could very well bring victory,'' he said.
   Despite all the talk about the vice presidency, Jackson said he
was still not willing to concede the nomination to Dukakis. The
Massachusetts governor has more than enough delegates to win the
nomination on the first ballot at the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta next month.
   ``My priority at this point is to seek the nomination,'' Jackson
insisted.
   Jackson also termed weekend Democratic platform-drafting
meetings on Macincac Island, Mich., a ``step in the right
direction'' toward resolving platform differences between him and
Dukakis.
   ``They established a framework for negotiation,'' he said.
   In his speech to the mayors, Jackson said he did much to set the
agenda for the presidential campaign.
   ``The present focus on human rights, drugs and, now, South
Africa, ratifies my leadership,'' he said.
   Jackson repeated his call for a military spending freeze, and
proposed financing small business loans and low-income housing with
securities purchased by public pension funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
