<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OperationSnowstorm 1stLd-Writethru a0484 06-15 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Operation Snowstorm, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agent `Flabbergasted' At Halting Of Drug Investigation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 7 grafs new with detail from today's hearing; pick up 6th
graf, According to.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undercover agent testified today he was
``very flabbergasted'' that a secret investigation into widespread
drug trafficking was abruptly halted at a California nuclear
weapons laboratory before he could penetrate highly classified
areas.
   Detective Robert Buda said the undercover investigation was
terminated by Energy Department officials three days before he
received his ``green card'' clearance to pursue drug ring leaders
in the most sensitive areas of the Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory near San Francisco.
   ``Unfortunately that door was closed before we could get in,''
he told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee.
   A subcommittee report circulated before today's hearing said
more than 100 employees had been targeted in the investigation
known as Operation Snowstorm.
   The report said the investigation was halted in September 1986,
nine months after it began. David A. Leary, who was in charge of
the investigation, said that 127 suspects had been identified
before the investigation was terminated.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said the investigation ``should be
called Operation Snowjob'' because Energy Department officials were
too afraid of adverse publicity to continue the drug investigation.
   The laboratory conducts top-secret research on nuclear weapons
and President Reagan's Star Wars missile defense system. Timothy L.
Mitchell of the laboratory's drug investigating team testified that
the volume of drug trafficking at Livermore ``has the potential to
endanger national security.''
   According to the subcommittee report, the drug investigation by
the laboratory's security department was halted by Lawrence
Livermore managers under pressure from Energy Department officials.
   The investigation began in January 1986 after an ``alarming
number'' of employees became involved in drug-related activities
and arrests. The report fails to specify the drugs, but a
subcommittee source told the Post that cocaine, methamphetamine and
marijuana were used during and after work hours.
   John Hunt, head of the security at the laboratory, told
investigators ``we would have to arrest 20 percent of the lab'' if
the operation were allowed to continue.
</TEXT>
