<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Children'sHome     06-15 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Children's Home,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welfare Commissioner Reports Threats Against Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi's welfare commissioner said
today he has moved his 13-year-old daughter out of state because of
kidnapping threats prompted by the state's closing of a Baptist
boarding school for troubled youngsters.
   The independent home was closed Friday amid allegations of child
abuse and neglect.
   Welfare Commissioner Thomas Brittain said he and his family have
been threatened, ``my daughter specifically, in terms of taking her
away to one of those homes.''
   He said there had been ``threats of kidnapping and putting her
in a home where she would never be found again.''
   The threats were made over the telephone, Brittain said. He
would not elaborate.
   Brittain's 21-year-old son, Thomas Brittain III, contacted at
the Brittains' home in Jackson, said his parents had moved his
sister, Brandi, out of state because of threats on her life.
   ``I'm big enough to take care of myself,'' the younger Brittain
said.
   On Friday, Youth Court Judge Robert Oswald ordered all residents
of the unlicensed Bethel Home for Children temporarily placed in
state custody. He ruled that the children, ages 10 to 17, had been
subjected ``to physical abuse, medical neglect and detention
amounting to imprisonment.''
   Before state welfare officials arrived, most of the children
fled. An estimated 60 still are missing. Since Friday, the state
has taken 77 other children from the home, releasing about 50 to
their parents so far.
   The state has required that parents or guardians wanting to
regain custody, must promise not to send the children back to
Bethel.
   The operator of the fundamentalist school, the Rev. Herman
Fountain, has been jailed on $40,000 bail on charges of scuffling
officers who tried to take custody of children.
   Diciplinary measures at the school have come under fire since
1980.
   Fountain, in an interview, said that no more than 10 licks with
a switch were allowed and that other punishments permitted were
running laps _ no more than 25 _ and making students write
sentences over and over on the blackboard.
   He said the investigation of the home was prompted by the
allegations of one runaway who claims he was abused. Fountain
added, ``He's a liar, and you'd know that too if you dealt with him
for five minutes.''
</TEXT>
