<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ContraAid 1stLd-Writethru a0461 06-15 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Meet with Congressional Leaders On Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: First 9 grafs new with White House meeting, Fitzwater quotes,
remarks from congressmen. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, House Speaker.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is weighing whether
to seek new U.S. military aid for the Nicaraguan Contra resistance
in the wake of collapsed peace talks with the Managua government, a
White House spokesman said today.
   Marlin Fitzwater told reporters the policy review includes
consultations with members of Congress and a fact-finding mission
to Central America by Max Kampelman, one of the administration's
key arms control negotiators.
   Fitzwater said the temporary reassignment of Kampelman to the
mission in Central America did not represent a downgrading of the
importance of negotiations on a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty
(START). Dispatching the veteran diplomat to El Salvador, Costa
Rica and Guatemala, he said, was done to get ``a fresh eye'' on the
problem.
   Fitzwater said that Reagan, in a meeting today with
congressional supporters of the Contras, expressed frustration that
the world was not being told enough about Sandinista excesses.
   ``The president said the Sandinistas want to talk about how to
lay down arms, but they do not want to talk about how to bring
democracy to Nicaragua,'' his spokesman said. ``He said they want
to talk about surrender but they do not want to talk about reform
and democracy.''
   ``The president listened to their various points of view. No
decisions were made. Everybody agreed that we need to be more
involved (in pushing the Contra cause),'' Fitzwater said of the
meeting. ``I can't say when we will have a decision.''
   Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., said he and other congressmen had
sought the meeting with Reagan out of a concern that the White
House had given up on the Contra issue after multiple setbacks
earlier this year in the House.
   ``It was necessary, I think, for some of us to point out that
with the Moscow summit and now the Toronto summit and a lot of
other things occupying the White House, that we thought it was
important that he keep the attention focused on Central America as
well,'' Edwards told reporters afterward. ``We have said that we
thought that more needed to be done to get leadership out of the
White House. ''
   Leaders of the Contra resistance were meeting with members of
Congress on Capitol Hill, meanwhile, to discuss the possibility of
a renewal of military aid for the rebels.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, issued a statement expressing
opposition to military assistance. House Republican leader Bob
Michel of Illinois, a longtime Contra supporter, indicated a
reluctance to renew the fight for military aid, suggesting that any
such proposal might face defeat.
   The failure of the peace talks produced vitriolic attacks by
Shultz against the Sandinistas on Tuesday and by Nicaraguan
Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann on ``extremist elements'' within the
Contras and the Reagan administration.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, blaming the Sandinistas for
the breakdown of the talks, said their actions have shown the world
``that their promises of democratization have no counterpart in
concrete action.
   ``Their consistent and apparent goal has been to disarm and
eliminate the resistance so that they can proceed to consolidate
their rule in Nicaragua,'' Shultz said after meeting at the State
Department with the Contra leaders.
   ``Their kind of rule in Nicaragua will never be accepted as
legitimate by the United States. We will stick with the resistance
freedom fighters. Their cause of peace with freedom is the right
cause.''
   It was not clear what Shultz meant when he raised questions
about the legitimacy of the Sandinista government, because the
United States has always been represented in Managua by an
ambassador since the start of the 1979 revolution.
   Tunnermann, in a letter to Wright, said the Contras on the final
day of the talks ``introduced an entirely new set of demands'' and
insisted that the Sandinistas accept them all within two hours.
   ``There can be little doubt that the sole purpose of the
Contras' last-minute maneuvering was to insist on demands so
outlandish and unacceptable that our negotiators would be forced to
reject them,'' Tunnermann said.
   Still, Tunnermann and the Contras both left the door open to a
resumption of the negotiations and Shultz also indicated support
for such a solution. A cease-fire agreed to in late March is still
being observed although each side has accused the other of
violating it.
   The rebels were dealt a setback last February 3 when the House
defeated a proposal by Reagan for additional military aid. U.S.
assistance is now limited to humanitarian aid.
   The Contras share the Reagan administration's view that the loss
of military aid has robbed the rebels of leverage in their
negotiations with the Sandinistas. But the administration is wary
of seeking a new congressional vote on military assistance until
there is some evidence that majority support can be obtained.
   Reagan discussed the issue with GOP congressional leaders on
Tuesday, but no decisions were reached. Contra leader Adolfo Calero
has called for a resumption of military aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
