<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MaineCongress     06-15 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maine Congress,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavily Financed L.L. Bean Heiress' Congressional Campaign Falters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.L. Bean heiress Linda Bean-Jones says
her decision to spend more than $500,000 seeking a Republican
congressional nomination may have backfired.
   Bean-Jones was defeated Tuesday by Edward S. O'Meara, an aide to
GOP Sen. William S. Cohen. Returns from 99 percent of the precincts
in southern Maine's 1st District showed O'Meara with 52 percent of
the vote and Bean-Jones, a businesswoman and conservative, with 48
percent.
   Bean-Jones, granddaughter of outdoors outfitter L.L. Bean, spent
more than $500,000 on her losing effort, more than $455,000 of it
from her own pocket. O'Meara, who credited his win to support by
Republican Party regulars, spent between $60,000 and $65,000, a
spokesman said.
   Bean-Jones said the spending gap became a dominant issue in the
campaign, and that her reliance on her wealth seemed to boomerang.
   ``That was the reason that a lot of people gave us as to why
they are supporting him,'' she said after conceding defeat.
Bean-Jones said voters ``are not very forgiving of heavy spending
in a campaign when it so outdistances a challenger.''
   O'Meara will face incumbent Democratic Rep. Joseph E. Brennan in
November. Brennan, a former two-term governor, was unopposed in his
party's primary.
</TEXT>
