<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--ComedieFrancaise     06-15 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Comedie Francaise,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Antoine Vitez Appointed Head of Comedie Francaise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minister of Culture Jack Lang on Wednesday named
Antoine Vitez to head the Comedie Francaise, France's premier
national theatre.
   Vitez, the 58-year-old former director of the national Chaillot
Theatre in Paris, replaces the former Comedie Francaise General
Administrator Jean Le Poulain, who died in March.
   In addition to running the Chaillot, Vitez, who speaks fluent
Russian and Italian, recently has directed productions of
``Tartuffe'' in Moscow and ``The Triumph of Love'' at the popular
Piccolo Teatro in Milan. He is known for his knowledge of classic
theatre, the speciality of the Comedie Francaise.
   Established in 1680 by the royal decree of Louis XIV, the
Comedie Francaise had the sole right to perform plays in French in
Paris until the French Revolution in 1789. It remains the nation's
great protector and promoter of French classics by playwrights such
as Moliere and and Racine.
</TEXT>
