<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-People'sDaily     06-15 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-People's Daily,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Paper Celebrates 40th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The People's Daily, the Communist Party
newspaper, celebrated its 40th birthday on Wednesday with
front-page tributes from top Chinese leaders, including party
General Secretary Zhao Ziyang.
   The paper has been the leading communicator of the party line
since its first edition was issued June 15, 1948.
   Its stolid gray pages have signaled to Chinese and the outside
world key developments such as the rise of the cult of Mao
Tse-tung, the start of the far leftist Cultural Revolution in 1966
and its end in 1976 with the arrest of Mao's wife, Jiang Qing, and
her fellow radicals.
   ``I hope you will enthusiastically and steadily carry out media
reform ... Constantly blazing new trails, and make the People's
Daily a paper that is warmly received by the masses,'' Zhao wrote
in a front-page-message.
   The anniversary edition carried a picture of the first edition's
front page with the lead headline: ``North China Liberated Area
Formally Organized.''
   One of the paper's most famous headlines appeared on June 1,
1966: ``Sweep Away All Ghosts And Monsters.'' The command,
appearing at the top of an editorial written by top government
officials, was one of the Cultural Revolution's first salvos
against alleged bourgeois and reactionary elements.
   A few days later, the People's Daily announced the dismissal of
Peng Zhen, head of the powerful Beijing Communist Party Committee,
signaling that rank would be no protection from attack in the
coming political storm.
   Recently the paper has conveyed official warnings that unity and
public order must be maintained if rapid economic development is to
be achieved.
   In the anniversary editorial, it reiterated that recent sharp
jumps in the prices of foodstuffs and other goods, which have
triggered widespread public discontent, are necessary to the
country's economic revitalization program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
