<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Sea-TacCrash     06-15 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sea-Tac Crash,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transcript Of Cockpit Exchanges Of Horizon Crew Released By NTSB</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Quotes from transcript are verbatim, including `(expletive
deleted)'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a Horizon Air plane that
crash-landed at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport in April had
no inkling of what was to come when one of the craft's engines
started to loose power 39 seconds after takeoff, according to a
transcript of cockpit exchanges released Wednesday.
   Nineteen of the 40 passengers aboard the de Haviland Dash 8
plane were injured. There were no fatalities.
   During the six minutes after takeoff, problems mounted as a fire
erupted in the commuter plane's right engine; lights that indicate
whether the landing gear was down failed, and three seconds after
touchdown the crew realized they had lost steering.
   ``I can't steer this (expletive deleted) at all,'' the pilot
said.
   ``We're out of control,'' the co-pilot notified the tower.
   ``Okay, hang on,'' the pilot said as the plane careened down the
runway narrowly missing the control tower.
   The plane crashed through baggage carts as it headed for the
terminal.
   ``Okay hit the brakes we're gunna' hit this (expletive deleted)
here,'' the pilot said. ``We're gonna do okay here hang on.''
   The next sound on the tape was of the impact as the plane
slammed into a boarding ramp where only 10 minutes earlier another
flight had departed.
   Within 15 seconds, the fire was extinguished by waiting
emergency crews.
   The National Transportation Safety Board, which is investigating
the accident, released the transcript of exchanges between the crew
and with the control tower.
   Release of the actual tape from the cockpit voice recorder, one
of two so-called black boxes planes carry, is prohibited under
federal law, said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a NTSB spokesman.
   Lopatkiewicz said the transcript was a ``factual report released
without comment. We are not analyzing anything yet.''
   The NTSB will probably finish its report early next year, he
said.
   Information from the other black box on board the Horizon plane,
the flight data recorder which monitors such things as airspeed and
compass heading, is also being reviewed, Lopatkiewicz said.
</TEXT>
