<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FALN     06-15 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FALN,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Jailed in Inquiry of Puerto Rican Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advocate for Puerto Rican independence
surrendered Wednesday to serve a jail term for refusing to appear
before a federal grand jury investigating the Puerto Rican
separatist group FALN.
   Nelson Ramirez, 28, a technician with the Emergency Medical
Service, reported to the U.S. marshal's office in Brooklyn as
ordered by a judge last week.
   About 30 protesters, many waving Puerto Rican flags, gathered
outside the courthouse and followed him in chanting, ``Free Puerto
Rico Now,'' and other slogans.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Platt found Ramirez in civil contempt
for refusing to answer a subpoena that would compel him to appear
before the grand jury and to give hand and voice prints.
   Platt ordered that Ramirez be jailed for the life of the grand
jury, which could be 15 months. The judge allowed him a week to
make arrangements for his pregnant wife.
   ``Today I'm stronger than I was last week and I expect to be
stronger when I get out,'' Ramirez said before his surrender.
   His attorney, Colleen McGuire, has said she was told by federal
officials that the grand jury was investigating a series of
terrorist bombings in New York City on New Year's Eve 1982 that
were blamed on FALN.
   FALN, whose full name is Spanish for Armed Forces of National
Liberation, advocates independence for the U.S. commonwealth of
Puerto Rico. The group has taken responsibility for more than 150
bombings in American cities from 1975 to 1984.
   Ramirez, of Manhattan, said he has not been politically active
for at least four years, but had previously been president of a
Puerto Rican student association at Hunter College and a member in
nationalist movement groups.
</TEXT>
