<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     06-15 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Radicals Fight Police In Protest Against Military Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students shouting
``Boycott military training!'' hurled rocks and firebombs Wednesday
at riot police who moved in to break up the protest. No serious
injuries were reported.
   The protest at Chungang University in Seoul turned violent when
hundreds of riot police marched on campus and fired tear gas to
disperse about 1,000 students from five Seoul colleges.
   Waves of masked students immediately dashed out and pelted
troopers with rocks and scores of flaming gasoline bombs. Female
students beat drums and carried rocks to encourage the protesters.
   A number of students and policemen were hit by rocks and other
objects, but no serious injuries were reported.
   Fighting started when students were preparing to march into the
street and continued for several hours, as students shouted ``Drive
out Yankees who hinder unification!''
   The students demanded an end to compulsory military training for
college students, denouncing the government of President Roh
Tae-woo and the United States. They contend military training for
students was ``preparation of machinery for the Yankees.''
   All male college students in South Korea are required to undergo
weekly military training on campus, along with an weeklong training
session at military barracks.
   Student speakers at a rally before the clash also demanded the
expulsion of the 42,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea under
a mutual defense pact, accusing the United States of hindering
unification of the Korean peninsula.
   Radical students want immediate reunification of the two Koreas,
divided since the end of World War II. They contend the United
States enforces partition of the peninsula to rule the South as a
colony.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority on college campuses,
have failed to attract public support.
   Major street clashes occurred in Seoul on Friday when riot
police blocked thousands of radical students trying to march to the
border for talks with North Kroean students. The two Koreas remain
bitter enemies since the Communist North invaded the South in 1950
and started the three-year Korean War.
   On Wednesday, minor clashes were reported from the central city
of Taejon, when students demonstrated off campus to protest a
government ban on last week's march to the North Korean border.
   About 10 radical students staged a dawn attack with firebombs
Wednesday on an office of the government party in Seoul, police
said. The firebombs missed and caused no damage.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent anti-government
and anti-U.S. protests in the past months. Police said Wednesday
that so far this year, they fired more than 270,000 rounds of tear
gas to block demonstrations.
</TEXT>
