<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0601 06-15 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Concerned About North Korea Threatening Summer Games</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, Shultz described, to include Japan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz,
registering concern about terrorism at the Olympics, said today
that North Korea has placed Soviet surface-to-air missiles within
range of Seoul where the Summer Games will be held.
   Shultz said he had received assurances from Soviet leaders that
``they feel certain there won't be any terrorist acts'' by their
North Korean allies.
   ``I have no reason to doubt the sincerity of that statement,''
Shultz said.
   But he said North Koreans ``are people you have to keep your eye
on, and we will do so.''
   Shultz made the remarks on the U.S. Information Agency
television program ``Worldnet.''
   He said the missiles had been installed near the demilitarized
zone and ``have a range that can go over the Seoul area.''
   Shultz said North Korean terrorists arranged the murder of half
of South Korea's cabinet ministers on a visit to Rangoon, Burma,
several years ago and also placed a bomb aboard a South Korean
airliner.
   ``Certain facts are disturbing,'' he said.
   Shultz said he expected the leaders of the seven Western
countries to discuss joint measures to combat terrorism at their
meeting next week in Toronto.
   As a result of a united stand, Shultz said, terrorism in Western
Europe is declining.
   He said the seven leaders may agree on a proposal that all
governments refuse to refuel hijacked planes that have landed on
their territory with hostages aboard.
   ``It's a specific thing that if given broad endorsement might be
helpful,'' Shultz said.
   On another subject, the secretary dismissed the idea of a
Marshall plan to provide economic assistance to eastern Europe.
``The countries are very different from each other, and they have
to be thought of country by country.''
   He said the eastern Europeans should be approached
``one-by-one'' to develop trade and other ties with the West ``as
they seek to open themselves up.''
   Shultz described President Reagan's participation in the Toronto
summit meeting as ``a kind of valedictory'' since it will be his
last meeting with the leaders of Canada, Britain, France, Italy,
West Germany and Japan before leaving office in January.
   Shultz said the economic picture had brightened considerably
since the last summit in Canada in 1981, with inflation way down,
taxes reduced and growth and incentives increased.
   Free enterprise is ``catching on'' and ``we're going to wind up
better off,'' Shultz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Military     06-15 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Military,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Says Its Military Strength Is Growing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea will be able to ensure its
own defense and overcome the military superiority of communist
North Korea by the turn of the century, officials said Wednesday.
   Opposition leaders received the assessment in a briefing at the
Defense Ministry on the nation's armed forces and the threat from
the communist north.
   In a related development, North Korea on Wednesday denied South
Korean and U.S. allegations that it has deployed Soviet-made SA-5
missiles along the Korean demilitarized zone. The North Korean
armed forces, in a statement broadcast by the official Radio
Pyongyang and monitored in Tokyo, termed the allegations
``unfounded, fabricated slander.''
   The 1988 Summer Olympic Games will be held in Seoul Sept.
17-Oct. 2. South Korean and U.S. officials fear that North Korea,
which has unsuccessfully demanded to co-host the Games, may
sabotage events.
   Defense officials in Seoul said on Wednesday that South Korea's
armed forces were making substantial progress.
   ``We would complete preparations for a fully independent defense
around 2000 if the current military buildup continued,'' an
official told Kim Dae-jung, Kim Young-sam and 60 other opposition
leaders.
   Ministry officials urged the opposition leaders to help ensure
the nation's independent defense posture. They said South Korea has
greatly expanded its forces through mass domestic production of
tanks and fighters.
   South Korea is strengthening early warning systems and war
preparedness with superior naval and air strategies to counter
possible threats from the North, officials said.
   The two Koreas, divided since 1945, are bitter opponents. The
North invaded the South in 1950 to start the Korean War and the two
nations maintain huge military forces in a state of frequent
tension along the border.
   Ministry officials said Wednesday that North Korea continued to
build up its armed forces, including a 96,000 member special attack
force.
   The ministry charged that the North had completed deployment of
most of its combat forces close to the border in combat positions.
They said 65 percent of the North's ground forces, 41 percent of
its fighters and 57 percent of its naval craft were deployed in
forward positions.
   The United States has 42,000 troops based in the South under a
mutual defense pact to help defend against possible threats from
the North.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and his South Korean
counterpart Oh Ja-bok closed the U.S.-South Korea Security
Consultative Meeting in Seoul on June 9 with a joint statement
saying North Korea's offensive-oriented military developments and
its strengthened surprise attack capability pose a serious threat
to South Korea.
   Carlucci and Oh also said they discussed North Korea's enhanced
offensive posture, including its recent deployment of advanced SA-5
missiles capable of striking the South Korean capital of Seoul.
   The North Korean statement Wednesday said: ``In building up arms
and increasing tensions, while slandering us under the pretext of
the Olympic Games, the U.S. imperialists ... seek to light the fuse
of a war of aggression against us.''
</TEXT>
