<DOCNO> AP880615-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     06-15 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Demos Plan Trade Bill Minus Plant-Closings Provision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats moved to breathe new life into their
vetoed trade bill Wednesday by splitting off a provision that would
require large companies to notify employees of plant closings and
major layoffs.
   ``The bottom line is that we're now going to have a trade bill
without a plant-closings provision,'' House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, told reporters.
   He said the House would repackage the plant-closings plan as
separate legislation and act on it before taking up the newly
refurbished version of its 1,000-page trade bill.
   He also said the plan envisions dropping Alaskan oil provisions
that would have capped exports from the state's new refineries at
70,000 barrels a day and 50 percent of output while requiring
Canadian-bound crude shipments to detour first to ports in the
lower 48 states.
   President Reagan was critical of both the plant-closings and the
oil provisions in his May 24 veto of the trade bill. The House
subsequently voted to pass the measure notwithstanding his
objections but the Senate on June 8 fell short of the two-thirds
needed for a presidential veto override.
   At the core of the bill are provisions to overhaul the system
under which the United States imposes import curbs to protect U.S.
industries and retaliate against international trade violations. It
also would grant the administration authority to make deals in
current global trade talks.
   The bill required companies with 100 or more employees to give
60 days notice of plant closings or large-scale layoffs.
   Other provisions range from substantial agricultural subsidies
to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies.
   Senate Democrats have been saying they would seek to attach the
plant-closings provision to any refurbished trade bill sent from
the House.
   There was no immediate word on whether they would go foward with
that plan or instead redirect their efforts into the separate
plant-closings bill.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., has been warning
that any new legislation was likely to become badly bogged down.
   Some of the administration's supporters in the Senate, however,
have been eager for another crack at the trade issue before
lawmakers adjourn to hit the campaign trail.
   Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter earlier called for swift
congressional action on a more moderate version of trade
legislation. And Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., has been
suggesting that he might sponsor trade legislation of his own.
   ``We're working on it,'' Dole said Wednesday. He said it was
necessary to ``get the ethanol provision out of it, otherwise
there's not going to be a trade bill.''
   One provision criticized by Reagan would permit duty-free
imports of ethanol from the Caribbean, a measure hotly opposed by
Midwest corn growers.
   AFL-CIO and other labor representatives who have been
campaigning for the plant-closings provision for 15 years
buttonholed Democratic leaders in a hallway adjacent to the House
chamber Wednesday morning.
   At one point, Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., emerged from the
House chamber, where the Democratic Caucus was meeting, in an
apparent effort to smooth any ruffled feathers. They later were
ushered into Wright's office.
   Wright told reporters he would bring the new, free-standing
version of the plant-closings legislation to the House floor prior
to action on the refurbished trade bill. He said there was a good
chance a veto of the plant-closings plan could be overridden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
