<1ST_LINE>u a PM-StrandedBarges     06-15 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stranded Barges,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Water Strands 750 Barges on Mspi River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 750 barges were backed up on the
Mississippi River near here today because of low water, and the
Army Corps of Engineers said twice as many could be stranded by the
weekend.
   The barges began backing up after one ran aground Monday and
others decided to wait for a dredge to arrive Thursday to deepen
the channel.
   ``They are skittish about using it because one mess-up costs
lots of dollars,'' said Michael Logue, spokesman for the corps'
Vicksburg District.
   The river is only 9 feet deep near Vaucluse Landing, Ark., about
3 miles north of the Greenville bridge.
   Logue said about 750 barges were backed up today and that the
number would probably double during the dredging, which is expected
to take a day or two.
   ``When the dredge gets in and begins working, it's likely we
will have to stop traffic off and on. This will back up normal
traffic.'' he said.
   Logue said the barges ``could be carrying anything _ just like
an interstate highway. It could be coal, grain, steel, chemicals,
petroleum products or military cargo. They do not normally carry
perishables.''
   He said Army engineers had no estimate of cargo value involved
in river shipping by the scores of barge lines that operate on the
Mississippi.
   Ron Goldman, chief of water control management for the Vicksburg
District, said the Mississippi is at its lowest point for this time
of year since records were first kept in 1872.
   He said the Vicksburg gauge read 2.5 feet on Tuesday. The lowest
level on record is minus 7 feet in February 1940, when much of the
upper river froze solid.
   Without significant rainfall, the river will fall below zero on
the Vicksburg gauge within two weeks, Goldman said, with zero on
the gauge representing 46.2 feet above mean sea level.
   Louis Logue, chief of river operations for the corps' Vicksburg
District and Michael Logue's brother, said dozens of other trouble
spots could develop if the river falls as expected.
   ``I'm talking seriously with the Lord about this now,'' he said.
``Up until now I've just been talking regularly.''
</TEXT>
