<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Energy-WaterMoney     06-15 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Energy-Water Money,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Super Collider Go-Ahead Should Be Left Up to Next President,
Senate Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Wednesday joined the House in
decreeing that the decision on whether to build the superconducting
super collider should be made by the next president.
   The Senate took the position as it voted 92-5 for its first
major fiscal 1989 appropriations bill, a $18.05 billion package to
finance energy and water development programs in the year beginning
next Oct. 1.
   The bill totals nearly $300 million more than what the House has
approved for the Army Corps of Engineers, the Bureau of Reclamation
and research activities by the Energy Department.
   Negotiators from both chambers will have to work out differences
in the two bills, which failed to grant an administration request
for more than $350 million to begin construction of the
superconducting super collider, envisioned as the world's most
powerful atom smasher.
   Backers of the proposed multibillion-dollar high-energy physics
project say it could carry the nation to new scientific frontiers.
   Both bills provide $100 million to continue early research on
the super collider, but both specifically forbid any spending to
start building the facility, which could cost $5.4 billion or more.
   Appropriations committee leaders on both sides of the Capitol
have said they want the next president to review the project and
decide whether to seek congressional approval to build it at a
yet-unspecified site.
   Supporters of the super collider say it is vital if this country
is to be competitive with other nations in the area of basic
science and technology. Opponents argue that the facility could eat
up money needed by other areas of science.
   Managers of the bills have agreed that in a time of tight money
and huge budget deficits, there is no money next year for the corps
and the bureau to start construction of new water projects.
   Both bills do contain funds to continue construction work on
dozens of dams, harbors and irrigation systems and to operate and
maintain hundreds of completed water projects.
   Nearly half the money in both bills, or $8 billion, is earmarked
for the Energy Department for defense-related nuclear activities.
   On Tuesday, the Senate approved its first fiscal 1989 spending
bill, a $1.7 million package to finance Congress next year.
</TEXT>
