<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peru-RebelAttack 2ndLd-Writethru a0687 06-15 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Rebel Attack, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0687,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Two Agronomists Working On US-Funded Project</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3th graf pvs, ``The U.S. ...'' and 7th graf pvs, ``The
U.S. ...'' to CLARIFY victims were not U.S. AID workers but working
under contract for U.S. project</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist rebels shot and killed an American
agronomist and a Peruvian colleague after dragging them from their
pickup truck on an isolated road, government officials said today.
   The attack Monday night was the second killing of an American in
the 8-year-old Shining Path guerrilla insurgency. Last week,
pro-Cuba guerrillas in Lima lobbed three mortar rounds at the
residence of the U.S. ambassador, causing minor damage but no
injuries.
   The U.S. Embassy said two agronomists working for a U.S.-funded
agricultural development project were reported ambushed and killed
near Huancayo, a city 125 miles east of Lima. The embassy declined
to confirm their identities or nationalities.
   The National Agrarian Research Institute said the victims were
Constantin Gregori of the United States and Gustavo Rojas, a
Peruvian.
   Institute spokesman Javier Recuenco said the men were en route
from Aramachay, 15 miles north of Huancayo, to buy supplies in the
town of Sincos when the attack occurred.
   Huancayo police said Gregori, 38, and Rojas, 35, were pulled
from their vehicle and killed with two gunshots to the head after
their identification papers were checked.
   The U.S. Embassy said the victims worked with the institute in a
program funded by the U.S. Agency for International Development. A
spokesman said they taught peasant farmers how to improve
production of sheep and small farm animals.
   The two men lived in Aramachay, Recuenco said.
   The Shining Path previously has assassinated development workers
in Peru's impoverished highlands in an effort to create economic
chaos.
   The Shining Path insurgency has claimed 10,000 lives. The other
American to die in the guerrilla war was a Texas woman who was
among seven passengers killed when rebels bombed a train heading
for the Inca ruins of Machu Picchu in 1986.
</TEXT>
