<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Strike,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Bus Strike Reported in Northeastern Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bus drivers in a northeastern Polish city
staged a wage strike Wednesday, the government said. It was the
first confirmed work stoppage in Poland since a wave of labor
unrest in May.
   A government spokesman, Ryszard Strauss, said the strike idled
part of the Lomza's transit system. But the strike was settled by
the end of the day, a man answering the phone at the transit
offices said.
   News of the settlement was not immediately confirmed by the
government.
   The city is 90 miles northeast of Warsaw and has 51,000
residents.
   ``The matter has been settled and there is nothing going on,''
said the man at the transit offices, who would not give his name.
``We achieved an agreement satisfying both sides.'' He gave no
further details.
   Strauss said the demands involved basic pay and overtime and
some ``social privileges'' such as lowering of retirement age.
   He said he did not know how many strikers there were, or detail
how much the strikers made or how much more they were demanding.
   Five strikes involving thousands of workers took place in Poland
between April 25 and May 10 in the worst outbreak of labor unrest
since the 1981 imposition of martial law and suppression of the
Solidarity trade union.
</TEXT>
