<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Murphy     06-15 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murphy,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Official to Visit Gulf Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard W. Murphy, the State Department's top
Middle East policymaker, will begin a trip to Iraq and other
Persian Gulf nations this week to discuss regional peace efforts,
the department announced Wednesday.
   Besides Iraq, which has been fighting a war with Iran since
1981, Murphy will visit Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait, Bahrain,
the United Arab Emirates and North Yemen, department spokesman
Charles E. Redman said.
   Murphy is assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern affairs.
   ``His visit to these states is part of the close consultative
process we have with them,'' Redman said. ``He'll be exchanging
views on a number of bilateral and regional issues. Obviously,
among others, this would include subjects like our continuing
efforts to launch a Mideast peace process and the Iran-Iraq war.''
   Redman said the trip would begin this week, but he gave no
dates, in keeping with a longstanding policy of limiting
information about official travel to the volatile Middle East.
   The United States has been seeking an end to the 7-year-old
Iran-Iraq war through diplomacy, notably an effort to get the
United Nations to impose an arms embargo against Iran. The Soviet
Union and China have blocked implemenation of the weapons ban.
   The United States is also using its naval forces to protect
shipping in the Persian Gulf and has proposed the sale of arms to
Kuwait and other oil-rich countries seeking sophisticated weapons
for defense against spillover attacks.
</TEXT>
