<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Baker-Veep 1stLd-Writethru a0653 06-15 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baker-Veep, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Howard Baker On The Veep Short List _ Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 17th graf to restore dropped letter in `poster' bgng ``He
has...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``I do not expect that, I do not want that,
and I have signaled ... that I do not want that to happen,'' said
Howard H. Baker Jr.
   Baker was talking about the possibility of his being offered the
Republican vice presidential nomination.
   He was talking about it in 1980.
   Cut to 1988. Baker, the outgoing White House chief of staff, is
asked the same question.
   ``It's really something that is presumptuous in the extreme to
say, `No, I would not do that,''' Baker said Tuesday. ``But I do
not want to do that, I do not expect to do that, and I think it's
extremely unlikely I would be asked to do that.''
   For 20 years, the name of the former GOP Senate leader from
Tennessee has cropped up as a contender for the paty's national
ticket.
   ``The poor guy's been dragged through this more than any human
should take, but maybe the eighth time's a charm, or however many
it's been,'' says former White House political director Mitchell
Daniels Jr., a long-time Baker fan.
   Others say Baker does not appear to be a leading contender to be
Vice President George Bush's running mate.
   ``I think they could do a whole lot worse than Howard Baker, but
I have not heard a lot of speculation about it, and I don't see his
name often mentioned,'' said Howard Liebengood, a key Senate staff
member when Baker was majority leader.
   Baker, 62, recalled recently that the first time he was
mentioned as a possible running mate was in 1968, the year Richard
Nixon chose Spiro Agnew. That was just two years after Baker's
election to the Senate.
   The Tennessee senator moved into the national spotlight during
the Senate Watergate hearings, asking over and over, ``What did the
president know and when did he know it?''
   In 1976, he was on then President Gerald R. Ford's list of
potential running mates, but was passed over in favor of Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole. Baker supporters blamed his loss on publicity
following disclosure that Baker's wife, Joy, had been hospitalized
for a drinking problem five years earlier.
   Baker became Senate minority leader in 1977 and ran for the GOP
presidential nomination from that post in 1980, bowing out after
faring poorly in early primaries. That year's Republican landslide
made him majority leader, but he retired from the Senate in 1984
and set his sights on a bid for the presidency this year. He put
that aside when President Reagan asked him to replace Donald T.
Regan as chief of staff at the height of the Iran-Contra crisis in
February 1987.
   Baker's supporters say his assets as a running mate include his
national stature, his Southern political base and his appeal to
independent voters.
   ``He has always been an attractive figure among Democrats and
independents, where the vice president needs to make real gains,''
said Daniels.
   Possible liabilities include conservative resentment over his
moderate record in the Senate, especially his support of the Panama
Canal treaties.
   ``He has always been sort of the poster child villain of the
Panama Canal treaty debate with certain elements on the right,''
said Liebengood. ``I would hope he has lived some of that down in
their eyes, but you never know.''
   Baker's tenure as White House chief of staff could bolster his
credentials with conservatives but hurt his chances among those who
argue Bush should assert his independence from the Reagan
administration.
   ``It cuts both ways,'' said Tom Korologos, a former White House
aide with strong Republican ties. ``It's more of a plus, except
there will be the naysayers who say, `You're not independent
enough.'''
   Baker has stopped short of saying he would not take the
nomination if offered. ``You don't turn down requests of that sort
if they are made,'' Baker said Tuesday.
   Said Daniels: ``As the race continues to come more and more into
focus, some very worthy candidates make less sense and some make
more, and he is one that I think makes very good sense.''
</TEXT>
