<2ND_LINE>AM-ND Lottery, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0669,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Dakotans Turn Down Lottery For Second Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with final unofficial vote totals; picks up 4th
graf pvs: ``King also ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a North Dakota lottery said
Wednesday the issue will probably be put to voters again in
November, despite its second rejection at the polls in 18 months.
   ``There's a very good chance we'll do it again,'' retired
businessman Gorman King Sr. said after voters turned thumbs down
Tuesday on a proposed amendment to the state constitution.
   Final unofficial totals showed the lottery measure had failed
61,082 votes, or 58 percent, to 44,043 votes, or 42 percent.
   King also was the driving force behind a November 1986 lottery
initiative, which failed 55 percent to 45 percent.
   North Dakota already had the distinction of being the only state
to reject a state-run lottery at the polls, according to the
National Conference of State Legislatures.
   Former Gov. Arthur Link, an outspoken foe of all forms of
gaming, said he hoped King would abide by the voters' judgment and
drop his crusade.
   ``It would seem to me a decisive expression of the will of the
people, and I would hope that the proponents would accept the
decision of the voters of North Dakota,'' Link said.
   Link was joined by religious groups and North Dakota charitable
gaming organizations, which feared a lottery would cut into their
gambling take.
   King's most recent lottery initiative called for channeling
lottery profits into the state general fund. He expected the North
Dakota game to gross $20 million in its first year, with $7 million
going to the state.
   Twenty-six states _ including neighboring South Dakota and
Montana _ operate lotteries, as does the District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
