<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drug-FreeWorkplace     06-15 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug-Free Workplace,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OMB Chief Voices Reservations About Draft Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James C. Miller II, director of the Office of
Management and Budget, said Wednesday that responsible employees
are threatened by having to work with and depend upon co-workers
who may be impaired by use of illegal drugs.
   Miller also told a House subcommittee that customers, including
the federal government, ``should not have to wonder whether the
products they purchase will fail because the workers putting them
together were high on drugs.''
   Testifying before the House Government Operations legislation
and national security subcommittee, Miller said the Reagan
administration supports efforts to create a drug-free workplace but
has reservations about legislation before Congress, including a
bill by the panel's chairman, Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas.
   The Brooks bill would require federal contractors and grantees
to establish a drug-free workplace policy, require employees to
observe that policy and would provide sanctions when that policy
fails and drug abuse in the workplace occurs. The sanctions, which
would be applied under due process requirements, include future
disbarment of contractors who are frequent violators.
   Miller said he particularly opposed parts of the Brooks bill
which calls for employers and employees to certify that they are
complying with the law, an action he said would require ``extensive
new paperwork burdens.''
   A measure by Rep. Robert S. Walker, R-Pa., would require
debarment if one employee is convicted of using illegal drugs. Dale
E. Kildee, D-Mich., would deprive a grantee or contractor of
federal contracts and grants if the company fails to make a
good-faith effort to keep a drug-free workplace.
   Miller said he would like to see one measure emerge from the
several before Congress but that the program ``be flexible enough
to permit departments and agencies to address the problems they
face in the most effective way.''
   He suggested that, instead of being specific, Congress should
take a broader approach in enacting the law. OMB could issue
guidelines for each of the departments and agencies to use in
promulgating regulations.
</TEXT>
