<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-WorldBank     06-15 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-World Bank</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Warns US May Lose Veto In World Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III told
Congress on Wednesday that the United States will lose its veto
over major decisions of the World Bank unless it puts up $70
million to join in increasing the bank's capital.
   ``I think it would be absolutely catastrophic if we withheld our
cooperation and lost the veto right that now exists,'' he said at a
hearing of the House Banking Committee.
   He argued that the World Bank, the largest source of aid to the
Third World, helps countries like Argentina and Mexico which are
important to U.S. national security but get no direct aid from the
United States.
   The U.S. veto right affects only major changes in the bank,
which is owned by 151 countries. The United States has the largest
voting strength, about 15 percent. This would be diluted if it
failed to take up the shares allotted to it in the current general
increase of its capital, which is already 79 percent susbcribed.
   Baker said only 11 countries have so far failed to take up their
shares, including the United States. Among them are Libya, Cambodia
and Vietnam.
   One World Bank official, spokesman Peter Riddleberger, has
suggested that Japan could became the largest single stockholder.
That would force the bank to shift its headquarters to Tokyo after
44 years in Washington.
   The U.S. veto does not apply to individual loans, which total
$17 billion a year. The increased capital will enable it to loan
well over $20 billion annually in the 1990s.
   Baker said the United States has opposed individual loans to
some members of the bank that have communist governments. In some
cases the United States was outvoted. In others, the U.S.
representative supported loans to Yugoslavia, Poland and Hungary
but not in the past three years, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
