<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraSuit     06-15 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Suit,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magistrate Recommends Jail For Mercenary Witness</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate recommended jail for a former
mercenary who refused to answer questions in a $24 million lawsuit
that claims former CIA officials and Contra leaders ran a
guns-for-drugs smuggling ring.
   Sam Hall has refused to answer questions during depositions
about who trained and paid him in Nicaragua. The suit is set for
trial June 27.
   Hall, who was kicked out of Nicaragua after officials there said
he had been caught spying for the Contras, appeared Wednesday
without his attorney before U.S. Magistrate William Turnoff to
answer contempt charges.
   ``I know what's facing me,'' said Hall. ``But it has to do with
principle.''
   He said he would not answer questions that might embarrass
anti-communist crusader and former Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub, his
boss while he was in Nicaragua, although he said their activities
were not illegal.
   The suit was filed by journalist Tony Avirgan, who was injured
in a 1984 bombing in Nicaragua that he blames on the alleged
conspirators. He and his wife Martha Honey are represented by the
Washington-based Christic Institute, which Hall called a left-wing
organization.
   The magistrate said he respected Hall's position, but that he
must answer the questions.
   ``There really is no alternative for me but to make a
recommendation that you are held in civil contempt,'' said Turnoff.
He said Hall could be released any time he agrees to cooperate.
   ``You hold the keys to the jail,'' said the magistrate.
   Turnoff will make his recommendation to the presiding judge in
the case, Chief U.S. District Judge James L. King.
   The damage and racketeering suit charges that members of a
right-wing terror network tracing back to 1959 participated in
assassination plots, gun running and drug trafficking.
   Defendants include Singlaub; Theodore Shackley, former deputy
director of operations for the CIA; Contra director Adolfo Calero;
Medellin Cartel leaders Pablo Escobar Gaviria and Jorge Ochoa
Vasquez; Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord, Robert Owen and Albert
Hakim, and others.
   The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the
Iran-Contra affair became public. Many of those the suit brought to
light have since been indicted or appeared before congressional
committees investigating the Contra case.
   Avirgan and Honey accuse the defendants of funding illegal
Contra activities with drug runs in cooperation with the Medellin
Cartel, and threatening, imprisoning and even killing anyone who
might expose the ring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
