<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuneralHome     06-15 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Funeral Home,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass Funeral for 13 Decomposing Bodies Slated for Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mass funeral was scheduled Friday
for 13 of the 44 decomposing bodies found last week at funeral home
closed by state regulators after they found the corpses stacked in
a closet.
   In addition to the 44 bodies, 26 boxes of cremated remains were
found at the Howell Morning Glory Funeral Chapel, officials said.
   The Medical Examiner's Office on Tuesday turned over remains to
the Hardage-Giddens Funeral Homes for the mass funeral. The names
of the dead have not been released because next of kin are still
being notified, said Ronald L. Giddens, executive vice president of
Hardage-Giddens.
   State inspectors found eight decomposing bodies in a routine
check of the Howell mortuary June 6. They received permission from
the owner, Lewis J. Howell, to search the funeral home and
discovered the other bodies, many stacked in a closet.
   Although some of the remains were recent, a death certificate
showed one body had been dead since July 1978, said Dr. Peter
Lipkovic, the city medical examiner.
   Since 1979, Howell received $200,749 for burial and cremation of
indigents, receiving $400 for each adult burial and $100 for
cremation.
   It was not known however, if the decomposing remains belonged to
indigents. On Tuesday, Virgil Green, director of Jacksonville's
Welfare Division, said a member of his staff witnessed all indigent
services _ 62 burials and three cremations this year, and about 70
burials last year.
   The Florida Times-Union quoted Howell last week as saying it was
paperwork, not money problems, that caused the delay in burials.
Repeated calls to Howell's home and the mortuary for additional
comment have gone unanswered.
   Meanwhile, city accounting records show that several thousand
dollars in city funds meant to cover the costs of indigent burials
and cremations were paid directly to the Small Business
Administration to help Howell repay a loan. Howell had apparently
defaulted on the loan, and in 1984 the city paid $5,000 to the SBA
in exchange for Howell's burying 10 bodies in August and September
of that year, said Louise Squayars, who manages the payable
accounts for the city Finance Department.
   Riverside Memorial Park Cemetery, which is owned by Service
Corp. International, the parent firm of Hardage-Giddens, has agreed
to donate up to 37 burial plots, Giddens said. Giddens said
Hardage-Giddens will get $400 for each burial.
</TEXT>
