<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MysteriousBoy     06-15 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mysterious Boy,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Woman Claims To Be Grandmother Of Mystery Boy In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French woman has told officials in Paris she is
the grandmother of a deaf boy whom American and Mexican authorities
have been trying to identify for more than six months, the U.S.
Embassy said Wednesday.
   Christopher English, chief of special consular services at the
embassy, said he was contacted Tuesday by a woman from a village in
the Normandy region who saw a picture of the boy on the television
news and recognized him.
   ``She called and calmly said she had reason to believe that she
was the boy's grandmother,'' English said.
   Authorities found the freckled, brown-haired boy, named Sabat by
his Mexican guardians, wandering near Juarez, Mexico, in November.
He had scars that looked about two years old and could have come
from home-treated injuries.
   He was unable to identify himself to authorities or say where he
was from.
   Sabat suffers from impaired hearing and communicates mostly by
drawing pictures and gesturing. His pictures seem to indicate he
survived the crash of a four-seat, single-engine airplane that
killed his parents and sister.
   After Mexican authorities noticed Sabat preferred hamburgers and
hot dogs over Mexican fare and responded more enthusiastically to
American cartoon characters, they contacted their Texas
counterparts.
   The story has received international media attention and
pictures of the boy have circulated in France, England, Mexico and
the United States.
   English said the French woman, who asked him not to release her
name until the child's identification is confirmed, provided the
address and telephone number for her son who lives in El Paso, not
far from where the boy was found.
   She said she had not spoken to her son for several months and
the telephone apparently was disconnected, said English who added
the son also is French.
   English said he called Terry Kincaid of the FBI in El Paso, who
checked out the address early Wednesday and found out the family
had moved in August 1987. They had also left the second address
without leaving a forward address.
   ``It is getting murkier and murkier,'' English said, adding that
the FBI was continuing to search for the family.
   The woman said her son was married to a Mexican woman and the
couple had three children. She had not seen them for several years.
She did not know whether the couple had American citizenship or
anything about their legal status in the United States.
   The woman's daughter, who lives in Paris, also recognized the
boy from pictures on the news, English said. He said the daughter
gave family snapshots of the boy to the embassy Wednesday which
would be forwarded to the FBI.
   Texas officials have said the boy is 7 or 8 years old. The
French woman said he was close to 12.
   English said that since news of the French woman's claims were
released his office had been deluged by phone calls from reporters
around the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
