<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ParkService     06-15 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Park Service,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houes Panel Approves Bill Requiring Senate Confirmation of Parks
Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee approved
legislation Wednesday to strip top political appointees in the
Interior Department of day-to-day control over the National Park
Service.
   The bill, reflecting increasing displeasure among committee
Democrats with the Reagan administration's handling of the national
parks, was cleared for floor action by a 25-14 partyline vote.
   The legislation would make the park service director a
presidential appointee, subject to Senate confirmation. A director
would serve a five-year term, could be removed only by cause and
would have to be knowledgable about managing natural and cultural
resources.
   Currently, the director is appointed by the interior secretary,
serves at the secretary's pleasure and is directly answerable to
the assistant secretary for fish and wildlife and parks. Both are
political appointees.
   The plan's principal advocate, Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., said
the move would elevate the stature of the service's director,
putting that official on a more equal footing with the current
supervisors.
   The bill also would create a three-member park system review
board appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate. The
board would advise the director and Congress on how to improve the
park system.
   Budgeting for national parks would continue to be done through
the Interior Department, but the park service director would have
more direct access to the White House and Congress, according to
advocates of the changes.
   Vento says the changes are needed to counter years of
encroachment on park service professionals by political appointees
in Democratic and Republican administrations.
   But a background statement on the bill by Vento's national parks
and public lands subcommittee cited activities during the Reagan
administration as reasons why the legislation should be enacted.
The reasons included:
   _``Political appointees were substituted for professionals at
various levels and at different times, including the deputy
director'' of the park service.
   _``The assistant secretary's office changed performance ratings
of professional employees for political reasons.''
   _``The assistant secretary's office forced the resignation of
one regional director and forced the demotion of another for
political reasons.''
   _Park service ``personnel appearing before House committees
present testimony written by low-level political appointees in the
assistant secretary's office that rarely reflects the professional
views of the park service.''
   Vento said the situation has reached the point that park service
director William Penn Mott is not allowed to use the word
``threats'' in discussing problems faced by units of the park
system.
   The Interior Department opposes the bill, noting that the
Justice Department considers it an unconstitutional infringement on
the separation of executive and legislative branch powers.
   ``This bill is not going to go anywhere,'' said Rep. Don Young
of Alaska, the ranking Republican on the Interior Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Democrats-Platform     06-15 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Democrats-Platform,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Committee To Meet June 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Platform Drafting Committee
will meet again in Denver on June 24, on the eve of a two-day
meeting of the full platform committee, the party said Wednesday.
   The 16-member drafting committee, chaired by Rep. William Gray
III of Pennsylvania, spent three days at Mackinac Island, Mich.,
last weekend hammering out working papers on key issues.
   Forces of Michael Dukakis, the all-but-certain Democratic
nominee, and presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson were divided over
whether the platform should call for a freeze on Pentagon spending
and a tax increase on the wealthy. They did agree, however, to
brand South Africa a terrorist state.
   Gray promised the participants Sunday they would get a chance to
vote on a draft platform sometime before the full 186-member panel
takes up the document June 25-26.
   Jackson has enough delegates to force floor fights on any issues
he chooses at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta. The
convention will take up the platform on July 19, its second night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
