<HEAD>Reagan Names Pastorino Special Assistant for National Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Wednesday appointed Robert
S. Pastorino as a special assistant for national security affairs,
succeeding Jose S. Sorzano as a senior director of Latin American
affairs on the National Security Council.
   Pastorino is a career Foreign Service officer who joined the
State Department in 1966. His early overseas assignments included
embassy posts in Caracas, Venezuela; Bogota, Colombia; and Lisbon,
Portugal.
   He served as charge d'affaires in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, between
July and November 1986 and as deputy chief of mission until May
1987. He then was named deputy assistant secretary of defense for
inter-American affairs.
   Pastorino, a 48-year-old native of San Francisco, graduated from
San Francisco State University.
</TEXT>
