<DOCNO> AP880615-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Brutality     06-15 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Brutality,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Film Documents Troop Brutality</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers will be shown a film
documenting their abuses of reporters and Arabs in the occupied
lands to discourage such behavior and show troops how news reports
of brutality damage Israel's image.
   The 22-minute army film, entitled ``The Camera Sees All,'' shows
disturbing images of troops responding to stone-throwing by beating
Arabs, vandalizing their shops and tying Palestinian children to
jeeps.
   The images ``prove there is no law and order and that the army
has lost control,'' narrator Michael Karpin of Israel Television
says in the film.
   The army showed the film to foreign journalists on Wednesday at
the military's main headquarters in Tel Aviv.
   Army officials said commanders were ordered this week to show
the film to all soldiers serving in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   ``These pictures will be shown (by the media) over and over
again around the world. They show exceptional behavior which does
us much damage,'' narrator Michael Karpin of Israel Television says
in the film.
   ``Do not make the cameraman put you on stage. You are not an
actor. Western television, especially in the United States, works
by the principle of getting a picture at any price. If the reporter
is treated well he will give a balanced account,'' Karpin said.
   The movie was made in response to dozens of incidents in which
soldiers have been filmed vandalizing photographers' equipment,
speaking harshly to foreign newsmen and beating Arabs during the
six-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories.
   The Foreign Press Association has complained of 150 cases of
physical abuse of foreign journalists since the unrest began Dec.
8. According to United Nations figures, 208 Palestinians have been
killed and two Israelis have died in the rebellion.
   ``This film will have a swift, shocking effect on soldiers
because the tough pictures show exactly what they have done
wrong,'' said Col. Raanan Gissin, an army spokesman.
   ``The message is, we don't want bad pictures. You can minimize
them if you behave correctly,'' Gissin said.
   In the film, Karpin urges soldiers not to cover camera lenses to
try to prevent pictures from being taken, and elite Golani troops
show how to politely steer reporters away from areas declared
closed military zones.
   The film tries to boost the image of foreign reporters by saying
their reports are usually fair and professional. It shows a foreign
cameraman helping weeping Israeli teen-agers in the West Bank
village of Beita after a clash between Jewish settlers and
villagers in which an Israeli girl was killed.
   The movie also runs through half a dozen of some of the worst
incidents of brutality since the uprising began.
   It shows Jewish settlers chasing Arab schoolgirls with their
pistols drawn, a soldier smashing the windows of a
Palestinian-owned clothing shop, and a trooper dragging an Arab
detainee by the hair and banging his head into a metal door.
   Another scene shows an incident filmed by the American CBS
network in the West Bank city of Nablus in February showing
soldiers beating Arab youths detained for stone-throwing.
   ``This is an extremely deviant incident,'' Karpin says. ``The
soldiers beat two detainees for 30 minutes.''
   ``The censor can ban pictures which are damaging to state
security, but the censor cannot ban transmission of ... a picture
of a soldier beating an Arab passerby,'' Karpin says.
   Western reporters ``will stress these pictures in their reports,
because television around the world stresses the unusual,'' the
narrator adds.
   The film also shows riot police breaking up protests in South
Korea and the United States in the 1960s, with Karpin saying:
``Viewers are used to seeing pictures of force used to quell
violence.''
   But, Karpin says, Western viewers are not used to seeing images
of troops beating unarmed Arabs or accosting foreign journalists.
``These only make the viewer sympathize with the party who is done
harm.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
