<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland-Shot     06-15 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland-Shot,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protestant Leader Slain In Belfast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Protestant loyalist paramilitary chief was shot
to death in Belfast on Wednesday, and the IRA said it killed him in
retaliation for attacks on Roman Catholics.
   The dead man was identified by the Royal Ulster Constabulary as
Bobby ``Blood'' Seymour, 33, a known gunman for the outlawed Ulster
Volunteer Force.
   He was jailed for life in 1981 for the murder of a Catholic who
was believed to a high-ranking Irish Republican Army member.
Seymour was released when an appeals court dismissed an informer's
testimony.
   Several hours after Seymour was shot in an alley behind his
video shop in east Belfast by two masked gunmen who fled in a car,
the outlawed IRA made telephone calls to the media claiming
responsibility for his killing.
   The car used by the attackers later was found abandoned in the
Markets area of the city, and the police said a man arrested there
was being questioned about the slaying.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the province with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
