<HEAD>That's My Lady, Lord Justice, To You</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's first woman Appeals Court judge resolved
a major problem of protocol on Wednesday.
   The former Justice Elizabeth Butler-Sloss became Lord Justice
Butler-Sloss upon receiving her new appointment in December because
there were no provisions for an Appeals Court judge to be called
anything other than Lord Justice.
   She took it upon herself to end the ensuing confusion about her
sex and on Wednesday informed barristers she would like to be
referred to in court as ``My Lady, Lord Justice Butler-Sloss.''
