<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     06-15 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Blames Poor Poll Showing on Democratic Criticisms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush on Wednesday blamed his poor
showing in recent public opinion polls on a primary season filled
with Democratic candidates ``shooting at you every single day'' and
held out the possiblity that he might name a woman as his running
mate.
   The vice president, in an interview, also said that while he
would pursue President Reagan's efforts for the rebel Contra forces
in Nicaragua, ``I'd want to do it practically to see. Let's be sure
what we do will pass.''
   The adminstration has repeatedly encountered broad congressional
opposition to its attempts to provide military assistance to the
Contras.
   And, while the all-but-certain Republican nominee said he wasn't
advocating a change in direction from that policy, he suggested he
would try to work more closely with Congress.
   ``I'd love to find a way to take a package to the Hill and get
it passed,'' Bush said.
   Bush insisted that he still hasn't given thought to a possible
running mate, saying he will wait until after the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta, July 18-21.
   ``The number one criterion is will this person be capable of
taking over if something happend to the president? Enough
experience, enough stature, to do that. But, having said that, man
or woman, I would say: look, the gender question was crossed when
Geraldine Ferraro went on the (Democratic) ticket (in 1984).
   ``And that was a good thing, a very good thing,'' he said.
   Asked if he would name a woman if polls suggested such a ticket
would help him, Bush said: ``Anyone who would help me in the polls
would be a factor _ a man or a woman.''
   Recent polls also show Bush receiving high negative ratings, but
the vice president said, ``I think the answer on the polls is, if
there are negatives there, to turn them into positives. By getting
out what I feel on the issues.''
   ``But when you're sitting out there in a primary process with
two candidates shooting at you every single day, and a lot of
editorial media attention on controversial matters, I think it
would be surprising if things were any different,'' he said.
   ``So I feel fairly relaxed about that. I think we have time to
be sure that a positive image is out on who I am and what I feel
and where I'll take the country. And I'll readily concede that some
of that's not that clear yet,'' he said.
   Bush said that his gender gap problem _ the fact that his
support is much weaker among female voters than among male voters _
should narrow in time as he speaks out on ``what I feel on peace
and some of the issues that may disproportionately concern women.''
   The vice president said he intends to address the issue in
campaign advertising and seek out prominent Republican women to
speak in his behalf.
   However, Bush said he did not intend ``to go off to some extreme
position in order to try to rectify what might be a gender gap.''
   ``Just spell out your concerns. People are interested in the
family. I've got a good one. I don't think we get credit for how we
manage family values yet. And what really motivates me. And caring
and compassion and all of that stuff,'' he said.
   Bush also said that, while he doesn't plan to overdo his efforts
to depict Dukakis as an ultra-liberal elitist for fear that it
might backfire, ``I've got to get people's attention.'' Bush said
he would mix rhetoric against the Democratic candidate with
``precise facts.''
   In a wide-ranging interview, Bush also called for an aggressive
investigation into allegations of bribery and fraud in the Defense
Department.
   ``It is essential that we get to the bottom of that, whatever it
is. Where there is smoke over there, see what fire is there and
clean that up. It is our commitment to getting rid of waste, fraud
and abuse that is leading to some of this inquiry,'' he said.
   The FBI disclosed Tuesday that its investigators bugged Pentagon
offices over a nearly two-year period before staging coordinated
raids there and at the office of defense contractors in 12 states.
The steps were part of a massive investigation of alleged fraud,
bribery and bid-fixing in military purchasing.
   Bush said that if elected, he would set up a presidential task
force on urban affairs with a membership made up primarily of
mayors.
   He made the proposal in a letter to the U.S. Conference of
Mayors, which is meeting this week in Salt Lake City. ``We need to
forge a new relationship. I intend to be an activist president
involved in helping you to find solutions,'' Bush said.
   ``Though massive amounts of federal aid are not available, my
goal is to shape a federal role that serves as a catalyst to help
the cities solve their problems,'' he said in the letter.
   He also said he would not make any structural changes in the
office of vice president, such as having the vice president head a
department. ``That would be bad government. (Former president)
Gerald Ford proposed making him (the vice president) chief of
staff. But I don't agree with that, either.''
   Bush has proposed making the vice president head of the
administration's anti-drug efforts.
</TEXT>
