<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party     06-15 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party To Debate Soviet's Ethnic Problems, But Only Generally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide Communist Party conference will
discuss the Soviet Union's ethnic troubles but probably won't
consider Armenia's demand to annex a region of a neighboring
republic, two delegates said Wednesday.
   The party conference that begins June 28 is to take up a series
of theses approved by the party Central Committee last month,
including a statement calling for more attention and compromise on
difficult ethnic problems.
   About 5,000 party members will gather in Moscow against a
backdrop of continued tension between Armenia and Azerbaijan over
control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   ``The issue of nationality relations will be debated at the
party conference,'' Vladimir Kluyev, a Moscow party official, told
reporters at a news conference sponsored by the government news
agency Novosti.
   But Kluyev, head of the party organization in the Lenin region
of Moscow, said he would be against reviewing a demand to allow
Armenia to annex Nagorno- Karabakh from Azerbaijan.
   Otto Latsis, deputy editor of the theoretical journal Kommunist,
said: ``It is necessary to discuss national relations, and what is
being done and what is going to be done,'' at the party conference
but the specific dispute between Azerbaijan and Armenia should not
be brought up.
   The Supreme Soviet of Armenia approved a request Wednesday to
annex Nagorno-Karabakh, and Armenian activists said they are
waiting for a response from Moscow. Officials in the capital
already have turned down the request.
   A general discussion of ethnic problems at the party conference
is unlikely to satisfy ethnic Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh and in
Armenia, who have rejected a special government aid package for
Nagorno-Karabakh as insufficient.
   When Communist Party authorities rejected the Armenian
annexation request in February, strikes and bloody ethnic violence
occurred in Armenia and Azerbaijan. On Feb. 28, riots broke out in
the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait, and 32 people, mostly Armenians,
were killed.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called for a meeting of
the policy-making Central Committee to discuss ethnic questions,
which he described as one of the country's most crucial issues.
   The theses for the party conference approved by the Central
Committee said that ``inter-ethnic relations require constant
attention, as does the progress of every ethnic entity.''
   ``Inter-ethnic issues shall be settled on the basis of genuine
democracy, in the spirit of perestroika,'' Gorbachev's effort to
restructure the economy, the theses say.
   They called for development of a policy that would satisfy
ethnic interests while subordinating them to a spirit of equality
among all ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
