<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Duke     06-15 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Duke,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patty Duke Makes Mid-Term Resignation As SAG President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patty Duke has resigned in the middle of her
second term as president of the Screen Actors Guild to produce a
movie based on her autobiography, ``Call Me Anna,'' the guild
announced Wednesday.
   Ms. Duke's resignation was effective immeidately. She was on
tour promoting the book and not available for comment.
   Guild by-laws state no officer or board member may hold a
production interest while in office.
   Ms. Duke was first elected president of the 70,000-member union
in November 1985 and was easily re-elected in November of 1987.
   Barry Gordon, Guild first vice president, will be acting
president until the board of directors holds its annual meeting in
December and elects a permanent replacement to complete Miss Duke's
term.
   ``Ms. Duke has worked tirelessly to project a positive image of
unionism at a time in our history when positive, aggressive
unionism is most needed,'' Gordon said.
   Ms. Duke's final speech as union president was Sunday at a SAG
mid-year membership meeting. She attacked management for refusing
to share with unions ``record profits for a record number of
companies, and record salaries for studio executives.''
   ``There has not been a single year in the 1980s when this
industry has not had a strike or been on the brink of one,'' the
actress said.
   Her resignation is the third time in the guild's history that a
president has stepped down to become a producer. The others were
Robert Montgomery in 1947 and Ronald Reagan in 1960.
</TEXT>
