<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NarcoticsBill     06-15 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Narcotics Bill,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Bill To Impose Foreign Aid Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation giving the government new
authority to withhold U.S. military and economic aid from countries
suspected of involvement in drug trafficking was approved on
Wednesday by the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   The bill also would require the secretary of state to revoke the
passports of U.S. citizens convicted of violating drug laws.
   Described as containing a series of ``modest new initiatives,''
the legislation will be included in a more comprehensive bill to be
considered by the full House later in the year.
   Committee staff members said the legislation is intended in part
to give specific authority to the Agency for International
Development to withhold economic and military aid from countries or
individuals known or believed to be involved in narcotics
trafficking.
   The bill also is intended to eliminate confusion in present law
on preventing aid from flowing to so-called ``drug transit''
countries.
   Other provisions include:
   _Making the secretary of state the coordinator of all overseas
anti-narcotics assistance.
   _Waiving present law to permit providing weapons to foreign
police units ``for anti-narcotics purposes only.''
   _Creating a special aid package for Colombia which is struggling
with powerful narcotics cartels.
   _Exploring the possibility of working with the Organization of
American States to create a multinational regional anti-narcotics
force.
   Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., the committee chairman, said that
while the bill does not substantially increase spending for the war
on drugs, ``it does provide incentives for cooperating countries to
do more to help us.''
</TEXT>
