<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHome     06-15 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welfare Commissioner Puts Daughter in Hiding After Kidnap Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state welfare commissioner said
Wednesday his 13-year-old daughter has been taken out of state
because of kidnapping threats following the state's closure of a
Baptist boarding home for troubled youths.
   The independent Bethel Home for Children in Lucedale was closed
Friday after allegations of child abuse and neglect.
   The home's operator, the Rev. Herman Fountain, is jailed on
three felony counts of assault of a law officer for scuffling with
George County sheriff's deputies and troopers who tried Monday to
take custody of children who returned to the home and serve
subpoenas on home staff members.
   Since Friday, state welfare officials have taken 77 children
from the home into custody. About 50 were later released to their
parents.
   Thomas Brittain, state welfare commissioner, said Wednesday that
he commonly gets telephone threats such as ``You're going to go to
hell and that sort of thing.''
   ``But here there was more specificity about what was going to
happen. The term children and my daughter was specifically
mentioned. ... Threats of kidnapping and putting her in a home
where she would never be found again,'' he said.
   Brittain said his daughter, Brandi, was moved about a week ago
after he had received three calls with specific kidnapping threats.
He said he had no idea who made the calls.
   ``We felt it just precautionary to move her, and she is
comfortable. Though she doesn't like being away and we don't like
it either, she'll remain out of state until all this has simmered
down,'' Brittain said.
   Brittain's other child, Thomas, 21, has remained at home.
   Fountain has told reporters he had about 120 children at the
home before Youth Court Judge Robert Oswald of Pascagoula gave the
state temporary custody of the youths on Friday.
   Oswald ruled the children, ages 10 to 17, had been subjected
``to physical abuse, medical neglect and detention amounting to
imprisonment.''
   Fountain has refused to give the Youth Court a list of the
children, claiming the home is part of his fundamentalist ministry
and exempt from state regulation because of the constitutional
guarantee of freedom of religion.
   The state has required that parents or guardians wanting to
regain custody must sign a statement promising not to send the
children back to Bethel.
   Fountain said in an interview that no more than 10 licks with a
switch were allowed and that other punishments permitted were
running laps _ no more than 25 _ and making students write
sentences over and over on the blackboard.
</TEXT>
