<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatMan     06-15 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fat Man,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walter Hudson Almost Ready to Go Outside</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Hudson says he has lost half his
1,200 pounds, gained his confidence and is almost ready to leave
his house for the first time in 17 years.
   ``I'm ready for the outside world,'' Hudson said Wednesday,
leaning out a back window of his Hempstead home. ``I hope the world
is ready for me.''
   Hudson wasn't ready for the world, or even his front yard, in
February, when he turned down an offer from comedian-nutritionist
Dick Gregory to attend Gregory's clinic in the Bahamas. Hudson
already had lost several hundred pounds under Gregory's regimen,
but balked at leaving the house.
   Gregory took an interest in Hudson after he fell Sept. 14 and
became wedged in a doorway. Rescue workers had to saw out the door
frame to free him.
   Hudson said Wednesday he would step outside in August onto a
patio being built flush to his bedroom by volunteers.
   ``I'm going to clap my hands and praise God when I get
outside,'' said Hudson, 42.
   He said he has controlled his fear of losing his balance and
built up his confidence through hours of therapy.
   ``I feel good,'' he said. ``I feel like I've been paroled from
jail.''
   He said the first thing he wants to do is visit his mother's
grave, a few miles from his house, and then go to nearby New York
City.
   Hudson is being treated by a medical team led by Barbara Rosen,
a psychologist who specializes in weight disorders. She said the
600-pound weight loss _ like his original 1,200-pound weight _ is a
doctors' estimate because Hudson does not fit on conventional
scales.
   He is on a special liquid diet and fasts every other day.
   Rosen said Hudson overate because of anxieties that had built up
over years, then his body image created a feeling of shame and
embarrassment which made him hide from the world.
   ``His depression has lifted,'' Rosen said. ``He is a happier man
and wants very much to get out of that house.''
   Hudson says he has been outside only once in 28 years, 17 years
ago when he moved from Brooklyn to Hempstead, where he lives with
relatives.
   Patrick Hynes, a contractor from Lake Grove, broke ground this
week for the patio. Hynes said he is donating the project, worth
$9,000, because ``it feels good to help someone.''
   Hudson said he has set up in recent months his own hot line to
counsel people with weight, drug and alcohol problems.
   ``In helping them overcome their addiction, I think I have
helped myself,'' Hudson said.
</TEXT>
