<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NancyReagan     06-15 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy Reagan,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Years Full of Thrills, Heartaches, Mrs. Reagan Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan offered a bit of advice to her
successor on Wednesday, warning the next first lady that she will
experience ``her greatest thrills and her greatest heartaches''
while in the White House.
   ``Life has been so magnified here,'' the first lady said.
``Sometimes it's been hard to comprehend what living in this house
really means. The day you come through the White House gates, your
life somehow becomes larger than life.''
   Mrs. Reagan addressed more than 100 women at the annual Senate
Wives' luncheon she traditionally holds at the executive mansion.
   Along with wives of most of the nation's senators, one possible
sucessor as first lady _ Vice President George Bush's wife, Barbara
_ was present. And seated next to Mrs. Bush was Elizabeth Dole, the
wife one-time presidential candidate, Senate Minority Leader Bob
Dole of Kansas.
   Looking back over her eight years in the White House, the first
lady said she'd experienced a ``rollercoaster of emotions'' ranging
from the first inauguration to the ``absolute terror'' of the March
30, 1981, assassination attempt on President Reagan.
   Mrs. Reagan noted that within the space of a single week
recently she'd visited the Kremlin with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, Buckingham Palace with Queen
Elizabeth, 10 Downing Street with British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and Disney World with a group of foster grandparents.
   ``Every one of those years has been fascinating in its own way.
... They've been truly remarkable years _ for both of us _ and ones
not given to many people,'' she said.
   ``It will be the same for the next first lady. And it will be
the cause of her greatest thrills and her greatest heartaches,''
Mrs. Reagan added.
   The first lady did not speak of the most recent controversy that
has dogged her, in particular her consultations with an astrologer
and the in-fighting with former White House chief of staff Donald
T. Regan, who disclosed the practice in his book, ``For the
Record.''
   She said she felt her most fulfilling years have come through
her work against drug abuse among youth, and she pledged to
continue her campaign once she leaves the White House.
   ``While I'm looking forward to California, I will miss
Washington, and I'll miss all of you,'' Mrs. Reagan told the
gathering.
</TEXT>
