<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ParentalConsent     06-15 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parental Consent,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martinez Signs Parental Consent Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez signed a bill into
law Wednesday that will require unmarried girls under 18 to obtain
parental or judicial permission before getting abortions.
   The law also re-enacts regulations of the state's abortion
clinics and allows the Department of Health and Rehabilitative
Services to revoke the license of any clinic that doesn't properly
dispose of fetal remains.
   Martinez, and representatives from several anti-abortion groups
who attended the bill signing, said the measure restored the rights
of parents to make decisions about their children.
   ``This has got to be seen as a victory for the children because
what child going through surgery should not have permission from
their parents,'' said Kay James, spokeswoman for National Right to
Life. ``Even pro-choice people ought to see this as a victory. This
is not about abortion.''
   Opponents of the law said it would lead to an increase in the
number of teen-age pregnancies and force some girls to go out of
state to seek abortions or prompt them to self-induce abortions.
   ``The parental-consent bill doesn't work,'' said Jerry Klein,
director of Planned Parenthood of Tallahassee. ``You end up with a
minor who delays telling the parent, you end up with a minor who
may seek an abortion out of state.''
   Under the new law, girls will be able to obtain permission from
a judge for an abortion. The so-called judicial bypass was designed
in cases such as incest.
   The law says the Supreme Court will develop rules to make sure
those cases are handled quickly and that the girls' anonymity is
protected.
   Klein estimated there were 10,000 teen-age abortions in Florida
in 1982, the latest available statistics.
   Tom Horkan, director of the Florida Catholic Conference, one of
several groups that lobbied hard for the parental-consent bill,
said at least seven other states have parental-consent requirements.
</TEXT>
