<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     06-15 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians Win Legislative Support In Territorial Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Armenian legislature defied central Soviet
Communist Party authorities on Wednesday by siding with
demonstrators who for months have demanded annexation of a region
in a neighboring republic.
   The chairman of the Armenian Supreme Soviet, Gramt Voskanyan,
emerged from a five-hour session of parliament to announce the
decision to thousands of people gathered outside the legislature's
headquarters in Armenia's capital, Yerevan, according to a
television journalist.
   The parliamentary session was broadcast live on Armenian
television, a first for the republic. And the official Soviet news
agency Tass reported that the Armenian parliament ``decreed to give
its consent to the inclusion of the Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous
Region'' into the Armenian republic.
   The Tass dispatch, also read on the nationally broadcast
television evening news show ``Vremya,'' or Time, did not explain
the dispute.
   In Moscow, several hundred Armenians applauded and raised
clenched fists as Tiran Gureghian, the Armenian church
representative in the capital, told them the vote had been
unanimous to annex the Nagorno-Karabakh region. The region is
populated mostly by Armenians, who are Christian, but is located in
neighboring Azerbaijan, which is predominately Moslem.
   The vote by the Armenian parliament transforms the issue, which
has caused bloody ethnic violence, into a national constitutional
crisis, because the Soviet Constitution requires that all republics
concerned and the central government approve any territorial
changes.
   And central Soviet Communist Party authorities have already
rejected Armenian annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   It was far from clear whether the Armenians would be able to
wrest control of Nagorno-Karabakh from Azerbaijan, to which it has
been attached since 1923.
   The Presidium, or executive committee, of Azerbaijan's Supreme
Soviet, voted Monday to reject the annexation demand, saying it
would ``be contrary to the interests of the Azerbaijani and
Armenian population of the republic.''
   The full Supreme Soviet of Azerbaijan is to take up the issue
Friday, said the TV reporter, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
It is unlikely the Azerbaijani Supreme Soviet will go against the
wishes of its Presidium.
   Central Soviet Communist Party officials in Moscow rejected the
annexation demand in February, touching off ethnic violence and
strikes in Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   The national parliament, the Supreme Soviet headed by President
Andrei A. Gromyko, has not addressed the issue.
   Thus the latest twist in the Armenian-Azerbaijani dispute puts
it at the heart of a debate now developing in the Soviet Union, the
balance of power between the legislature, which according to the
Constitution is supreme, and the Communist Party, which has run the
Soviet Union since its creation in 1917.
   The Armenian Supreme Soviet, in the resolution it passed
Wednesday, said that a majority of residents of Armenia and
Nagorno-Karabakh want the region taken out of Azerbaijan, according
to the TV journalist, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Nagorno-Karabakh's local legislature voted Feb. 20 to request
the transfer. The region's Communist Party committee endorsed the
move a month later, saying it had been wrong to make the area part
of Azerbaijan.
   More than three-quarters of Nagorno-Karabakh's 160,000 people
are ethnic Armenians. Most Armenians are Christian while most
Azerbaijanis are Moslem.
   Gureghian, speaking from the steps of the red-brick church in a
Armenian cemetery, said Armenians would now wait for a decision by
national authorities: ``The people are united in their mood.
Everyone is waiting for a just decision.''
   The crisis has been costly. On Feb. 28, riots broke out in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait, and 32 people, mostly Armenians, were
killed. The Armenian Supreme Soviet resolution passed Wednesday
condemns that violence and offers condolences to relatives of the
victims, according to the TV journalist.
   Additionally, official press reports said strikes in Armenia and
Nagorno-Karabakh have damaged the area's economy.
   The turmoil puts Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
administration in a political quandry: if it agrees to transfer
Nagorno-Karabakh, it will anger Azerbaijanis. If it rejects the
demand, Armenians will be incensed.
   The bitter ethnic dispute has been an important test of
Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' which encourages the Soviet
people to speak out.
   ``Moscow will now have to play the role of an arbitrator,'' a
correspondent for the Armenian Communist Party newspaper Kommunist
said. He spoke by telephone from Yerevan on condition he not be
identified.
   The unrest over the dispute continued Wednesday. More than 150
students remained outside Yerevan's Opera Theater, staging a sit-in
they began May 25, the Kommunist reporter said.
   The TV journalist estimated that 1 million people from Armenia
gathered Wednesday in Yerevan's streets to monitor the Supreme
Soviet session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
