<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Drugs     06-15 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Drugs,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Endorses House GOP Anti-Drug Plan, Criticizes Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush on Wednesday
endorsed a House GOP plan to severely punish narcotics users, then
accused Democratic presidential candidates of making a ``shrill
political issue'' of anti-drug programs.
   ``I'm sick and tired ... in hearing the Democrats do nothing but
tear down and criticize'' Reagan administration anti-drug efforts,
Bush said. ``I'm talking about Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis
the last two months.''
   Standing with some 50 House Republicans, the all-but-certain GOP
presidential nominee turned a news conference on their plan into a
blistering partisan attack. He declared the proposed package
``better than anything the Democrats are going to dream up.''
   Included in the proposal are recommendations to take away
driving licenses of those convicted in drug cases, fine them up to
25 percent of their adjusted gross income and net assets, and make
them ineligible for federal contracts, loans or licenses.
   Answering reporters' questions, Bush said he supports the
administration's ``zero tolerance'' policy of seizing property when
even a small amount of illegal drugs is found. He said, ``If some
yacht owner is inconvenienced, it's too damn bad.''
   He challenged Dukakis, his likely presidential rival this fall,
to endorse a section of the plan calling for the death penalty for
drug kingpins.
   Dukakis, who has said capital punishment wouldn't help,
lambasted the administration's drug-fighting effort earlier
Wednesday in Framingham, Mass.
   In particular, he criticized cuts in funds for the Coast Guard,
saying, ``How can we possibly be serious about fighting a war on
drugs when we're cutting Coast Guard patrols by 55 percent. It's
that kind of thing _ one of the reasons I'm running for the
presidency.''
   Bush, however, blamed congressional Democrats for a $72 million
cut in the Coast Guard budget for drug patrols.
   The vice president said the military can do more in the
anti-drug effort, but added ``I have trouble'' with proposals for
the military to arrest civilians.
   The GOP plan would:
   _Make anyone convicted of a drug trafficking offense or of two
drug possession offenses ineligible for federal grants, contracts,
loans, or licenses for five years.
   _Create a civil fine of up to a quarter of the adjusted gross
income and net assets of anyone caught possessing illegal
substances.
   _Require that before a state could receive federal highway
money, it must enact laws to suspend a driver's license upon
conviction of a drug offense.
   _Require that before receiving a federal contract or federal
assistance a company must show a good-faith effort to maintain a
drug-free workplace.
   _Mandate drug testing for all federal arrestees in drug cases,
and revocation of bond if the result is positive. A clean drug test
would be a condition to federal probation, and parolees would be
tested at random.
   _Increase drug abuse treatment services.
   _Authorize grants for states that establish innovative anti-drug
programs.
   _Require a 10-year prison term for using a firearm in an assault
on a federal officer, and prohibit possession of a firearm in a
U.S. courthouse.
   _Require governors to use the national guard in assisting drug
enforcement efforts.
   _Increase penalties for train or other transportation operators
convicted of operating their vehicles while under the influence of
alcohol or drugs.
   _Increase the military's role in drug interdiction, a proposal
identical to legislation already passed by the House.
</TEXT>
