<FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CableReport     06-15 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cable Report,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Recommends Rule Changes To Increase Cable
Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's cable TV industry increasing is
controlled by a few large companies, the Reagan administration said
Wednesday in a report recommending rule changes to increase
competition.
   The report by the National Telecommunications and Information
Administration, a Commerce Department agency, said opening local
cable TV markets to more competition would reduce growing concerns
about ownership trends in the industry that may give large cable
companies excessive power to influence program distribution.
   Only a handful of communities offer residents a choice of cable
TV services, and outdated regulations serve only to perpetuate
monopoly franchising, said Alfred C. Sikes, assistant commerce
secretary for communications and information.
   ``Let's get more competition so we can have marketplace
solutions and not government regulatory solutions,'' Sikes said.
His agency is responsible for developing U.S. information and
communications policy, and the report was the Reagan
administration's first review of the cable TV industry.
   The head of the Federal Communications Commission praised the
report's conclusions, which generally propose the same deregulatory
course the commission has followed during the Reagan administration.
   ``Competition and open entry regulate best,'' Dennis R. Patrick,
FCC chairman, said in a statement. ``They guarantee responsiveness
to consumer demand and are the most effective safeguards against
market power.''
   The National Cable Television Association called the report
``interesting reading,'' but disagreed with some of its
recommendations, including a proposal that would give telephone
companies more freedom to provide transport facilities for cable TV
in their local service areas.
   The report says allowing phone companies to provide ``video dial
tone'' would allow anyone, including Hollywood studios, sports
organizations and broadcasters, to lease video channels to
distribute programs to subscribers.
   The report recommends elimination of a law that permits local
phone companies to lease channel capacity only to cable companies
that have a local cable franchise. It also recommends, however, no
change in laws that prohibit phone companies from owning cable
systems.
   The cable association says the proposal would put at a
disadvantage franchised cable companies, which pay a portion of
their revenues to the local municipal governments and which must
meet other community requirements.
   ``We don't want someone out there competing with us when they
don't have the same requirements imposed on them as we do by the
cities,'' cable association spokeswoman Lynn McReynolds said.
   The report also recommends eliminating a regulation that
prohibits TV networks from owning cable systems. The report says
national programming and advertising markets have become more
competitive since the 1970 ban was imposed.
   In addition, the agency recommends the FCC investigate ownership
concentration in the cable industry and consider taking steps to
limit cable ownership.
   Cable TV is available to about 80 percent of American homes.
About half of those households, an estimated 42.7 million,
subscribe to cable.
   The report noted that Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's
largest cable company, owning or controlling systems with about 10
million subscribers, has seen its share of the market grow from 9.1
percent in 1983 to 23.4 percent last year. The company's share more
than doubled from 1986 to 1987.
   The second-biggest cable company, American Television &
Communications Corp., owns or controls systems with about 4.4
million subscribers; Continental Cablevision Inc. is third, with
2.2 million subscribers; Cox Cable Communications and Storer
Communications have about 1.5 million each; and Warner Cable and
Comcast Cable Communications each have about 1.4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
