<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCockroaches     06-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Cockroaches,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cockroaches Bug Bus Riders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unwelcome passengers are bugging commuters on
city buses, say officials trying to get rid of a cockroach invasion
blamed on hot weather and garbage left by riders.
   ``These roaches have been using little cracks and crevices for
their little homes when the weather was not so hot,'' Chicago
Transit Authority spokeswoman Rosemarie Gulley said Wednesday.
   With summer approaching, the authority is painting and doing
other maintenance that destroys the varmints' homes, she said.
   ``Once we throw paint on them, they go running.'' The transit
authority has to deal with the problem somehow, she added, since
``we cannot count on our riders to starve them,'' despite an eating
ban on buses.
   ``For people who want to become squeamish about it, it's not a
health hazard, and it's not a safety hazard,'' she said.
   Cockroaches have been found on about 40 of the agency's more
than 2,000 buses, she said. They show up every year when the
weather turns hot.
   The agency routinely sprays insecticide in the buses, but this
year's roach crop is resistant to the poison, she said. A shortage
of dumpsters at a South Side bus terminal also contributed to the
garbage problem, she said.
   ``A couple of riders spotted a cockroach or two or three,'' Ms.
Gulley said, but ``to call it an epidemic is overstating the case.''
   Still, the problem is serious enough to have made the agency
look for a stronger insecticide and haul more dumpsters to the
terminal.
   And the buses put out of commission for spraying added another
bug to the city's attempts to control a recent shortage of usable
buses.
   Tuesday, 61 bus runs were canceled and 64 other buses ran late
because of a vehicle shortage.
   But transit authorities say it was due mainly to a lack of
replacement parts and delays in structural overhauls.
   Ms. Gulley said it's too soon to tell how well the new
insecticide is working.
   At least one insect expert predicts riders may have to wait
until winter for relief.
   ``There are enough areas back behind the paneling and walls and
under the floors of buses that roaches find places to hide,'' said
entomologist Philip Nixon of the University of Illinois Cooperative
Extension Service in Champaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
