<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0697,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Close Schools, Bus Companies To Combat Arab Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Troops reportedly... with 1 graf and 14th
pvs, Army officials... with 2 grafs to UPDATE with army confirming
identity of dead man and additional injury; PICKS up 15th pvs:
Wednesday's strike...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's army closed schools and ordered
Arab-owned bus companies off the streets Wednesday after Arabs shut
down the occupied territories in solidarity with thousands of
jailed Palestinians.
   Troops killed a 21-year-old Arab who was blocking a West Bank
road to force workers to stay home from their jobs, the army said.
It said another Arab was wounded by army gunfire.
   The commercial shutdown was called for in a widely distributed
underground Palestinian leaflet.
   The strike's success appeared to anger military leaders, who
closed West Bank schools for two days. They also closed 16
Arab-owned bus companies in east Jerusalem and the West Bank for a
week beginning Thursday because they had participated in the strike.
   If protests continue, ``(the Arabs) will all be sorry about
it,'' said the military government chief, Brig. Gen. Shaike Erez.
   Palestinian leaders said the school closings and bus ban would
not slow six months of Arab protests against 21 years of Israeli
occupation.
   ``The uprising will continue because it is the key to our
future,'' said deposed Nablus Mayor Bassam Shakaa, who lost his
legs in a 1982 attack by Jewish terrorists.
   Also Wednesday:
   _Israel's chief fire official, Rami Kachalon, said his office
had recorded 2,500 forest and brush fires since May 15, most set by
Arab activists. ``We ask all the public to mobilize because of this
emergency situation,'' said Yaacov Markovitz, the government
official in charge of firefighters.
   _Leaders of Israel's tourism industry held an emergency meeting
with Tourism Minister Avraham Sharir to try to reverse a 40 percent
decline in visitors to Israel so far this year.
   _The army showed journalists a documentary film about Israeli
army brutality that will be viewed by all soldiers who serve in the
occupied lands. The film, which focuses on abuse of Arab civilians
and journalists, is intended to teach troops how to avoid such
behavior.
   Wednesday's fatality occurred in Battir, five miles northwest of
Bethlehem, where 40 youths blocked a road with boulders and
overturned trash barrels to make sure Arab workers participated in
the strike, said villager Ribhi Mustafa.
   When Israeli troops arrived on the scene, the Palestinians began
throwing bottles and stones, said Mustafa and an official at nearby
Beit Jalla Hospital.
   Soldiers responded first with tear gas and then fired live
ammunition, hitting Nidal Ibrahim Hassan in the head and killing
him, said the hospital official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The army confirmed Hassan was the dead man and said troops shot
him after he hurled a firebomb. A military spokesman said troops
wounded another Palestinian who was about to throw a firebomb.
   The death brought to 208 the number of Arabs killed since the
uprising began Dec. 8. Two Israelis also have been killed.
   Wednesday's strike was virtually universally observed among the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip's 1.5 million Palestinians, as well as
in east Jerusalem.
   In Bethlehem, graffiti on walls said in Arabic: ``Observe The
Strike, Or Else!'' In Nablus, outlawed Palestinian flags flew from
electrical poles.
   The army released figures Wednesday showing 7,800 Arabs now are
held in Israeli detention centers and 2,500 of those are under
administrative detention, which permits jailing for six months
without trial.
   Hanan Ashrawi, an English teacher at the West Bank's Bir Zeit
University, said the effectiveness of the strike showed the
intefadeh, Arabic for uprising, was still alive.
   ``It is wishful thinking for the Israelis to say the uprising is
dying,'' she told The Associated Press. ``To end the occupation,
people are willing to sacrifice.''
</TEXT>
