<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RecruitingMistake Bjt   06-15 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Recruiting Mistake, Bjt,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State National Guard Commander Says He's Sorry for Recruting
Mistake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Jersey National Guard commander
apologized Wednesday for a recruitment letter which was
accidentally sent to a 91-year-old World War I veteran and hundreds
of other men too old or too disabled to enlist.
   The World War I soldier, whose name was not released by state
officials, wrote that he was ``flattered,'' but the state's
adjutant general, Maj. Gen. Francis R. Gerard, said he feels some
of the other ineligibles are upset.
   ``There's enough for us to be concerned about and to publicly
apologize. I wish we could have avoided it,'' Gerard said. ``It is
something that is very embarrassing to happen.''
   ``Some people were originally concerned about the cost or felt,
`Don't you know I'm 70 years old?' or `Don't you know I'm 67 years
old?,''' said Ray Martyniuk, a spokesman for the state Department
of Veterans Affairs and Defense.
   The New Jersey Army National Guard needs recruits because only
80 percent of its 13,000 authorized positions are filled. The unit
is considered ``combat effective'' at 85 percent. Officials say New
Jersey's booming economy and low unemployment rate are primarily
responsible for the shortage.
   The mailing, which included an appeal signed by Gov. Thomas H.
Kean, went out nearly two weeks ago to 300,000 New Jersey veterans.
The guard targeted this group in order to save the $40,000 in
training costs incurred every time someone with no military
experience enlists.
   A ``concerted effort'' was made to purge from the mailing list
veterans over 41 years old, those who receive disability checks,
and other ineligibles, but the names of hundreds, and possibly more
than a thousand, ``inappropriate candidates'' slipped through, much
more than expected, Gerard said.
   ``It is quite evident ... that the realities of mass mailing
produce a certain percentage of error,'' Gerard said.
   The direct mail campaign cost $203,000, but will pay for itself
if only six veterans enlist, Gerard said. So far, the response has
been promising: More than 2,800 veterans have written or called the
guard, expressing an interest in signing up.
   Even the ineligibles who received letters and contacted the
guard were satisfied once they received an explanation, Martyniuk
said.
   Other veterans, like the World War I soldier, were thrilled, or
in some cases amused, to get the letter and the accompanying
``certification of appreciation'' from the governor.
   ``I am tremendously flattered by Gov. Kean's offer,'' said
Albert Marks, 75, a World War II veteran. ``If he would offer me a
star at my age _ all I would like is one star _ I would consider
it.''
   Harry Romano, 67, of West New York, said he was surprised to
find the letter in his mail, and added, ``I don't even think I can
hear the bugle in the morning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
