<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-MotleyCrue     06-15 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Motley Crue,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement Reached In Concert Injury Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A settlement in excess of $175,000 was
reached in a lawsuit filed against the heavy metal band Motley Crue
by two boys, one of whom lost an eye during a 1986 ``Theater of
Pain'' concert.
   Jim Corder, an attorney for one of the youths, said Motley
Crue's insurer, Fireman's Fund, will pay an undisclosed sum to
Robbie Miller, now 17, of Athens, and David Wright, now 19, of
Grant.
   The settlement will allow both sides to avoid a second trial.
The first ended with a deadlocked jury.
   Corder said most of the settlement will go to Miller, who was
blinded in one eye during the concert, allegedly when dry ice or
other debris flew off the stage during a pyrotechnic display.
Wright suffered facial cuts.
   Corder said the financial settlement is larger than $175,000,
but he said the agreement stipulated that the amount not be made
public.
   The two boys had asked for about $1.2 million in damages from
the band and other defendants, including the city of Huntsville,
concert promoter Sound Seventy Prodctions Inc. of Nashville, Tenn.,
and the Von Braun Civic Center.
   Before a mistrial was declared in the first trial, Circuit Judge
Henry Blizzard had dismissed charges against all defendants except
the heavy metal band and its members, Nikki Sixx, Mick Mars, Tommy
Lee and Vince Neil.
   Sixx, the band's bass guitarist, was the only band member to
attend the trial. Crowds of young people came to court seeking his
autograph.
</TEXT>
