<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-DrugTesting     06-15 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drug Testing,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Casts Symbolic Vote for Random Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House members urged their negotiators on
Wednesday to accept Senate legislation imposing random drug and
alcohol testing on the 3.3 million employees of the airline,
railroad and trucking industries.
   The 377-27 vote will have no legal effect because the resolution
was non-binding. But it adds momentum to the efforts of lawmakers
seeking to spread drug testing requirements, and gave them another
opportunity to participate in what has become a popular
election-year exercise of voting against drug abuse.
   The two chambers have been locked in a dispute over the testing
measure since October, when it was approved by the Senate. Because
of the standoff, a bill that would require airlines to provide more
flight information to passengers _ of which the drug testing
language is a part _ has been bogged down in a House-Senate
negotiating committee.
   Supporters of the testing proposal say the threat of random
examinations would deter transportation workers from using drugs
and alcohol, and thus help prevent accidents.
   ``We cannot allow one more disaster to happen while the House
and Senate quibble over the importance of this amendment,'' said
Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., who sponsored the non-binding
measure.
   Members of the House negotiating team have argued that testing
is an invasion of privacy, and that laboratory techniques are not
error free and could jeopardize the careers of workers by producing
false results.
   Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., sponsor of the testing provisions
passed by the Senate, said the House vote would put pressure on
that chamber's members to finally approve the drug and alcohol
requirements.
   He also said he will look for other legislation to which he
could attach the testing proposal, in an effort to increase its
chances for receiving final congressional approval.
   ``Anything that moves, we'll add it,'' he said in an interview.
</TEXT>
