<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Touts His Crimefighting Record, Scoffs at Liberal Tag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush comment, subbing 3 grafs for 5th graf pvs,
While Dukakis, and subbing 8th graf pvs, Asked if</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, portraying
himself as an effective crimefighter, said Wednesday misguided
Reagan administration action in fighting illegal drugs was ``one of
the reasons I'm running for the presidency.''
   The Massachusetts governor and probable Democratic presidential
nominee touted the declining Massachusetts crime rate.
   He also accused Reagan of hampering the war on drugs by cutting
Coast Guard funds. ``It energizes me on the presidential trail,''
Dukakis said of the reduced anti-drug patrols.
   ``How can we possibly be serious about fighting a war on drugs
when we're cutting Coast Guard patrols by 55 percent,'' he told
reporters outside the state police academy. ``It's that kind of
thing _ one of the reasons I'm running for the presidency.''
   In Washington, Republican George Bush, Dukakis' likely opponent
in the fall, blamed congressional Democrats for the Coast Guard
budget cut, and he accused Democratic presidential candidates of
making a ``shrill political issue'' of anti-drug programs.
   ``I'm sick and tired ... in hearing the Democrats do nothing but
tear down and criticize'' Reagan administration anti-drug efforts,
Bush said. ``I'm talking about Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis
the last two months.''
   While Dukakis was in Massachusetts, his close friend and
campaign chairman Paul Brountas continued meetings in Washington
with party leaders and prospective Dukakis running mates. Sens.
John Glenn of Ohio, Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Llyod Bentsen of
Texas and Sam Nunn of Georgia as well as House Majority Leader
Thomas Foley of Washington were among those expected to meet with
Brountas before he returned home late Thursday or Friday, campaign
and Capitol Hill aides said. Brountas also met with Jackson on
Wednesday.
   Dukakis, who was to begin a Southern campaign swing Thursday
during which he will continue to focus on crime, was at the police
academy to meet with his anti-crime council and salute the state's
Violent Fugitive Arrest Squad, which has made more than 700 arrests
in its two and one-half years of existence.
   ``Eternal vigilance is what's needed,'' Dukakis said.
   Asked if he felt Bush would be able to portray him as being soft
on crime, Dukakis cited his state's crime rate, which has dropped
14 percent in the past four years.
   Then, lumping Bush with Reagan, he added: ``They've got lots of
answering to do for what's been happening over the past eight
years.''
   The governor broke into a broad smile when asked what he thought
of Bush's comment that he was a ``Brookline, Mass., liberal,'' a
reference to Dukakis' hometown.
   ``If you come from Milton ...,'' Dukakis said before breaking
off in mid-sentence. Milton, in the same county as Brookline, is
Bush's birthplace.
   On other matters, Dukakis:
   _ Supported in general the recommendations of a presidential
commisson on AIDS and said as president he would personally lobby
for an anti-discrimination law called for by the panel to protect
victims of the disease.
   _ Said he had made no decision whether to support a $40 million
cigarette tax being considered to help the state erase a projected
budget shortfall for next year.
   Wednesday was the third straight day Dukakis was on the road
discussing crime and drugs. On Monday he visited a Somerville,
Mass., playground to pomote drug education, following that up a day
later with a visit to the New Bedford waterfront and an idle Coast
Guard cutter. He stopped in front of a large mounted gun on deck as
photographers scrambled for shots.
</TEXT>
