<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FastingJudge Bjt   06-15 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fasting Judge, Bjt,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspended Judge's Protest Fast at Day 35</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge suspended for misconduct is 35 days
into a fast to protest what he contends is discrimination against
him because he is Hispanic, bisexual and critical of the judicial
system.
   Ramsey County District Judge Alberto Miera has vowed not to eat
for 100 days, which nutrition experts say would mean certain death.
However, some have questioned whether the St. Paul judge is really
sticking to his fast.
   ``Obviously I'm weak physically. That has to be expected,''
Miera said Wednesday. ``But emotionally and spiritually and in
terms of internal strength, I feel very strong.''
   Miera, 37, was suspended with pay in March by the Minnesota
Supreme Court, which is considering a recommendation by the state
Board on Judicial Standards to remove him from the bench.
   The board recommended in February that the Supreme Court remove
Miera for forcibly kissing his male court reporter, for making
improper remarks and gestures to female court employees, for
referring to other judges as ``bloodthirsty hypocrites,'' and for
other alleged misconduct.
   Miera's case has divided the Twin Cities' Hispanic community.
   ``There are people in the community that don't agree with what's
going on and there are those in the community that feel Alberto has
brought it upon himself,'' said Martin Diaz, chief legal officer
for Centro Legal, a Hispanic-oriented legal aid organization with
offices in Minneapolis and on St. Paul's West Side, which has a
large Hispanic population.
   The Minnesota Minority Lawyers Association has called for an
investigation, saying Minnesota judges face a ``hostile
environment.''
   Miera said he began a 40-day partial fast on April 1, eating one
meal every other day supplemented with nutritional liquids. On May
11 he began drinking only water with lemon and taking vitamins, he
said.
   But a nutrition expert last month questioned whether Miera was
sticking to his fast.
   Dr. Ancel Keys, an expert on human starvation, said when the
judge appeared for a Supreme Court hearing May 24 he looked better
than a person at that stage of the fast would look.
   ``If he lasts 100 days, we'll know he's cheating, but I think
he's cheating anyway,'' Keys, director and professor emeritus of
the University of Minnesota's epidemiology department, told the St.
Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch.
   Miera, who would not discuss his weight loss, maintains he has
stuck to his fast and has invited reporters to observe him at home.
   ``Granted, I tried something extreme,'' Miera said. ``If that's
what I need to demonstrate the sincerity of what I said, the
commitment I need and the dedication I have, then that's what I
have to do.''
   Some legislators have called for Miera to end his fast and for
an investigation of alleged bias in the judicial system. Gov. Rudy
Perpich, who appointed Miera to the bench in 1983, met with him
last weekend to urge him to end his fast, but the judge would not
relent.
   Archbishop John R. Roach of the Archdiocese of St. Paul and
Minneapolis prayed with Miera at the judge's home Wednesday, Miera
said. An archdiocese spokeswoman confirmed the meeting but released
no details.
   Neil K. Johnson, the former court reporter who won a civil jury
verdict against Miera last year but declined comment for months
after the trial, broke his silence this week. On Wednesday he
called Miera's fast manipulative.
   ``This whole story breaks down to a guy who's so outrageous and
just happens to be Mexican,'' Johnson said. ``Nobody comes to help
me because I'm white.''
   In March 1987, a jury found that Miera committed battery under
civil law by forcibly kissing Johnson in December 1984. The jury
awarded Johnson $375,000 in damages, but District Judge John
Weyrens of Litchfield reduced the amount to $125,000. The jury's
decision and the judge's award reduction were upheld by the
Minnesota Court of Appeals on June 7.
   Miera said he fired Johnson for poor work habits and attitudes.
Johnson contends he was fired because he refused the judge's sexual
advances.
   Johnson accused Miera of trying to manipulate public sympathy.
   ``He's getting national press and he knew he would,'' Johnson
said. ``I'm defending myself for having won.''
   Miera said he'll end his fast only if Johnson recants or if
other Ramsey County judges acknowledge that they did not have a
right to publicly comment while Miera's case was pending. He does
not expect either to happen.
</TEXT>
