<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Press     06-15 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Press,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banned Weekly Reappears In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cape Town weekly banned in
May by the home affairs minister was back in circulation Wednesday,
although its publishers said they fear it could be outlawed again
at any time.
   South, one of two papers banned by minister Stoffel Botha
because he objected to their content, went on sale with a
front-page story headlined ``Crackdown.'' The paper reported on
anti-government activists who have been detained or restricted
since the state of emergency was renewed last Friday.
   South was banned on May 9 for one month. Under the new emergency
laws, Botha can extend the ban two additional months but thus far
has not exercised that power.
   New Nation, a weekly published by the South African Catholic
Bishops Conference and aimed at a black audience, says it intends
to put out an expanded issue when it reappears June 30 following a
three-month ban.
   Botha can still ban New Nation along with South and at least
five other publications to which he has issued warnings.
   Both pro- and anti-government newspapers have complained about
the new emergency regulations, which have extended restrictions on
who can be quoted and what they can be quoted as saying. Newspapers
now are also prohibited from indicating how their reports have been
censored to comply with the regulations.
   The emergency regulations prohibit reporting about calls for
boycotts or illegal strikes and ban information about their success
or any measures used to ensure they occur.
</TEXT>
