<DOCNO> AP880615-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People Sub a0691 06-15 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People, Sub, a0691,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead of 3rd item, dateline NEW YORK, to delete
extraneous `the.'
^LaserPhoto NY44</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacques d'Amboise brought the sights and sounds
of Coney Island alive on stage at the Felt Forum, with scores of
dancers playing waves, crabs, sand fleas and a family at the beach.
   A thousand school children were joined by professional dancers,
senior citizens, New York City police officers and Australian
lifeguards for ``A Day in the Life of Coney Island.''
   Tuesday's show was the National Dance Institute's annual ``Event
of the Year.''
   d'Amboise, who founded the institute in 1976 to teach dancing to
schoolboys, wrote this year's story. He also wrote most of the
lyrics and conductor Lee Norris wrote most of the tunes used for
the dances.
   The event, once limited to boys, featured male and female
dancers, ages 3 to 85.
