<HEAD>William Horn Leaving Assistant Interior Secretary Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Park Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William P. Horn, assistant interior secretary
in charge of the National Park Service and the Fish and Wildlife
Service, has resigned effective July 1, the department announced
Wednesday.
   Horn, 38, is one of the last high-level Interior officials left
who came to the department with the Reagan administration. He
served as deputy undersecretary from 1981 to 1985, when he became
assistant secretary for fish and wildlife and parks.
   Horn, who has served on the staffs of members of Congress from
Alaska and was a specialist on Alaska issues on congressional
committee staffs, said he would join the Washington office of the
Anchorage law firm of Birch, Horton, Bittner, Pestinger and
Anderson.
