<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     06-15 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Battling Along Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes flew hundreds of
sorties Wednesday and Iran claimed to have shot one down.
   Iraq said its fighter jets and helicopter gunships flew 332
sorties, 60 more than Tuesday. The official Iraqi News Agency,
monitored in Nicosia, said 83 fighter jets and 249 helicopter
gunships were involved.
   Heavy use of gunships usually indicates major ground battles.
Iraq's strategy in the war that began in September 1980 has been to
use its air superiority to counter Iran's greater strength on the
ground.
   A television report in Tehran said Iranian fighters shot down an
Iraqi Mirage fighter jet over the Persian Gulf, but Iraq denied any
losses.
   Iran reported several other air encounters. Iraq said its
soldiers won skirmishes in the northern and central sectors of the
730-mile border war front, but Iranian reports did not mention
fighting on the ground.
   Conflicting reports cannot be reconciled because neither side
allows independent observers near battle zones except on rare
guided tours.
   The current battles started Monday with an Iranian assault on
Iraqi positions east of Basra, the Iraqi port and southern
provincial capital.
   In the Persian Gulf, the U.S. Navy completed its 36th convoy of
the year on Wednesday as the U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker Surf City
sailed out through the Strait of Hormuz, the waterway's southern
entrance.
   Maj. Charles Boyd, a spokesman for U.S. Central Command, said
the trip was uneventful. It started in Kuwait on Sunday.
   The 81,283-ton Surf City is one of the 11 Kuwait-owned tankers
re-registered by the United States a year ago to entitle them to
U.S. naval protection in the war-torn gulf.
   The 3,600-ton missile frigate Robert G. Bradley, one of several
recently arrived warships, escorted the Surf City.
   Since July of 1987, the Navy has conducted 58 convoys through
the gulf, most involving at least one Kuwaiti tanker.
</TEXT>
