<FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Bush     06-15 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Bush,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dole Meet With Lyng To Discuss Farm Drought Situation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought has punched hard at much of the nation
and threatens to shrivel this year's corn crop if rains don't come
soon, Vice President George Bush said Wednesday after a briefing at
the Agriculture Department.
   Bush and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole met about half an hour
with Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng to hear the latest
information on the widespread drought that has gripped many of the
nation's most productive agricultural areas.
   ``The nation's corn crop is now entering a very crucial growing
period,'' Bush said in a statement. ``While it is too early to
fully assess any damage from the drought, without rain there is the
potential for this to be a catastrophe.''
   Bush said the administration ``is working closely with the
members of the Senate and the House, and we hope to do whatever we
can to minimize the effect'' of the drought on U.S. agriculture.
   Farmers in more than 800 counties in 21 states are receiving
some form of emergency relief, he said.
   ``But sad to say, nothing will take place of rainfall, and we
have to be concerned about the plight of the nation's farmers,''
Bush said.
   Bush and Dole left the USDA meeting without responding to
reporters' questions.
   However, Norton Strommen, the department's chief meteorologist,
went over material he said was presented to Bush and Dole,
including red-and-yellow charts showing the advent of drought
conditions.
   Strommen said the West was severely lacking in moisture from
reduced snowpack during the winter, which resulted in
``well-below-normal'' reservoir levels in much of the region,
including Idaho, Washington, Oregon and Nevada.
   Another major problem area to develop was in the northern Great
Plains, notably in Montana and the Dakotas, he said. And dry areas
still persist in the Southeast, which has not yet fully recovered
from the 1986 drought.
   ``The best areas in terms of moisture are the Southwest, up into
the central Great Plains ... in Kansas and Nebraska,'' Strommen
said.
   Just in the last two weeks, the drought has expanded into the
eastern Corn Belt states of the Midwest, and ``this is a major
concern for us,'' he said.
   Without substantial rains soon, Strommen said the Corn Belt
drought has a ``potential for deterioration'' of crops.
   ``It simply is too early in the growing season to try and define
what that potential is,'' he said.
   Corn planted this spring will need enough moisture to get it
through its critical pollination stage of development in mid-July,
while soybeans are later and run into critical moisture needs in
July and August, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
