<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MovieColorization     06-15 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Movie Colorization,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jimmy Stewart Lobbys for Movie Colorization Disclaimers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Jimmy Stewart urged Congress on
Wednesday to preserve ``the creative vision'' of the directors of
classic films by preventing their work from being ``colorized'' or
otherwise altered by computer techniques.
   ``I have been in the motion picture business quite a while now,
almost 60 years, and I have great respect for the motion picture,''
Stewart said. ``I think it's something of tremendous value and I
want to do everything I can to preserve it.''
   Stewart, 80, spoke with reporters on the eve of a congressional
committee's vote on the National Film Preservation Act of 1988. The
measure seeks to settle the dispute over the artistic rights of
directors who object to color being added to black and white films,
or to editing or other changes made to their films by distributors
or exhibitors.
   ``There've been all sorts of things happening lately that take
the motion picture as a means to make more money and in doing so
destroy the original picture itself,'' Stewart said.
   Stewart read a letter of support from Frank Capra, who directed
him in ``It's a Wonderful Life.'' Through a clerical error, the
film fell into the public domain, was bought, colorized and
copyrighted by the new owners.
   ``This monstrosity is an embarrassment to me and my friend James
Stewrt,'' Capra said. ``They splashed it all over with Easter egg
colors and they ruined it.''
   Lamenting the alteration of what Capra described as a film
originally ``intended to prove the worth of every person,'' the
letter said, ``even the villian looks pink and cheerful. The story,
therefore, has been changed.''
   Earlier this year, Stewart and a number of Hollywood directors
voiced their opposition at Senate hearing investigating the
dispute, which became more heated after Atlanta businessman Ted
Turner bought the rights to and colorized classic films such as
``Casablanca,'' ``Yankee Doodle Dandy'' and ``It's a Wonderful
Life.''
   The film preservation act, sponsored by Rep. Robert J. Mrazek,
D-N.Y., creates a National Film Commission to determine which films
are ``culturally, historically or esthetically significant'' to be
placed in a newly created National Film Registry.
   Once designated, these films, if altered, would have to include
a disclaimer indicating that ``this version is not the original
creative vision'' of the director, actor or screenwriter, he said.
   ``Our National Film Commission simply has the responsibility to
determine whether, in fact, certain films are works of art and
deserving of some protection by U.S. government because they are an
enduring part of our national cultural heritage,'' Mrazek said. The
bill seeks $500,000 to create the commission.
   He said the bill also affords full copyright protection to the
creators of designated films and makes it unlawful to colorize or
materially alter these works without changing the titles.
   ``This is the best compromise we could come up with. I think we
have a consensus,'' Mrazek said.
   Asked if his old friend Ronald Reagan agreed with his position,
Stewart mentioned a brief meeting during which the president ``was
very positive in his statement that he was with us all the way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
