<DOCNO> AP880615-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ConcreteMail 1stLd-Writethru a0713 06-15 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Concrete Mail, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office To Cut Concrete Mail Loss</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng: `It will, to CORRECT figures to
$45,000 sted $88,000 and $135,000 sted $98,000 to reflect official
correction by Postal Service. Picks up 5th graf pvs, But that's</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal officials have found a way to cut _ but
not eliminate _ their loss in hauling building materials for an
Alaska shipper.
   An Anchorage building-materials supplier is mailing more than
10,000 concrete blocks and bags of cement about 700 miles to a
remote village, postal officials confirmed Wednesday.
   Each block and bag of cement must be individually addressed to
get within the 70-pound weight limit on parcels.
   ``It will cost us about $180,000 to transport all that stuff,''
spokeswoman Meg Harris said. The postage is expected to bring in
only about $45,000, meaning a loss of about $135,000 for the post
office.
   But that's still considerably better than the loss of $500,000
originally reported for the shipment.
   The postal service is faced with transporting the material for
less than its actual costs because postage rates are universal _
meaning they are the same across the country.
   Thus, the price charged for sending mail is based on the average
cost of delivering it. If the postal service only has to take a
parcel from Cleveland to Dayton, it comes out ahead on the deal.
   If it has to carry concrete blocks 700 miles across the tundra,
or cartons of eggs down into the Grand Canyon, costs exceed the
postage.
   The idea of universal rates, explained Ms. Harris, is that
people do not have to suffer because they reside in rural areas.
   When confronted by an unusual case, however, such as the Alaskan
contractor, the Postal Service's only recourse is to try and find a
way to handle the material for less.
   The original, higher cost estimate for the massive shipment was
projected under a special ``bypass'' mail system used in Alaska,
where groceries and other large, heavy items often are mailed to
rural areas. The bypass system lets mailers bring their items
directly to the airlines, bypassing the post office.
   Ms. Harris said officials have ``decided to bypass the bypass
system,'' at least in the case of the shipment of concrete blocks
and cement.
   Instead, the shipment will be trucked to a mail center at Dead
Horse, Alaska, and flown from there, reducing the agency's overall
costs.
   The shipment, 6,000 blocks and 4,600 bags of cement, is being
sent by Bush Consolidators in Anchorage to the village of
Wainright, about 90 miles from Barrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LowRiver     06-15 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Low River,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Water Hampers Traffic Along Mississippi River</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 750 barges were stranded Wednesday
on the Mississippi River because of low water, and the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers said that twice as many could be stranded by the
weekend.
   The low water has forced barges to operate only during daylight
hours and to lighten their loads, said Jeffrey Smith, vice
president of the American Waterways Operators in Arlington, Va.
   ``Low water _ since the days of Mark Twain _ has been an
occupational hazard, and they know how to deal with it. Things are
somewhat restricted, but cargo is still moving,'' Smith said
Wednesday.
   Mississippi River barges carry such cargo as grain, petroleum,
chemicals, iron and steel, he said.
   The barges began backing up after one ran aground Monday and
large barges decided to wait for a dredge to arrive Thursday to
deepen the channel.
   The river is only 9 feet deep near Vaucluse Landing, Ark., about
3 miles north of the Greenville, Miss. bridge.
   ``They are skittish about using it because one mess-up costs
lots of dollars,'' said Michael Logue, spokesman for the corps'
Vicksburg District.
   Ron Goldman, the district's chief of water control management,
said the Mississippi is at its lowest point for this time of year
since records were first kept in 1872.
   The Vicksburg gauge read 2.5 feet on Tuesday, he said. The
lowest level on record is minus 7 feet in February 1940, when much
of the upper river froze. Without significant rainfall, the river
will fall below zero on the Vicksburg gauge within two weeks,
Goldman said, with zero on the gauge representing 46.2 feet above
mean sea level.
   Louis Logue, the district's chief of river operations, said the
river is expected to keep falling and other problem sites could
develop.
   ``I'm talking seriously with the Lord about this now,'' he said.
``Up until now I've just been talking regularly.''
   Logue said barges and tows generally require 9 to 10 feet of
water. Each barge carries an average cargo of 1,000 tons.
   Bob Gardner, vice president of ContiCarriers in Chicago, said
the low water was also creating bottlenecks near Memphis and Cairo,
Ill.
   ``The low water is definitely causing us some disruptions on the
lower Mississippi,'' said Gardner, a former Mississippi River
captain.
   He said his company has reduced the number of barges to a
maximum of 20 per tow and some lines are running only in daylight
hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
