<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Retireless     06-15 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Retireless,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>92-Year-Old Back to Work After Finding Fourth Retirement
Unsatisfying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAK LAWN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old habits die hard, which may explain why
Clarence Walker occupies a stool at Western Tool and Die Works each
morning when nearly all his contemporaries are deep in easy chairs.
   Retirement, says the 92-year-old, was no more satisfying the
fourth time than the first.
   ``The reason I'm back at work is because I want to live a while
longer,'' Walker said during a telephone interview Wednesday.
``Without work, I was laying around, just kind of dying.
   ``My mind was going blank and I didn't know what to do with
myself,'' he added. ``I didn't need the money so much as something
to do.''
   Walker's last job lasted more than a decade and his fourth try
at full-time leisure for three years after that, most of it spent
watching television and enjoying the company of his gray cat,
Smokey.
   Feeling he was getting stale, Walker bought a new pickup truck,
renewed his habit of ``wandering'' on weekends, then enrolled in
Operation ABLE, a county-funded job program to help people 55 and
older find work.
   He landed at Western Tool and Die, a subsidiary of Chicago-based
Eastco Corp., which draws as much as 30 percent of its workforce
from the 65-and-over crowd.
   ``He's happy to be working and we're just as happy to have
him,'' said Eastco President George Patrick Pollack. ``Talking to
him or looking at him ... or listening to him trade barbs with the
guys on the (assembly) line, you'd never guess his age.
   ``It's only when he walks that you can see him slowing down,''
added Pollack.
   Walker has rheumatoid arthritis in both knees and needs two
canes. But thanks to the pickup, he still spends most weekends
criss-crossing Wisconsin, where he owns five acres of land, and
Michigan.
   ``I got lost Sunday on the way back from Michigan, but I just
figured that kind of thing is the spice of life,'' he said. ``I've
always had a yearning to see what's on the other side of the hill.''
   That yearning prompted Walker to join the Army _ he was a chief
cook in Winchester, England, during World War I _ and several years
later to quit a job as a bakery truck driver and rode the rails out
West for a year and a half.
   ``It was,'' he says, ``the best time of my life.''
   Walker returned to Wisconsin and began working steadily again,
and married in 1923. He and his wife of 52 years, Anna, had five
children. She died in 1975.
   Walker first retired at 65, from Modern Machinery in Cudahy,
Wis. He was back a year later, but left two years after that
because he hit the mandatory retirement age of 68.
   He drove a school bus outside Milwaukee the next four years, but
``at 72, they told me I was too old; they couldn't get insurance.''
   So after gardening at his Wisconsin home, he moved to Illinois
in the early 1970s, went to work for Chicago Cylinder for more than
10 years, then made another try at retirement before landing his
current job.
   Walker concedes that inspecting 6-inch electrical wires for
defects six hours a day, five days a week is boring work. But he's
done assembly-line work before, the pay _ $7 an hour _ isn't bad,
and it beats sitting around the house.
   ``When you're 65 retirement isn't too bad because you have some
friends around and your family,'' said Walker. ``When you're 90,
you don't have any friends left and your kids have got their own
lives to lead so you don't want to be with them all the time either.
   ``That's why this working business is so nice. I never could sit
still.''
</TEXT>
