<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0791,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Holds `Meaningful Discussion' With Dukakis Running Mate
Searcher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES in top 6 grafs with Jackson further comments on
meeting, picking up 4th graf pvs, Dukakis, who ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said he held a ``meaningful
preliminary discussion'' on Wednesday with the Michael Dukakis'
campaign aide interviewing potential running mates, but said he has
not decided if he wants the spot.
   Following a meeting with the Congressional Black Caucus, in
which members urged him to seek the post, Jackson revealed he had
talked to Dukakis' campaign chairman Paul Brountas earlier in the
day about the matter.
   ``It was a very meaningful preliminary discussion,'' he told a
news conference.
   Later in an interview on Cable News Network, Jackson elaborated
briefly, saying, ``We simply discussed today the process, discussed
the guidelines, we talked about the requirements. After all, we
need to know what the rules are, what the standarsds will be.''
   Jackson also made clear he wants to discuss a range of issues,
in addition to the vice presidency, with the Dukakis camp. He said
he is prepared to go to the convention floor if Dukakis balks on
Jackson's key budget items of increasing taxes on the wealthy and
corporations and a military spending freeze.
   ``Of course, that's the proper mechanism and it's the thing to
do,'' he told CNN when asked if he would wage a floor fight over
those issues.
   Dukakis, who already has the delegate strength to win the
Democratic presidential nomination at the party's convention in
July, has designated Brountas to prospect for running mate
possibilities.
   Dukakis has previously said that Jackson will be considered, but
not that he will get any special consideration by virtue of his
runner-up status.
   Jackson made clear he would like the offer to be made to him
although he has declined to say that in so many words publicly,
instead stating that it is Dukakis' option.
   Black Caucus Chairman Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., said there was a
consensus among the caucus members that ``we ought to urge Reverand
Jackson to seek the seocnd spot on the ticket.''
   He said Jackson reacted privately with the congressmen as he
does publicly on the issue and did not go further in disclosing
whether he would accept it if offered.
   ``I've not yet made that decision,`` Jackson told reporters. ``I
have stated very clearly I`ve earned the right of serious
consideration.''
   Despite all the talk of the vice presidency, Jackson has not
officially conceded the presidential nomination to Dukakis. He said
earlier Wednesday that he has no intention of throwing the governor
his support before the convention, and said of his former
Democratic rivals who are lining up behind Dukakis: ``They lost and
surrendered. I did not. We're not in the same category.''
   The Black Caucus members said they want to meet with Dukakis and
lobby him to put Jackson on the ticket as his running mate.
   ``We come in with a candidate ... It seems to me that Governor
Dukakis has to come up with a better candidate, or at least be
prepared to share with us why he does not believe that Reverand
Jackson is the best candidate,'' if he does not choose Jackson,
said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y. He added ``nobody in this room''
can think of a better choice than Jackson.
   ``We want Governor Dukakis to say ... why he believes that
Reverand Jackson is a liability for the ticket,'' if in fact that
is the governor's decision, he said.
   One caucus member, Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., said he would not
support the Democratic ticket if Jackson was not on it and he felt
there was racism in keeping him off.
   But Dymally said Savage was the only one to voice that opinion,
and others said they would be faithful to the Demcratic ticket
regardless.
   Jackson, during a two-day swing through Washington, also said
Wednesday that his ``most critical'' political concern now is for
the Democratic convention to accept his budget priorities.
   Jackson's proposals include increased taxes on the wealthy and
corporations, and a military budget freeze to pay for social
programs.
   ``The most critical becomes this budget, a commitment to invest
in people, a commitment to reinvest in America,'' Jackson said
following a meeting with leaders of civil rights groups.
   
 
