<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nuclear-Drugs 3rdLd-Writethru a0838 06-15 0953</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear-Drugs, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0838,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Probe at Nuclear Weapons Lab Prematurely Shut Down, House
Told</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 15th graf pvs bgng, `Leary once,' with 1 graf to CORRECT
that Leary was 2nd in command of department, head of Operation
Snowstorm</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department prematurely shut down an
undercover investigation of widespread drug trafficking at a
top-secret California nuclear weapons laboratory and tried to
prevent Congress from finding out, House investigators were told
Wednesday.
   At the time the drug investigation, code-named ``Operation
Snowstorm,'' was killed, agents were still pursuing leads on 127
employees at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, near San
Francisco, who were suspected drug users or dealers, witnesses said.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said the nine-month investigation was
abruptly halted in September 1986 because officials were fearful of
publicity about rampant drug trafficking at Livermore, where highly
classified research into President Reagan's Star Wars missile
defense system is conducted.
   ``It seems to me that this Operation Snowstorm should be called
`Operation Snow Job','' Wyden said. He said DOE officials ``seem to
think just saying no is enough. DOE is too afraid of the stigma of
drugs to do anything about it.''
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations, declared:
``We have serious questions about the integrity of security at our
nation's most sensitive nuclear weapons and research facilities.''
   Dingell said that after DOE and Livermore officials shut down
the drug investigation, they ``attempted to conceal this fact from
the subcommittee by providing conflicting statements to the
subcommittee staff and by withholding key documents.''
   Energy Undersecretary Joseph F. Salgado said officials decided
to terminate the investigation ``because it had run for eight
months and was apparently not uncovering new productive leads.''
   He said Operation Snowstorm had served its purpose in putting
Livermore employees on notice that drug use would not be tolerated.
Salgado denied that the Energy Department had attempted a cover-up.
   In a report circulated in advance of the hearing, Dingell said
Operation Snowstorm began in January 1986 because of ``an alarming
number of laboratory employees who were becoming involved in
drug-related incidents and arrests,'' including the sale of
computers and other government property for drug money.
   David A. Leary, who managed the undercover investigation,
testified that many of the drug pushers among Livermore's 8,500
employees held top-secret ``Q'' security clearances. He said the
illicit drugs they were selling included cocaine, marijuana,
methamphetamine and barbiturates.
   By contrast with Salgado's testimony, Leary said his
investigators were still pursuing 127 leads when the probe was
halted.
   Dingell quoted John Hunt, head of safeguards and security at
Livermore, as telling investigators that if Operation Snowstorm had
been allowed to continue, ``we would have to arrest 20 percent of
the lab.''
   Dingell also said that Leary and three other Livermore leaders
of Operation Snowstorm were effectively demoted when the
investigation was halted, and were barred from dealing further with
the laboratory's drug problems.
   ``When Leary resisted pressure to shut down Operation Snowstorm,
his career took a nose dive,'' Dingell said.
   Leary once supervised 200 employees as second in command of the
laboratory's safeguards and security department and as head of
Operation Snowstorm, Dingell said, but four months after the
investigation was terminated, Leary was working in Livermore's
laser program where he supervised no one.
   Salgado said the four were given ``diminished responsibilities.''
   Detective Robert Buda, who was recruited as an undercover agent
from the University of California police force for the
investigation, said he was ``very, very surprised'' at being able
to make his first drug purchase from a Livermore employee within
one week.
   Buda said this convinced him that drug traffickers regarded
classified areas of the laboratory as ``a complete sanctuary where
they were untouchable.''
   Within a few months, the panel was told, confidential informants
had fingered 35 suspected dealers or drug users at the laboratory,
many of whom held sensitive ``Q'' clearances.
   Buda said he was ``flabbergasted'' to learn that the
investigation was terminated three days before he received
clearance to pursue drug suspects in Livermore's classified ``green
badge'' area.
   ``We felt like the kid in front of the candy store,'' said John
C. Barber, the University of California police chief who served as
consultant to Operation Snowstorm.
   ``We had the money in our hands and we were ready to go inside
and do business,'' Barber said. ``But the investigation was shut
down before we reached the goal we'd set out to accomplish.''
   In May 1986, midway through the investigation, security agent
Timothy L. Mitchell said he told his superiors at Livermore that a
laboratory chemist had bought a 65-foot houseboat, was throwing
weekly champagne parties and was flashing wads of $100 bills.
   Mitchell said he told James Kahn, associate director at
Livermore, that the chemist's extravagant lifestyle, which he could
not afford on his salary, suggested he was involved either in drug
trafficking or espionage.
   According to Mitchell, Kahn replied: ``What's the matter, are
you just jealous?''
   Mitchell said Kahn ``told me to let DOE deal with security, and
you just butt out.''
   ``From the beginning there has been reluctance among senior
managers at the laboratory to acknowledge there was a drug issue in
classified areas of the laboratory,'' Mitchell said.
   Mitchell said the volume of drug trafficking at Livermore ``has
the potential to endanger national security.'' Under questioning by
Dingell, Buda agreed that the sale of computers and other sensitive
laboratory equipment in drug transactions ``could jeopardize
national defense secrets.''
   Dingell said the subcommittee staff has evidence that senior DOE
officials exerted pressure on authorities at Livermore to shut down
Operation Snowstorm prematurely and to conceal Operation Snowstorm
from House investigators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
