<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SoccerInvasion 1stLd-Writethru a0783 06-15 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Invasion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0783,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soccer Fans Fight; Riot Police Patrol</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with late developments, detail</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   English, Dutch and West German
fans brawled outside boarded-up bars after a championship soccer
game Wednesday but patrolling riot squads prevented large-scale
violence.
   Some officers held unmuzzled dogs on chains as they patrolled
near bars still open. Duesseldorf mobilized more than 2,300 police
officers.
   More than 200 people had been detained by Wednesday night,
according to official and unofficial figures. Police said most
would be held only briefly.
   Most bars in Duesseldorf's Old City were closed, and many
boarded up to avoid the kind of damage caused during street fights
the night before.
   More than 40,000 English and Dutch soccer fans were in
Duesseldorf for the European Soccer Championship series match
between their national teams.
   Fistfights broke out throughout the city after the Netherlands
won the game 3-1. Soccer fans filled the streets and the area near
the main railroad station, where West German, Dutch and English
brawled Wednesday night.
   Riot police broke up the fight and arrested about 20 people,
witnesses said.
   Minor scuffles between West German and English rowdies were
reported inside the station while the English waited for trains
leaving the city. Riot police were seen taking three people away.
   British fans sang ``God Save the Queen'' and shouted insults at
West German rivals, the British news agency Press Association
reported.
   By midnight the station and surrounding streets were nearly
clear of everyone except police, and streets of the Old City were
reported quiet.
   Just before the game, 150 West Germans were detained temporarily
while trying to march from downtown to the stadium. Police said
those arrested planned to incite battles between English and Dutch
fans, and that 39 other West Germans were detained for the same
reason.
   Thirteen English hooligans were arrested for disorderly conduct
or drunkenness earlier Wednesday.
   No violence was reported during the game.
   British Sports Minister Colin Moynihan was in Duesseldorf on a
fact-finding mission for Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   He told Press Association the English soccer rowdies ``are worse
than animals, because I know of no animals which would behave in
this manner.''
   Police spokesman Wolfgang Rodax said riot officers rounded up
about 200 drunken English fans near the rail station in the
afternoon and took them to the stadium by bus _ ``to defuse the
volatile situation at the train station.'' He said police dispersed
about 200 Dutch fans who were planning to ``move in on the train
station to confront'' the English.
   West Germany's ZDF television showed a man bleeding from the
head after a street fight. Also shown on West German TV was a
pistol that was confiscated, but the owner was not identified.
   Police used breathing devices to test alcohol levels before
letting fans into the stadium and scanned them with metal detectors
for knives and other weapons.
   Bert Millichip, chairman of the British Football (Soccer)
Association, told Press Association in Duesseldorf: ``People say
that if there was not a football match these hooligans wouldn't be
here _ and you cannot argue against that principle. ... These
people should not have been allowed to come here in the first
instance.''
   British clubs were barred from European Cup tournaments after a
rampage by British fans that left 39 people dead at a European Cup
final in Brussels, Belgium, three years ago. The ban did not
include the national team.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
