<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Firmenich     06-15 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Firmenich,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Guerrilla Leader Mario Firmenich Given Life In Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge sentenced a
former guerilla leader to life in prison Wednesday for the murders
of an Argentine businessman and his bodyguard and for his role in
the attempted murder of a Cabinet member.
   Mario Firmenich, who led the Montoneros guerrillas and is
already serving a life prison sentence, will serve a maximum 30
years in prison under terms of an extradition agreement with
Brazil, which returned him to Argentina in 1984.
   Federal Judge Martin Irurzun ruled that Firmenich, 40, killed
businessman Francisco Soldatti and his bodyguard, policeman Ricardo
Duran, in 1979. Firmenich was also found guilty as
``co-determinator'' in the 1979 wounding of former Treasury
Secretary Juan Alemann in an attack in downtown Buenos Aires.
   Among evidence presented were press communiques issued by the
Montoneros under Firmenich's leadership, including an instruction
manual telling how to carry out commando-style attacks against the
government and its forces.
   Firmenich was given a life term earlier for the 1974 kidnapping
of grain industrialists Juan and Jorge Born, whose bodyguards were
killed in the abduction. The Born brothers were freed after payment
of a $60 million ransom.
   The Supreme Court has repeatedly rejected appeals filed by
Firmenich and his lawyers for his release from a Buenos Aires
penitentiary.
   Firmenich led the Montoneros during the turbulent 1970s when
Argentina was wracked by social and economic chaos. The Montoneros
battled police and the armed forces and kidnapped foreign and local
industrialists for ransom before being virtually eliminated.
   The chaos continued even after a 1976 military coup replaced
President Isabel Peron, eventually resulting in a bloody campaign
by military forces to wipe out leftist subversion.
   That campaign, dubbed the ``dirty war,'' resulted in the
disappearance and presumed deaths of at least 9,000 suspected
subversives. Human rights groups say up to 30,000 people
``disappeared'' before civilian rule was restored in 1983 with the
election of President Raul Alfonsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
