<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0816,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Planted In Military Van Explodes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with sixth soldier dying of
injuries; police saying bomb planted in military van, sted of
truck, details; CORRECTS that it worst attack against army since
1982, sted 1979. PICKUP 10th graf pvs `Eyewitness Sanford ....
Includes LaserPhoto number.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON28</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A booby-trap bomb planted in a
military van exploded Wednesday night in Lisburn, killing six
soldiers who had taken part in a charity race and injuring at least
10 civilians, police said.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for the bombing and for the
shooting death earlier Wednesday of a Protestant paramilitary chief
in Belfast.
   Belfast police said the ``no warning'' bomb went off as about
4,000 people completed a charity race in Lisburn, a town 7 miles
southeast of Belfast that is the main base of the British army in
Northern Ireland.
   An 80-year-old man and a 2-year-old boy were among 10 civilians
injured in the explosion, which police said happened shortly after
9 p.m (4 p.m. EDT). None of the civilians suffered serious
injuries, police said.
   The soldiers had driven to the market square in an unmarked
military van to take part in the amateur race, police said. While
they were away, guerrillas wired a booby-trap bomb to the van's
chassis.
   The bomb exploded when the soldiers returned from the race and
had driven off just a few yards, police said.
   Four soldiers died at the scene, one was pronounced dead on
arrival at a hospital and a sixth died after undergoing surgery for
head injuries, police said.
   The death toll was the highest against the army since a 1982
bombing in the a pub in Ballykelly, near Londonderry, killed 11
soldiers and six civilians. An IRA offshoot, the Irish National
Liberation Army, claimed responsibility.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. reported that the IRA said it
carried out Wednesday's bombing in a message to news media in
Belfast.
   Reporter Daryl Fitzsimons of Downtown Radio, a Belfast station,
who was at the scene, reported: ``The bomb exploded ... blowing the
heart out of the town center.''
   Eyewitness Sandford Fitzpatrick said on the broadcast: ``I saw
one person in the middle of the road with blood coming out of his
head ... It's absolute chaos here ... There were thousands of
people in the town for the race, from all over Ireland.''
   The man killed in Belfast earlier Wednesday was identified by
the Royal Ulster Constabulary as Bobby ``Blood'' Seymour, 33, a
known gunman for the outlawed Ulster Volunteer Force.
   He was jailed for life in 1981 for the murder of a Catholic who
was believed to be a high-ranking IRA member. Seymour was released
when an appeals court dismissed an informer's testimony.
   Several hours after Seymour was shot in an alley behind his
video shop in east Belfast by two masked gunmen who fled in a car,
the IRA made telephone calls to the media claiming responsibility
for his killing. It said the shooting was in retaliation for
attacks on Roman Catholics.
   The car used by the attackers later was found abandoned in the
Markets area of the city, and the police said a man arrested there
was being questioned about the slaying.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the province with the Irish Republic.
