<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeatRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0847 06-15 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0847,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How Hot Was It? ...</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 5-6, `Elsewhere, a...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
tornado injuries.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserColor NY81</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the Northeast and Midwest scorched under another day of
temperatures in the 90s, and heat problems exacerbated by a severe
drought in many areas left people without relief.
   ``It's the kind of thing that makes you sweat even with air
conditioning,'' said Fred Martin, director of utilities in Camden,
N.J.
   An estimated 196,000 people hit the beaches in New York City,
where the temperature hit 96 degrees, tying a 97-year-old record.
It was 98 degrees at midafternoon in Boston, exceeding by 2 degrees
the record set in 1956.
   Records fell like drops of sweat, and the weather officially
became a heat wave, meaning at least three straight days of
temperatures at 90 or higher, in Massachusetts and Rhode Island,
the National Weather Service said.
   Elsewhere, five tornadoes touched down in Colorado in an area 55
miles long from north to south, injuring seven people, none
seriously.
   One tornado hit near Denver's Stapleton International Airport,
where the air traffic control tower was evacuated for about 25
minutes, Stapleton spokesman Richard Bouleware said. There was no
immediate word on effects on air traffic.
   Touchdowns also were reported near Barr Lake, and on Denver's
east side, where hundreds of stately trees collapsed across lawns
and crushed several cars.
   Thunderstorms hit parts of Kansas, Oklahoma and the Texas
Panhandle. An inch and a half of rain fell at Amarillo, Texas, and
scattered showers continued over Florida. Thunderstorms also
developed over parts of Michigan.
   West of the Rocky Mountains, it was sunny, with temperatures
mostly in the 80s.
   The severe heat to the east is being caused by a high-pressure
system off the mid-Atlantic coast pumping in hot air from the south
central part of the country, National Weather Serivice
meteorologist Mike Wyllie said.
   ``Over hundreds and hundreds of miles, the ground is very, very
dry,'' said Peter Lamb of the Illinois State Water Survey. ``So
what the sun is doing is heating the ground and the ground is
heating the air.''
   Efforts to cool off put extraordinary pressure on municipal
water and utility systems, and some communities began ordering
conservation. In northern New Jersey, authorities followed young
people, shutting fire hydrants.
   ``The kids open them up as soon as they get out of school,''
said John Oliver, a regional fire dispatcher in Hudson County, N.J.
``People couldn't flush their toilets. There was low water pressure
all over the place.''
   Low water pressure canceled classes for 1,150 pupils at East
Dover Elementary School in New Jersey. Students in communities in
Maryland and Connecticut were sent home early because of excessive
heat.
   Air quality was unhealthy in parts of the Northeast, especially
where the heat combined with air pollution.
   The Massachusetts Department of Environmental Quality
Engineering said 18 towns have declared water supply emergencies.
Of them, 14 have imposed voluntary water restrictions, spokeswoman
Nan Kates said.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Santa Barbara, Calif., to 103 degrees at Needles, Calif.
   The forecast for Thursday called for widely scattered showers
and thunderstorms from New England across the Ohio Valley,
Arkansas, southern Missouri and parts of the southern Plains.
Thunderstorms will develop in the mountains of Nevada and the
Pacific Northwest. Showers and thunderstorms will continue in
southern Florida.
   High temperatures will be in the 80s to mid-90s over most of the
nation; the 60s and 70s from the Great Lakes region across the
upper Mississippi Valley to eastern North Dakota and along the
Pacific coast; and 100 to 110 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   Some records set Wednesday:
   Albany, N.Y., 96 degrees, broke mark of 95 set in 1891.
   Boston, 98 degrees, broke mark of 96 set in 1956.
   Burlington, Vt., 96 degrees, broke mark of 93 set in 1891.
   Detroit, 94 degrees, broke mark of 93 set in 1976.
   Fort Wayne, Ind., 95 degrees, broke mark of 94 set in 1954
   Hartford, Conn., 97 degrees, broke mark of 95 set in 1957.
   Newark, N.J., 99 degrees, tied mark set in 1945.
   Philadelphia, 97 degrees, tied mark set in 1957.
   Pittsburgh, 93 degrees, broke mark of 92 set in 1967.
   Portland, Maine, 96 degrees, broke mark of 94 set in 1956.
   Syracuse, N.Y., 97 degrees, broke mark of 92 set in 1972.
   Youngstown, Ohio, 92 degrees, tied mark set in 1967.
</TEXT>
