<HEAD>Australian Woman, Thai Man Sentenced to Death For Heroin
Trafficking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Australian woman and a Thai man were
sentenced to death Wednesday for trafficking in 12 pounds of heroin
the woman carried in her 14-month-old son's stroller.
   The Bangkok Criminal Court reduced an earlier death sentence
against the woman's common law husband to life imprisonment after
he admitted to heroin possession and cooperated with authorities.
   Nola Blake; the man she lived with in suburban Sydney, Paul
Hudson; and Supoj Kittidejdamkern were arrested in January 1987 and
charged with possessing heroin with intention to sell.
   Police said Ms. Blake and Hudson, who is also Australian,
obtained the heroin from Supoj for sale in Australia.
   Ms. Blake and Hudson, both 37, were arrested in front of a
department store while pushing their son in a stroller that
contained the heroin, police said. The baby was flown to Australia
to be cared for by relatives in Sydney.
   ``I knew it was coming. I knew it was coming,'' Ms. Blake said
after the verdict, shaking her head as she walked from the court
back to jail.
   Ms. Blake translated the verdict for Hudson, who appeared pale
and shaken.
