<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BaptistConvention 1stLd-Writethru a0800 06-15 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baptist Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0800,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Baptists Modify Key Doctrine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `In a...' with 4 grafs to update with
demonstrations.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Baptists, who a day earlier
elected a fundamentalist to lead them for a 10th straight year, on
Wednesday toned down a hallmark doctrine emphasizing members'
rights to dissent from the clergy.
   That doctrine _ called the ``priesthood of the believer'' _ also
has stood as a hub of the 16th-century Protestant Reformation. The
modified interpretation espoused here was denounced by critics as
reflecting a new clerical authoritarianism.
   ``What it's talking about is denominational dictatorship,'' said
the Rev. Buckner Fanning of San Antonio. ``It says the only way to
lead is by blind obedience.''
   About 200 Baptists assembled late in the afternoon at the Alamo
andceremoniously tore up copies of a resolution passed by the
convention on ``priesthood of the believer.''
   The action ``repudiates the heritage of of Baptists,'' said the
Rev. Randall Lolley, pressured out of the presidency of
Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary along with four acadmic
colleagues by new rules imposed by fundamentalist trustees.
   The demonstrators sang 16th-century Protestant reformer Martin
Luther's rousing hymn, ``A Mighty Fortress is Our God.''
   In the resolution, the convention declared that the idea of the
equal ``priesthood'' of believers should not be applied contrary to
``authority of the pastor, which is seen in the command to the
local church.''
   The concept ``has been used to justify wrongly the attitude that
a Christian may believe whatever he so chooses and still be
considered a loyal Southern Baptist.''
   The ``doctrine in no way gives license to misinterpret, explain
away, demythologize or extrapolate out elements of the supernatural
from the Bible,'' the resolution said.
   Its passage came after a tumultuous session of representatives
of the 14.7 million-member denomination, the nation's largest
Protestant body. For Southern Baptists, the governing body is the
local church.
   Protests that the resolution meant a ``papal system'' of
clerical control and that it undermined Jesus' view that ministers
were servants not masters crackled through the convention hall.
   The Rev. Adrian Rogers of Memphis, Tenn., departing president of
the denomination, halted the discussion and put the matter to a
vote. By a show of hands, it passed by about a two-thirds majority.
   The action came a day after the factionally divided convention
had elected another fundamentalist, the Rev. Jerry Vines of
Jacksonville, Fla., to succeed Rogers. Vines takes over at the
close of the meeting Thursday.
   He narrowly defeated the moderate candidate, the Rev. Richard
Jackson of Phoenix, Ariz.
   Through presidenial appointive powers, the fundamentalist wing
gradually has brought the vast network of denominational operations
under its control. It would take a decade, even with unlikely
successive moderate wins, to reverse the pattern.
   The fundamentalist leadership has stacked institutional boards,
setting stricter rules for literalistic interpretations of the
Bible, and inaugurating screening processes to assure adherence.
   The new qualifying limitations on the universal ``priesthood''
concept was seen as the latest move toward extending clerical
supervision.
   Historically, Baptists, more than any other Protestants, have
stressed freedom, both of individuals from clerical domination and,
of the church from the state and state from the church.
   Besides the equal priesthood-of-all concept, the historic
emphasis has been on autonomy of local churches and ``soul
competence'' of individuals to interpret the Bible.
   Fanning, pastor of Trinity Baptist Church here, said the
universal priesthood notion dates to Protestant Reformers Martin
Luther and John Huss, burned at the stake over it.
   ``It's one of the fundamentals that the fundamentalists
ignore,'' he said, noting that it is also mandated in the New
Testament, calling all believers _ not just the clergy _ ``a royal
priesthood.''
   The the Rev. James Dunn of Washington, D.C., director of the
inter-Baptist Joint Committee on Public Affairs, said the
fundamentalists ``don't know what Baptist means.''
   Meanwhile, the denomination's ``peace committee,'' set up to try
to settle the prolonged factional conflict, went out of business,
lamenting that peace has not been achieved.
   ``We deplore the divisive political activities and counter
activities by all sides this past year,'' said the chairman, the
Rev. Charles Fuller of Roanoke, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
