<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Landecker wasn't going to let a
little chicken pox keep him from the first day of his new job _ not
after what he did to get it.
   Landecker was hired Monday by radio station KKSU after he spent
the day sitting on Main Street with a sign that said, ``I am Bob
Landecker. I need a job.''
   Cliff Shank, who needed a program director and afternoon
announcer for KKSU, stopped by.
   ``Anyone who has got the gumption to do that might be someone
worth looking at,'' Shank said.
   Landecker went on the air Tuesday.
   ``I started breaking out right before my first show,'' said
Landecker, who worked in a secluded room.
   Landecker said he once worked for a public relations company in
Ponca City, Okla. He said he got the idea to advertise for a job
from a radio announcer in Tulsa who rented a billboard and received
several offers.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood has gone crackers over its newest
star.
   A replica of a slab from the Hollywood Walk of Fame was
presented Wednesday to ``Belle,'' a big cheese from Wisconsin.
   Photographers seemed to take the presentation in stride, even
though the ``Belle of Wisconsin'' said ``cheese'' without smiling,
and doesn't come close to the kind of Hollywood cheesecake they're
accustomed to.
   ``Belle'' weighs in at 40,000 pounds, is 20 feet long, over 5{
feet wide and 5-feet-10. More than 3,500 cows and 37,000 dairymen
worked to produce it earlier this year in Little Chute, Wis.
   The block of cheese was presented with the star replica as
promoters prepared for a cross-country tour in a specially designed
``cheesemobile'' trailer, complete with glass-sided walls.
   The chunk of Cheddar has been acclaimed by Guinness as the
world's largest, outdoing the previous Wisconsin-bred titleholder,
``The Golden Giant,'' by 5,409 pounds.
   ``Belle,'' accompanied on tour by ``The Big Cheese Escort,''
Susan Hughes, will parade through 36 cities with a dozen hungry
mice in hot pursuit.
   The whole affair is being sponsored by the Wisconsin Milk
Marketing Board Inc., to promote the state, which supplies nearly
40 percent of the country's cheese.
</TEXT>
