<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionDispute     06-15 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Dispute,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elkhart County Woman Can Have Abortion After Courts Decline To
Intervene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court order barring a woman from having an
abortion expired Wednesday, after two U.S. Supreme Court justices
and Indiana's highest court rejected emergency requests to continue
the ban.
   The Elkhart Superior Court order expired at 4 p.m., removing the
last obstacle preventing the woman, identified in court documents
by the pseudonym Jane Smith, from ending her pregnancy.
   The woman's attorney, Richard Waples of the Indiana Civil
Liberties Union, said he didn't know if or when she would undergo
an abortion. ``That's her decision,'' he said. ``It's really
nobody's business, not even mine.''
   Before the lower court order expired, U.S. Supreme Court
Justices John Paul Stevens and Byron R. White refused to issue
emergency orders sought by the Evansville man who claims to be the
father of the fetus.
   The man claimed his interests should be weighed before the woman
was allowed to have an abortion.
   Robert J. Palmer, attorney for the man identified in court
documents only as John Doe, said his client was ``very upset. It
was a difficult telephone call to make to him.''
   Late Wednesday afternoon, the state Supreme Court also rejected
a request to reconsider its earlier decision not to prevent the
abortion.
   Palmer said he plans to appeal to the Indiana Supreme Court,
which agreed Tuesday to accept jurisdiction over the case while
refusing to bar an abortion while the substantive legal arguments
were made.
   The woman is about eight weeks pregnant, according to court
documents. After she scheduled an abortion, the man went to court
two weeks ago.
   The case is the second in Indiana in which a man claiming to be
the father of a fetus has tried to stop an abortion. In April, a
Terre Haute woman underwent an abortion in defiance of a court
order barring the operation.
   That case, also initiated by a man claiming to be the father, is
being reviewed by the Indiana Court of Appeals.
</TEXT>
