<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Japan-BuyingBack Adv20   06-15 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Buying Back, Adv 20,0790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs June 20 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Products Made Abroad Attract Buyers In Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yoshifumi Kaneda is very proud of his new Honda. It
looks like an ordinary 2-door Accord _ except that it was made in
the United States.
   ``I like it a lot because it's unique in Japan,'' said Kaneda,
36, who works in the Tokyo office of a French pharmaceutical
company.
   For one thing, it has left-hand drive, while Japanese domestic
cars have right-hand drive, like cars in Britain.
   ``I was thinking about buying a BMW first, but everyone has BMWs
and Mercedes in Japan these days,'' Kaneda said. ``So, instead, I
decided to go for something very different, very unique, very
peculiar.''
   Kaneda's Honda is one of the very first Accord coupes made in
the United States and imported to Japan starting in April.
   A upsurge in the value of the Japanese yen against the dollar by
more than 50 percent in two years has made Japanese products less
competitive in overseas markets. Export-based Japanese companies
wasted no time shifting production bases abroad, looking for
cheaper production and labor costs.
   Today, products made at those overseas factories are beginning
to flood into Japan. And the affluent Japanese consumers, with
their ever-stronger yen and a big appetite for distinguished
products, are eagerly buying them up.
   In fiscal 1987, Japan imported $1.6 billion worth of products
from overseas subsidiaries of Japanese companies, according to the
Ministry of International Trade and Industry. The ministry projects
that figure will jump to about $2.5 billion this year.
   Following the much-scrutinized reimporation of Accords from
Honda's Ohio factory, Mazda Motor Co. has decided to begin selling
its U.S.-made subcompact Probe later this month. Honda also imports
500 units of 1,500-cubic-centimeter motorcycles from its U.S.
factory in Marysville, Ohio.
   Kirin Brewery, Japan's largest beermaker, is now selling Kirin
Export made for sale in West Germany, while its rival Sapporo
Brewery imports a soft drink called Sapporo Wow from Hansen Foods
based in Los Angeles.
   Consumer analysts see the trend as an ideal mix of Japanese
traditional adoration for foreign products and the steadfast
confidence in domestic-made products.
   ``Today's young Japanese do not know the days when Japanese
products were notorious for being cheap but poorly made,'' said
Kazuma Shindo, a chief researcher at the Hakuhodo Consumer Research
Institute. ``Their perception of Japanese products usually is that
they are the most reliable in the world in quality but a bit
boring. For them, reimported goods satisfies their hunger for
identity without sacrificing the quality.''
   The idea of reimportation is not necessarily new for Japanese
companies.
   Electronics companies, most of them heavily export-dependent,
launched their offshore move immediately after the yen's
appreciation began in mid-1985.
   Sony Corp., often depicted as a symbol of Japan's export-based
economic miracle, imported TV tubes from its U.S. subsidiary in
1985. Also, Fujitsu has been importing computer disks from the
United States for more than two years.
   But analysts said the more recent reimport boom differs from
that of a few years ago.
   Geoffrey Wilkinson, a market analyst for Salomon Bros.
investment firm in Tokyo, said the reimport boom began as a means
of making greater profit, taking advantage of currency fluctuations.
   However, many companies now are reimporting products to protect
themselves politically from protectionist sentiment in the United
States, and to improve their image, he said.
   Honda officials said they were stunned by the response to their
reimport drive.
   ``We implemented the measure as part of our efforts to set up a
global network,'' said Hiroshi Ohshima, spokesman for Honda. ``But
to be honest, we did not anticipate such a response.''
   Ohshima said 1,500 units have been reserved already and the
waiting period can be as long as five months. Honda expects its
first year target of 5,000 units will be cleared easily. Ohshima
said by 1991, Honda wants to increase the reimports to as many
50,000 units.
   But some customers hope the reimported Accord will remain a rare
item in Japan.
   Yoshifumi Kaneda said that when he ordered his American Accord,
a friend did also. But the friend canceled his order when he
learned of the company's plan to import 5,000 units this year.
   ``He was looking for something different,'' said Kaneda. ``He
told me that he couldn't stand the idea that 4,999 others own the
same car as his. I am not sure if I would have bought this car if
Honda's plan was 20,000 units a year instead of 5,000.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs June 20</NOTE>
