   Smaller proportions of people have
preferences for mainline denominations than was the case in the
1960's and mid-1970's, says the Religious Research Center.
   It says a poll of 14,147 adults show these declines in
percentage expressing preferences for various major denominations:
   For Methodists, now 9 percent, down from 11 percent in 1976; for
Lutherans, now 6 percent, down from 7 percent in l976; for
Presbyterians, now 3 percent, down from 5 percent in l976; for
Episcopalians, now 2 percent, down from 3.
