<1ST_LINE>s w BC-DeathRow-Scotus Adv19   06-15 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Death Row-Scotus, Adv 19,0665</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Ponders Fine Points of Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having upheld the use of capital punishment
since 1976, the Supreme Court now is considering whether the death
penalty is appropriate for killers who committed their crimes as
juveniles.
   The justices are expected to decide soon whether an Oklahoma
man's death sentence for a murder he committed when he was 15 is a
type of ``cruel and unusual punishment'' banned by the Constitution.
   The case, along with three other death-penalty disputes the high
court is studying, gives the justices their latest chance to
fine-tune the administration of capital punishment.
   ``It is hard to find a broad-based constitutional challenge to
the death penalty today,'' said Henry Schwarzchild of the
pro-abolition American Civil Liberties Union's capital punishment
project. ``I'm not aware of any in the works that are national in
scope.''
   He added: ``The Supreme Court isn't going to make any major
changes in the administration of capital punishment until the
American culture wants major changes, and right now the culture is
in an extraordinarily macho mood.''
   The number of prisoners executed since the Supreme Court's
ruling in 1976 that allowed states to resume capital punishment
reached 100 last week, with the death of convicted murder Edward R.
Byrne in Louisiana on Tuesday.
   Leigh Dingerson of the National Coalition to Abolish the Death
Penalty is one of those closely following the Oklahoma case.
   ``The court has the opportunity to bring us out of the depths of
being among the few countries that execute kids,'' she said.
   Oklahoma Assistant Attorney General David W. Lee told the
justices, however, that ``chronological age is an inherently poor
criterion'' for determining which convicted killers should be
executed.
   How the court decides the fate of William Wayne Thompson, now
21, will affect only 30 of the more than 2,100 death row inmates
nationwide, but the case of Thompson vs. Oklahoma nevertheless has
captured worldwide attention.
   Three other death penalty issues are expected to be decided by
the high court by July:
   _In Ross vs. Oklahoma, the convicted killer of an Oklahoma
policeman is arguing that he is entitled to a new trial because his
was tainted by a jury-selection error.
   During jury selection at Bobby Lynn Ross' trial, a potential
juror said he would vote to impose the death penalty _ and would
not even consider a life sentence _ if Ross were convicted.
   The judge refused to diqualify the person ``for cause,'' and
Ross' lawyer used one of nine ``peremptory challenges'' to oust the
potential juror. Ross says the judge's error tainted the jury's
make-up in a way that made a fair trial impossible.
   _A case that could affect a significant number of the some 260
death row inmates in Texas is Franklin vs. Lynaugh.
   Convicted killer Donald Gene Franklin argues that Texas' capital
punishment law, as interpreted by the state's courts, stacks the
deck in favor of death over life in prison.
   Texas courts say judges are not required to tell jurors about
the relevance or importance of mitigating evidence, that which
points to life in prison rather than death as the punishment.
   Franklin wanted his jury to be told it must consider his
character, prison record and capacity for rehabilitation when
assessing his future dangerousness.
   _In Johnson vs. Mississippi, Samuel Bice Johnson's sentencing
jury was told about his 1963 conviction for assault in New York.
The prior conviction was considered an aggravating circumstance but
that conviction subsequently was set aside by New York courts.
   Mississippi's courts, however, refused to conduct a new
sentencing trial for Johnson.
   The justices already have ruled in five death penalty cases
during their current term, none of which is expected to carry much
impact beyond the respective states involved.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Adv for Sunday, June 19</HEAD>
</DOC>
