<DOCNO> AP880615-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-DeathRow-Connecticut Adv19   06-15 0879</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Death Row-Connecticut, Adv 19,0908</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv19</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Inmate Has Lonely Existence Awaiting Death Appeal In Connecticut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOMERS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Death Row in Connecticut is just one
prisoner, separated by a cinderblock wall from an inoperable
electric chair.
   The chair known as ``Old Sparky'' hasn't worked since 1960, when
it was in another prison, and state officials aren't sure the
electrical system in Somers State Prison is up to delivering the
2,000-volt shock.
   ``If the wheels grind through, the state will do what it has to
do,'' said Lt. James Burke, a correction officer at Somers.
   Michael B. Ross, who was convicted of raping and murdering six
young women, may be years away from an execution date.
   Last summer, Ross became the first and still the only person
sentenced to die under Connecticut's 1980 law, which rules out the
death penalty if there is any mitigating factor such as emotional
distress. Jurors must also find an aggravating factor, such as a a
particularly heinous crime.
   The law prescribes an automatic appeal, a process which state
officials say could take as long as eight years.
   Connecticut is one of 37 states that have death penalty laws,
one of 34 in which a prisoner is under sentence, and the only state
with a single condemned prisoner.
   The state's electric chair, which was installed in the
maximum-security prison in Wethersfield in 1937, was used in 18
executions. The last was Joseph ``Mad Dog'' Taborsky, who was put
to death May 17, 1960 after being convicted of six murders. The
Wethersfield prison has since been demolished.
   Correction Department spokeswoman Connie Wilks said it has been
estimated that it would cost at least $10,000 to hook up the chair
at Somers.
   The state doesn't have an executioner and would be required to
find a master electrician if a prisoner should be put to death,
Burke added.
   Ross, 29, lives next to the chair, in a 6-by-10 foot cell that
was designed as the final holding area for inmates on their way to
the death chamber.
   He was arrested in 1984 on charges he killed six women between
ages 14 to 23. He pleaded no contest to two of the murders in June
1985 and was sentenced to 120 years in prison.
   Last year, he was convicted of kidnapping, raping and strangling
two women aged 17 and 19, and of kidnapping and murdering two
14-year-olds.
   Testimony by friends, family and psychiatric experts portrayed
him as a sick man whose drive to rape and kill was rooted in a
tormented childhood, but the jury rejected that as a mitigating
factor.
   A gangly six-footer with wire-rim glasses, Ross spends his time
writing and reading. The Cornell University graduate is separated
from other inmates by a wall, but he can hear their banter through
a doorway that is usually kept open. Ross has a string tied to the
knob so that he can close the metal door when he wants quiet.
   Outside the door are seven other cells designed as death row but
now used as a segregation unit for unruly or dangerous inmates.
   ``I understand why I'm being held in the death cell, the theory
being, why empty out death row and lose seven cells for one inmate,
especially with the sytem overcrowding at present?'' Ross said in a
letter responding to questions from The Associated Press.
``However, while I understand it, I'm not sure it is the correct
action to take.''
   A camera outside his cell monitors Ross continuously.
   ``Even though the camera is always there and always watching, it
is less obtrusive than a guard and can for the most part be
ignored,'' Ross wrote. ``However, it does occasionally get lonely
down here and I do have more trouble getting those things that I'm
entitled to.''
   He said he would like a desk, shelves and a window in his cell.
   He is allowed one visit per week, plus one other visit every
other weekend.
   Some prosecutors have complained that Connecticut law makes the
death penalty too difficult to impose, because it is nullified by
any mitigating circumstance.
   The sharp division on death penalty laws was apparent last year
when the state House narrowly voted down a bill to abolish the
death penalty, then approved another which would make capital
punishment easier to impose. That bill died in the Senate.
   This year, capital punishment was not a significant issue in the
Legislature.
   A poll last year of 500 adult residents of Connecticut found
that 69 percent supported the death penalty, although a majority
expressed a preference for lethal injection rather than
electrocution.
   Diane Randall of the Connecticut Network Against the Death
Penalty said the Ross case is a tough one for death penalty
opponents. There is no question of guilt, and there is no question
of racial bias _ both killer and victims were white.
   ``Those kinds of cases _ mass murderers, or horrendous things
like that _ are hard to combat,'' she said.
   ``One of the things we have talked about is how can we be
sensitive to people who have suffered, and yet say that the
response to that pain is not to inflict more inhumanity?''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Adv for Sunday, June 19</HEAD>
</DOC>
