<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Participants, Adv 19-1st Add,0779</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>TORONTO: and 1988.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PREMIER CIRIACO DE MITA, Italy</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   De Mita, who is determined to bring Italy's byzantine political
system closer to the style of other Western democracies, was chosen
in April to lead Italy's 48th post-war government.
   The 60-year-old veteran of Italy's volatile political scene has
led the dominant Christian Democrats since 1982, a post widely
considered the most powerful in Italy.
   When he became premier, De Mita demanded that the party allow
him to remain leader of the Christian Demcorats _ something no
premier had done for 29 years. He argued that it would give him the
authority to govern effectively and the Christian Democrats agreed,
though a leadership fight is expected within a year.
   The always nattily dressed son of a tailor, De Mita was born in
Nusco, a poor mountain village east of Naples. He studied law at
the Catholic University in Milan, joined the Christian Democrats in
the 1950s and was first elected to Parliament in 1963 at age 35.
   Known as an ideas man, he served as minister of industry,
minister of foreign trade, and minister to oversee development of
southern Italy, before becoming party leader.
   De Mita was in a key position when factional fighting within the
Christian Democrats, the country's largest vote-getting party,
undermined the government of Premier Giovanni Goria, who resigned
for the third and final time March 11.
   De Mita's commitment to streamline Italy's cumbersome
bureaucracy and legislative process remains undeterred, despite the
murder of one of his closest advisers on reform, Sen. Roberto
Ruffilli, in April. The leftist terrorist Red Brigades claimed
responsibility.
   On international issues, De Mita favors reductions in nuclear
and conventional arms, but opposes any move that would weaken
Western security.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PRIME MINISTER NOBORU TAKESHITA, Japan</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Takeshita, 64, took over the as premier and leader of the ruling
party on Nov. 6, after being handpicked by his predecessor,
Yasuhiro Nakasone.
   A martial arts expert and former Kamikaze pilot, Takeshita is
well-known for his ability to work behind the scenes for a
compromise.
   Takeshita is the son of a sake brewer and taught junior high
school English before his election to the Shimane Prefecture
assembly in 1951. He was elected to the House of Representatives
seven years later.
   He served as parliamentary vice minister for trade and industry
in 1963 and 1964, and was named chief Cabinet secretary under
Eisaku Sato in 1971. In 1976, he was appointed construction
minister and later became finance minister, a post to which he was
reappointed five times.
   In September 1985, Takeshita represented Japan at the meeting of
five industrial nations in which action was taken to reduce the
value of the yen. Since that meeting, the yen has soared some 70
percent against the dollar, forcing Japan to alter its export-led
economy.
   During his terms as finance minister, Takeshita steadfastly
carried out Nakasone's program of fiscal reform and oversaw the
liberalization of the nation's capital and financial markets.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CHANCELLOR HELMUT KOHL, West Germany</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Kohl, 58, took office in 1982 with the reputation as an
unexciting but dependable former state governor who had limited
experience in international affairs.
   Kohl's coalition government has pledged to stimulate the
nation's economy, but critics, including members of the U.S.
Congress, have charged that West Germany is not doing enough to
fire up its economy.
   Kohl, a staunch Roman Catholic, was born in Ludwigshafen, an
industrial city in a wine-growing region of the Rhine River in
southwest West Germany. His father was a low-level revenue official
and his mother a teacher.
   He graduated from Heidelberg University with a doctorate in
political science in 1958, and has spent his entire adult life in
politics.
   He has been leader of West Germany's Christian Democrat party
since the early 1970s, made an unsuccessful bid for the
chancellorship in 1976 and was a minority leader in Parliament
until 1982.
   Kohl has good personal relations with Reagan, with whom he
shares many conservative views.
   He has sought to normalize relations with Communist East
Germany, but always in the context of improved East-West ties.
   He stirred an international controversy when he invited Reagan
in May 1985 to visit Bitburg, a World War II cemetery which
included the graves of 49 Nazi SS soldiers.
   Jewish leaders worldwide denounced the move.
   Kohl defended the invitation _ which Reagan accepted _ as a
``demonstrative gesture of reconciliation'' 40 years after the
defeat of Adolf Hitler's Nazi Germany.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
