<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit shrank to $9.89 billion
in April, its best showing in more than three years, the government
has reported.
   The April deficit narrowed by 15.5 percent from a seasonally
adjusted March deficit figure of $11.70 billion, with all of the
improvement coming from a steep drop in imports, the Commerce
Department said Tuesday.
   Investors scooped up U.S. securities and dollars in response to
the surprise plunge, which diluted inflation fears, depressed
interest rates and sent the stock market to a post-crash high.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farms across the nation's midsection must have
rain soon or a fierce drought that is scorching fields could become
a national disaster, according to Agriculture Secretary Richard E.
Lyng.
   ``I guess the best thing for us to do is pray for rain,'' Lyng
told the Senate Agriculture Committee on Tuesday. But he said USDA
already was providing drought aid, and he agreed with lawmakers
that congressional action may be necessary.
   Lyng also told the panel, which is considering legislation to
bolster drought-plagued farmers, that it is too soon to assess the
full impact of the drought.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically built cars and light trucks
fell 4.1 percent in early June from last year's levels for the same
period, automakers have reported.
   Domestic car sales in the nine selling days from June 1 to June
10 were down 4.8 percent from the identical period a year earlier
and domestic light truck sales were down 2.7 percent.
   The eight companies that build passenger vehicles in the United
States said Tuesday that they sold 198,647 domestic cars and
112,945 domestic light trucks in early June, down from 208,699 cars
and 116,00 trucks a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC members have agreed to a six-month
extension of their existing production accord, but the long-term
outlook for the fractious cartel remained cloudy as its midyear
conference adjourned.
   Even though it expects oil demand to grow, the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries decided not to raise its production
as a conciliatory gesture to independent producers, said OPEC
President Rilwanu Lukman at a Tuesday news conference ending the
meetings that began Saturday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI and the Naval Investigative Service
have served search warrants at the Pentagon and some 30 other
locations in 12 states in a massive investigation of alleged
defense procurement fraud involving the sale of electronic gear to
the military.
   Part of the investigation is focusing on the activities of at
least two top Pentagon officials, government and industry sources
who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said Tuesday. The
officials' names could not be learned immediately.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee has
approved a controversial product liability bill that consumer
activists immediately denounced as a pro-business assault on the
legal rights of victims of hazardous products.
   Tuesday's bipartisan compromise, which is given virtually no
chance of passing Congress this year, would establish uniform
federal liability standards for lawsuits over defective consumer
goods. Conflicting but generally stronger state laws would be
pre-empted.
</TEXT>
