warned that a half-million weed trimmers made by Black & Decker
Corp. that could pose an electrocution hazard remain in consumer
hands, despite an earlier recall.
   The safety agency said Tuesday it issued the new warning because
of a lower than expected return rate for the trimmers.
   Involved are Black & Decker Model 82209 and Model 82210
bump-feed string trimmers used on grass and weeds.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorneys general of New York,
Massachusetts and Texas have urged Congress to repeal the insurance
industry's federal antitrust exemption.
   The McCarran-Ferguson Act, passed in 1945, grants the antitrust
exemption. A number of states have filed suit claiming that dozens
of insurance companies, under the guise of the exemption, conspired
to create the liability insurance crisis of 1985-86. Insurance
during that time period became unavailable or too costly for many
governments and businesses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tobacco companies have gone on the offensive
to counter fallout from their first loss of a cigarette liability
case.
   Industry lawyers Tuesday attacked the impartiality of the judge
in the four-month trial that on Monday held a cigarette maker
partly responsible for a smoker's lung cancer and awarded $400,000
in damages to her widower.
   They also argued that greed, not principle, drives attorneys who
sue their $35 billion-a-year industry. And they released a detailed
rebuttal of previously secret industry documents introduced by
anti-smoking forces during the trial.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's go-slow approach
to revamping regulation of the stock and futures markets has
received a warm reception from the House Agriculture Committee.
   A top-level administration policy group previously heard its
