<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-15 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rally As OPEC Session Ends</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-OPEC Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Market relief that the latest OPEC meeting ended
without producing a price war has sent oil futures rebounding
following three days of losses.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, rose 40 cents
Tuesday to settle at $16.83 per barrel. The contract had dropped 90
cents over the preceding three sessions, amid skepticism that the
cartel would take any substantial steps to help boost prices.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
rose 1.02 cents a gallon to 49.53 cents and home heating oil
declined rose 0.57 cent to close at 44.32 cents a gallon.
   Members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries ended their meeting in Vienna, Austria after agreeing to
extend their existing production accord for six months.
   Traders who sensed animosity among the various factions within
OPEC were relieved when the gathering concluded, said Richard
Redoglia, a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   ``The people were very, very nervous that these guys would come
out with a full-blown price war,'' Redoglia said. ``When that
(animosity) abated, then the market was able to rally.''
   OPEC's inability to come up with a new production agreement had
been digested by the market on Monday, analysts said.
   The cartel has been divided into two main camps. The majority,
led by Venezuela, wanted to cut production to boost prices closer
to the target level. A minority, led by powerful Saudi Arabia,
OPEC's largest producer, wanted to increase production to take
advantage of a expected increase in demand during the rest of the
year and to maintain market share.
   The agreement extended Tuesday calls for production quotas for
the 12 OPEC members other than Iraq totaling 15.06 million barrels
a day.
   Iraq has refused to sign the accord because it wants a quota
equal to Iran's. The two countries have been at war since 1980.
   Current OPEC production is estimated at 18.5 million barrels a
day.
</TEXT>
