<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Icahn-Texaco Bjt   06-15 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Icahn-Texaco, Bjt,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Block of Texaco Shares Traded _ Who's Buying?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both parties in the sale of a huge block of
Texaco Inc. shares remain unidentified, as the proxy fight between
Texaco and Carl C. Icahn, its largest shareholder, moves closer to
a showdown.
   The sale late Tuesday morning consisted of 7,696,300 shares,
representing 3.2 percent of Texaco's 243 million outstanding
shares, at $50.25 per share, according to New York Stock Exchange
officials.
   Speculation was rife among market-watchers that the investment
firm Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Co. _ known to have had a 4.9
percent stake in the company _ probably did the selling, with Icahn
or allied parties as the likely buyer or buyers.
   Icahn's last report to the government said he held 14.8 percent
of Texaco's stock.
   Last month, he offered to pay $60 per share for the outstanding
Texaco shares he does not already own. After Texaco rejected that
offer, he began campaigning with four allies for seats on Texaco's
14-member board, in order to pressure the company into putting his
buyout offer to a shareholder vote.
   The board election will conclude with the end of Texaco's annual
meeting Friday in Tulsa, Okla.
   Texaco was the most actively traded issue on the New York Stock
Exchange, closing down 12{ cents at $50.37{ a share.
   Wall Street has shown skepticism about Icahn's ability to
finance a takeover bid, keeping the price of Texaco stock well
below his $60 offer.
   That led some analysts to speculate Kohlberg Kravis was the
seller.
   Michael Young, an oil analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co., took that view, and said he believed Icahn was the other party.
   ``If it was KKR, it went into someone else's hands just as tight
and just as aggressive. That sounds like only one person to me _
but we'll have to wait until Icahn files with the SEC to find
out,'' said Young.
   Young was referring to a Securities and Exchange Commission rule
that a shareholder who acquires more than 5 percent of a company's
stock must report all subsequent transactions in the company's
stock.
   He also noted that Texaco's share price remained unchanged after
its volume had surpassed 12 million shares _ a sign that ``whoever
they sold it to, it did not go into loose hands.''
   There has been much speculation on Wall Street over whether
Kohlberg Kravis, a highly successful leveraged buyout firm,
intended to bid for Texaco.
   Icahn said Monday that one of the firm's partners, Henry Kravis,
had told him it might make a bid if Icahn's offer was put before
Texaco's shareholders. Giving a deposition for a lawsuit, Icahn
quoted Kravis as saying he ``might be willing to pay more'' than
$60 a share, the Wall Street Journal and the New York Times said.
   Tom Daly, a spokesman for Kohlberg Kravis, said the firm had no
comment on the matter. A woman at Icahn's office said he had no
comment.
   Lois Johnston, a spokeswoman at Texaco's headquarters in White
Plains, N.Y., said the company had a policy of not commenting on
market activity.
</TEXT>
