<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OPEC Bjt   06-15 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, Bjt,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Higher Following OPEC Quota Extension _ At Least For
Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-OPEC Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices jumped higher following OPEC's
decision to extend its current output ceiling, but experts say the
cartel's failure to resolve key production disagreements makes it
unclear whether the buoyant effect will last.
   ``You can almost toss a coin as to what this will mean for the
market,'' said Paul McDonald, an independent, London-based oil
consultant.
   The deeply-divided Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
as expected announced Tuesday it would extend through the end of
this year its accord to limit daily output to 15.06 million
barrels, even though it expects oil demand to grow.
   The limit is intended to control supplies and help push oil
prices to the cartel's target price of $18 a barrel.
   OPEC actually produces 18.5 million barrels daily, partly
because of cheating by individual nations and partly because the
ceiling, which the cartel last December had extended through June
30, excludes Iraq.
   Iraq refuses to sign the accord because it wants a quota
equalling that of Iran, its war enemy since 1980.
   News of the extension, reached at the cartel's regular mid-year
meeting, immediately buoyed the oil markets.
   The July contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude oil, rose 40 cents to close at $16.83 a barrel Tuesday
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The contract had dropped 90 cents over the preceding three
sessions, amid skepticism that the cartel would take any
substantial steps to help boost prices and jitters of a potential
price war.
   But analysts were divided about what the meeting's outcome would
mean for oil prices in coming months.
   Paul Mlotok, an oil analyst with the New York investment firm
Salomon Brothers Inc., said the meeting ``came out pretty much as
you would have expected.''
   Philip Morgan, an oil analyst with the London investment firm
Warburg Securties, said, ``The factions were just too divided to
come to any conclusion other than this.''
   Both analysts indicated many market watchers were relieved that
the cartel was able simply to agree on the extension, given its
internal frictions.
   ``There was the possibility for serious trouble,'' Mlotok said.
   OPEC has split into two key factions, with the majority, led by
Venezuela, pressing to cut production to boost prices closer to the
target level.
   A minority, led by powerful Saudi Arabia, OPEC's largest
producer, has wanted to increase production to take advantage of an
expected increase in demand during the rest of the year and to
maintain market share.
   Rilwanu Lukman, the Nigerian oil minister who serves as cartel
president, said at the meeting's conclusion that the expected
increase in demand made OPEC optimistic that oil prices would
increase to $18 a barrel by year's end.
   Citing that anticipated demand increase, Mlotok and Morgan said
they expected oil prices to hold in a range of $16 a barrel to $18
a barrel over the next few months.
   McDonald said the output pact extension ``will keep them limping
along at $15 a barrel until the next meeting,'' which the ministers
scheduled for Nov. 21.
   But John Toalster, an oil analyst with the London investment
firm Hoare Govett Ltd., said the meeting's outcome was ``kind of a
fudged issue'' because there had been no commitment to cut
production.
   Saudi Arabia views the target price as a ceiling and sees $14 a
barrel as a floor price, Toalster said.
   Those factors, plus the cartel's overproduction during a period
of high oil stock levels, will depress prices to below $14 a barrel
in the near term, Toalster speculated.
   ``It really will be a testing time in the next few weeks,''
Toalster said.
   OPEC's members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
