<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SteelImports     06-15 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel Imports,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quota Plan Exceeds Goal, Importers Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. steel trade quotas restricted April
imports of finished steel products to 1.33 million tons, or 15.7
percent of the market, well below the plan's 18.5 percent goal,
according to importers.
   Imports during the first four months of 1988, not counting
semi-finished steel bound for U.S. mills, represented 17.5 percent
of the domestic market, importers said Tuesday.
   ``U.S. rolling mills have urgently needed semi-finished imports
since early 1988,'' said Erwin L. Klein, president of the American
Institute for Imported Steel.
   Klein, who also is vice chairman of Steelinter Inc., a New
York-based importer, said American steelmakers more frequently are
citing domestic shortages in seeking Commerce Department permission
to exceed quotas for imported semi-finished steel.
   ``Semi-finished imports even now cannot meet demand,'' Klein
said.
   April's semi-finished imports were 198,119 tons, or 12.9 percent
of all steel imports, the AIIS said, citing Commerce Department
statistics.
   Klein said the situation should be considered in the debate over
extending the quotas, which are scheduled to expire in September
1989.
</TEXT>
