<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CigaretteHazardAppeal     06-15 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Hazard Appeal,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Label Was Enough Warning For Smoker, Appeals Court Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The warning labels on cigarette packages
provide enough information to educate people about the dangers of
smoking, a federal appeals court has ruled in rejecting a Tennessee
couple's $107 million claim against R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.
   Tuesday's ruling by a three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals upheld a lower court decision against the claims
brought by Floyd F. Roysdon and his wife, Ruth Ann, of Oneida, Tenn.
   The Roysdons had sued R.J. Reynolds on the grounds that the
company's Camel and Winston brands of cigarettes were dangerous.
Roysdon said he became addicted to smoking and that addiction
caused the vascular disease which resulted in amputation of his
left leg below the knee almost five years ago.
   Roysdon, 55, accused the cigarette maker of failing to warn him
of the risk of vascular disease and of selling cigarettes that were
defective and dangerous. He said he began smoking Camels in 1946 at
age 13, later switched to Winstons, and was unable to quit smoking
despite repeated attempts to do so.
   The appeals court panel unanimously upheld a lower court's
conclusion that the Federal Cigarette Labeling and Advertising Act,
which was enacted in 1965 to require warning labels on cigarettes,
pre-empts Roysdon's claim that Reynolds failed to warn him.
   The court also upheld a previous decision of U.S. District Judge
Thomas Hull in Tennessee to direct a verdict in favor of Reynolds
on Roysdon's claim that the company sold a defective, dangerous
product.
   Hull ruled the Roysdons failed to establish a jury case as to
whether the cigarettes were unreasonably dangerous. Hull had ruled
that Roysdon could make a case only for harm he allegedly suffered
during the 10 years he had smoked before filing his product
liability lawsuit in July 1984.
   On Monday, a federal jury in Newark, N.J. found Liggett Group
Inc. had failed to warn the public about smoking's dangers and
violated a promise, or ``express warranty,'' in advertisements that
cigarettes were safe.
   The verdict was the first loss by a tobacco company in a
cigarette liability case. The jury found the cigarette maker partly
responsible for a smoker's lung cancer and awarded $400,000 in
damages to her widower.
   However, the six-member jury cleared Lorillard Inc., Philip
Morris Inc. and Liggett of conspiring to mislead the public about
the risks of smoking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
