<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SouthKorea-Economy     06-15 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Economy,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Projection: Economic Slowdown From Labor Disputes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's second quarter economic
growth rate is expected to fall to 9 percent from 15.6 percent a
year earlier, mainly because of labor disputes over wage hikes, the
Economic Planning Board said Wednesday.
   The projected April-June figure would be the lowest quarterly
growth rate in three years.
   The growth rate for the January-March quarter was 15.1 percent.
   The board projected industrial production, which rose 20.9
percent in the first quarter, would drop to 10 percent growth in
the second quarter.
   Officials said more than 900 labor disputes have occurred so far
this year, mosly in April and May, with 815 of them settled. The
exported-oriented auto industry was hardest hit.
   Korean merchandise exports will rise 19 percent in the second
quarter, compared with 35 percent in the first quarter, according
to the official projection.
   Besides the prolonged labor problem, a strengthened Korean won
also was blamed for a slowdown in exports. The Korean currency has
risen 8.7 percent against the U.S. dollar since January.
   The current account surplus, tallied at $3.02 billion in the
first quarter, is likely to decline to $2.38 billion in the second
quarter, the board said.
</TEXT>
