<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 0919EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Futures-Jobs     06-15 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Futures-Jobs,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bull Market For Jobs At Board of Trade Member Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bull market in grain futures and options also
has been bullish for job hunters on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Last month alone, between 800 and 1,000 more clerks and brokers'
assistants were working on the exchange floor compared with a year
ago, according to Raymond Carmichael, an exchange spokesman.
   He said member firms have hired more assistants to help handle
the activity at the Board of Trade, where the volume is up 15
percent so far this year compared with the same period in 1987.
   Prices have soared for grains and soybean futures due to a
strong global demand for U.S. farm products caused by the dollar's
drop in value, declining stockpiles and a recent drought in the
Midwest.
   ``It's a perfect time to get a job as a runner,'' said another
Board of Trade spokesman, William Murschel. ``Those jobs don't pop
up very often but right now is a good time.''
   Runners deliver trading orders from brokers manning telephones
to traders in the pits.
</TEXT>
