<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-15 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0309</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market eased slightly today as traders
moved to cash in on profits posted in a strong rally in the
previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which soared 25 points
to a post-crash high on Tuesday, was off 0.53 point at 2,123.93 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.73 million shares. Losers
outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 2 with 352 up, 531 down and 508
unchanged as of 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Traders said there was some uncertainty in the market today
following Tuesday's rally that was sparked by a
better-than-expected trade report for April.
   While there was ``basic profit-taking going on,'' buying
interest appeared to remain strong, noted Emmanuel Geronimos, a
senior vice president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``I think the market should have sold off a little bit more, but
we're seeing buyers at the moment,'' he said.
   Geronimos said there was little interest in government reports
that showed retail sales rose 0.1 percent and industrial production
rose 0.4 percent, both seasonally adjusted, in May.
   Among actively traded issues, IBM was unchanged at 118}, Texaco
was down [ at 50\, Philip Morris was up [ at 83], and Ford Motor
was unchanged at 52{.
