<2ND_LINE>PM-Industrial Production,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Production in Factories, Mines, Utilities Rises in May</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production at the nation's factories, mines
and utilities rose a moderate 0.4 percent in May, the eighth
consecutive month without a decline, the government said today.
   The Federal Reserve said the May advance followed a stronger
gain of 0.6 percent in April, revised down slightly from a previous
estimate of 0.7 percent. There was a climb of 0.2 percent in March
and no change in February.
   The May increase was about in line with expectations. Economists
had predicted a good showing based on a pickup in production at
auto factories. The output of motor vehicles in May surged to an
annual rate of 7.5 million units, up from the 7 million unit rate
in April and a 6.6 million rate in March.
   With the latest growth, overall industrial production now stands
6.1 percent higher than it was a year ago, a further sign of the
resurgence of the U.S. manufacturing sector, which has enjoyed
booming export sales because of the decline in the value of the
dollar.
   The Federal Reserve also noted what it called ``robust gains''
in the output of business equipment. That fits in with previous
reports showing that businesses plan big jumps in modernization and
expansion spending this year.
   Areas of weak growth or decline include appliances and other
goods for the home, food and gasoline and heating oil.
   The May report showed that output in the manufacturing sector
climbed 0.4 percent, reflecting a 0.9 percent pickup in durable
goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years
and a 0.1 percent decline in production of non-durable goods.
   Output in the mining industry fell 0.8 percent in May, following
a 1.9 percent jump a month earlier. This sector, which includes oil
and gas, has been depressed because of falling oil prices.
   Production at the nation's utilities rose 0.7 percent in May
after a 0.8 percent decline the month before.
   The various changes left the industrial production index in May
at 136 percent of the 1977 annual average, up from 135.5 in April.
</TEXT>
