<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BankBid     06-15 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bank of NY Boosts Bid For Irving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. today boosted its bid for
rival Irving Bank Corp. by slightly raising the stock portion of
the offer and adding other shareholder incentives, including a
special cash dividend.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady valued the revised offer
for all of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding at about $1.4
billion, or $76.53 per share. Its existing tender offer is valued
at around $1.1 billion, or $64 a share.
   Irving said its board of directors would consider the offer at
its next meeting June 21. The bid was presented during a 40-minute
meeting today between Irving Chairman Joseph Rice and Bank of New
York Chairm J. Carter Bacot.
   The meeting was scheduled after New York State Supreme Court
Justice Herman Cahn suggested the two banks attempt to bridge their
differences. Bank of New York has gone to court to overturn the
results of a proxy battle for control of Irving's board and to
invalidate Irving's anti-takeover ``poison pill.''
   Irving management has consistently rejected Bank of New York's
takeover propoals, favoring instead a friendly merger with Banca
Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second-largest bank.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $80 a share for 9.5 million Irving
shares, or about 51 percent, valued at $760 million. In addition,
it said it would pay shareholders interest on the purchase price
from May 31 until the deal closes.
   The proposal is part of a complex defensive restructuring plan
that includes, among other things, sale of Irving assets,
cost-cutting measures and a special cash dividend.
   Bacot said Bank of New York's new bid ``is clearly superior'' to
the Banca Commerciale offer, which has a blended value of as much
as $76.53 per share.
   Wall Street also acted postively to the offer. In midday trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, Irivng jumped $3.12{ a share to
$69.37{, while Bank of New York fell 87.5 cents to $32.87{.
   Bank of New York said its new offer includes $15 in cash, 1.675
shares of its stock, a one-time $2.50 cash dividend and securities
valued at up to $2.50 per share. The securities promise to disburse
profits from the sale of Irving's Wall Street headquarters.
   The existing tender offer, which expires later this month, is
for $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of Bank of New York stock.
   Bank of New York said the offer was subject to the approval of
Irving's board and redemption of its poison pill, which would make
an unsolicited merger prohibitedly expensive.
</TEXT>
