<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Scotus-VW 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-VW, 1st Ld-Writethru,0387</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 9th graf pvs, ``The Schlunks ... to delete reference
to VW design as ``defective.'' Picks up 10th graf pvs, Schlunk's
lawyer ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today allowed Americans who
sue foreign corporations to notify those corporations through their
U.S. subsidiaries.
   The court voted unanimously to let survive a wrongful-death
lawsuit against Volkswagenwerk Aktiengensellschaft (VWAG), a West
Germany-based corporation, growing out of a 1983 traffic accident
in Illinois.
   At issue was whether an international agreement dealing with how
defendants are informed about pending litigation against them _
what lawyers call ``service'' _ precludes state laws allowing other
methods.
   The Hague Service Convention, ratified by both the United States
and West Germany, provides methods for transmitting judicial and
other documents for service abroad.
   But writing for the high court today, Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor said the Hague Service Convention does not apply when, as
in Illinois, a state law makes a foreign corporation's subsidiary
the legal recipient of service.
   ``Where service on a domestic agent is valid and complete under
both state law and the (Constitution's) due process clause, our
inquiry ends and the Convention has no further implications,''
O'Connor said.
   She added, ``Contrary to VWAG's assertion, the due process
clause does not require an official transmittal of documents abroad
every time there is service on a foreign national.''
   Herwig Schlunk sued the West German car manufacturer in 1984
over the Dec. 17, 1983 death of his parents, Franz and Slyvia
Schlunk in a Cook County traffic accident.
   The Schlunks were driving a 1978 VW Rabbit when a negligently
driven car collided head-on with theirs. Their son's suit alleged
that the VW's design contributed to their deaths.
   Schlunk's lawyers sought to deliver a summons and a copy of the
complaint to VWAG through the registered Illinois agent of
Volkswagen of America Inc., the wholly owned subsidiary of VWAG.
   Lawyers for VWAG contended that an Illinois state court's
jurisdiction over it could be invoked only after service was
perfected in accordance with the international agreement.
   That argument was rejected by the justices today, and the case
will proceed in the Illinois state court.
   The case is Volkswagenwerk Aktiengesellschaft vs. Schlunk,
86-1052.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AmericanStores     06-15 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-American Stores,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earnings Expected To Decline Because of Lucky Purchase, Skaggs
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co.'s earnings are
expected to decline for the remainder of 1988 because of its $2.5
billion acquisition of Lucky Stores, American Stores Chairman L.S.
Skaggs told the company's annual meeting.
   But Skaggs said at Tuesday's gathering he expected the
supermarket company's earnings to improve in 1989.
   ``We have chosen to operate the company not for the short-term
gain but rather the good of our shareholders over the long term,''
he said. ``The reason for our acquisition (of Lucky) was to create
long-term value for our shareholders. Our past history has shown
that this strategy has been successful.''
   John M. Lillie, formerly chairman and chief executive officer of
Lucky and now head of American's new Alpha Beta-Lucky subsidiary,
said combining the two companies' operations in California and
Nevada will give American 600 stores with annual sales of about $8
billion.
   Lillie said Alpha Beta will be fashioned into a low-cost
supermarket chain designed for ``the efficient shopper,'' which he
said is one who values shopping time but wants low food prices and
quality products.
   ``Recognizing the value of our customers' time, we also will
institute various Lucky service programs in all the Alpha Beta
stores,'' he said. He referred to Lucky's checkout system that
allows shoppers to pay for their groceries with an automatic teller
machine card and also receive as much as $200 in cash.
   Lillie said that before the acquisition by American Stores,
Lucky began working on a plan called ``the California Strategy.''
   ``This continues to move ahead. The strategy is for us to
dispose our stores in Arizona and in Florida. We will become a
company that serves markets (only) in California and Nevada,'' he
said.
   Lucky already has sold its Arizona stores, and it will ``move
ahead shortly'' to sell its Florida stores, he said.
   ``Our California strategy will allow us to become totally
focused on maximizing the value of our strong market position in
California where the combined operation will have full market share
well in excess of 20 percent,'' said Lillie.
   In a presentation of American Stores' 1987 financial results,
Victor L. Lund, chief financial officer, said the company has
considered its sales for the year to be below expectation.
   The company earned $154.3 million, or $4.19 a share, on sales of
$14.27 billion, compared to $14.5 million, or $3.79 a share, on
sales of $14.02 billion in 1986.
   Shareholders re-elected as directors Skaggs; Leon G. Harmon,
director and former president of First Interstate Bank of Utah, and
I.J. Wagner, president of the Keystone Co., Salt Lake City, and
elected as director John E. Masline, former senior partner of the
accounting firm Ernst & Whinney.
</TEXT>
