<HEAD>Most Grain, Soybean Futures Open Limit Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rocketed higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as weather forecasters reduced
the amount of rain in their short-term predictions for the Midwest.
   Prices for future delivery of soybeans, corn and oats all
rocketed up their limits for daily trading within seconds of the
opening bell.
   In addition to the weather forecasts, buying interest was stoked
by Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng's statement Tuesday that the
dry weather had the potential for becoming a national disaster,
analysts said.
   ``Those statements by Lyng were on traders' minds,'' said Walter
Spilka, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New
York. ``There's just a general bullishness (in the grain markets)
and no one wants to miss it.''
   The drought has begun to take a toll on the corn crop, which is
in a critical stage of development, and will reduce soybean yields
if it continues for another two weeks, Spilka said.
   In early trading, wheat was 5 cents to 10 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.80 a bushel; corn was 6 cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.79{ a bushel; oats were 5 cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.76{ a bushel; soybeans were 7{
cents to 30 cents higher with July at $9.15 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .48 cent lower to .35 cent higher with June at
71.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to 1 cent lower
with August at 72.45 cents a pound; hogs were .35 cent lower to .10
cent higher with June at 50.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .45 cent lower to .08 cent higher with July at 46.45 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday.
