<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Ober Adv17   06-15 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Ober, Adv 17,0762</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday June 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gus Ober: Image Maker For Those Who Already Have `It'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gustavus Ober is an image maker for those who
already have It.
   Money. Clothes. Looks. Personality. Probably in that order.
   For a minimum $10,500 per six-month season, Ober sees that his
personal clients are launched into social orbit. He makes sure they
are invited to New York's proper parties, that they sit at
influential tables at glamorous galas and have dazzling guest lists
for their own soirees.
   Getting Ober to take you on is no small social coup.
   ``I don't take on anybody who I don't think has it,'' he says
simply.
   Seated on an overstuffed magenta couch behind a coffee table
ladened with copies of Vanity Fair and Gourmet magazines, Ober
describes himself as one of a handful of ``personal publicists'' in
the Big Apple who can do in six months what it would take someone
even with the most vibrant qualities six years to accomplish on the
social circuit.
   ``It's expensive,'' he admits. ``You have to have the clothes,
especially if you're a woman.'' A few ``terribly expensive,
sensational dresses'' are just the core of the necessary wardrobe,
he said.
   ``And you have to be willing to entertain and willing to buy
tickets'' to charity benefits, among the more popular grazing
grounds of the wantless.
   Ober even will try to persuade Architectural Digest to feature a
client's apartment _ if the apartment is up to it and if the client
is willing to live with the risks that go along with the general
public knowing just how many Ming vases are sitting on the
mantlepiece.
   While reluctant to disclose his client list, the rotund,
``over-50-year-old'' Ober said many are wealthy newcomers to the
city.
   The reason they seek him out, Ober says, is that ``people are
looking for recognition'' _ from their peers as well as the working
class guy riding the subway who invariably will read about them in
the gossip columns of the daily tabloids.
   Much ink goes to what Ober calls ``nouvelle society'' _ the
likes of real estate devloper Donald Trump and his Czech-born wife,
Ivana.
   ``You can't pick up a paper without the daily press release on
the Trumps,'' he sniffed.
   New York is a different animal of a city. Attributes like
``nice'' and ``intelligent'' may suffice elsewhere, but in New York
the operative characteristic is to be amusing.
   ``Society is a surface scene, so you have to have the right
qualities _ in particular, to be amusing,'' Ober said. ``To be
interesting to anybody here, you have to have a serious interest,''
he said, citing two cosmetic queens.
   ``Elizabeth Arden had her horses, and Helena Rubenstein had her
art,'' he noted. Ironically, investor Asher Edelman, considered by
some to have amassed the most impressive private art collection in
the city, typically is absent from Ober's social scene.
   Ober lived very much the life of many of his clients _ attending
the prestigious St. Paul's boarding school and Princeton
University, where he graduated with a degree in English.
   He worked five years as a reporter for the Baltimore Sun,
interrupted by a stint in the Army, and later traveled the country
for S&H Greenstamps before coming to settle in New York, with no
particular game plan.
   But society is his element, and circulating in it his great
pleasure. Ober realized that when he was about 16 years old and
attended a ``very glamorous'' New Year's Eve party at the home of
Mrs. Evalyn Walsh McLean, the socialite who bought the Hope diamond
and wore it until she died in 1947.
   ``Very few people have the staff to give a party at home
anymore,'' he said, waxing sentimental about a bygone era of maids
in starch-white aprons, cucumber sandwiches and silver tea trays.
   Among some of Ober's observations:
   _``Ladies That Lunch,'' those eulogized by songwriter Stephen
Sondheim, have become a dying breed.
   _Playboys are out. A lot of people play, but the label ``isn't
that helpful anymore.''
   _It's okay to befriend a few penniless ``little people,'' as
long as they are amusing.
   _Safaris in Kenya are still in, as long as you're there to
socialize with government officials and wealthy expatriates and not
to charge after wild game.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday June 17</NOTE>
