<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Father-To-Be Adv18-19   06-15 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Father-To-Be, Adv 18-19,0777</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
<HEAD>Couple Market Items For The Forgotten</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY650 of June 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRING VALLEY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Susan Ecker was pregnant with
her second child, husband Lloyd felt left out.
   ``There's a lot of hype about being in the labor room and all
that, but being the father is still being an outsider,'' said
Ecker, 34. ``I was a wallflower and melted in with the plants
wherever we were.''
   His wife, who apparently has a green thumb for wallflowers,
understood. She bought him a baseball cap and attached a
``Father-to-Be'' logo.
   Thus was born a business empire: Beegotten Creations, a
whimsical little company that aims to provide novelty items to
every expectant relative.
   It is a small empire, with sales of $750,000 last year _ but it
is an empire nonetheless, with ``Family-to-Bee'' T-shirts, mugs,
hats, key rings, mugs, night shirts and even underwear on sale in
2,200 stores nationwide and in the Virgin Islands and the Bahamas.
   The couple is even thinking of expanding out of their current
headquarters, the basement and garage of their Spring Valley home.
   ``I remember the old days when it would rain and I'd put the car
in the garage,'' said Susan wistfully, amid the garage warehouse
crammed with the shirts, mugs and other items.
   The corporate headquarters _ also known as the family room _ is
adorned with photos of the couple's three children, Holly 8, Deena,
6, and Ari, almost 4. The children wander in to use the TV set and
VCR; sometimes they, like their parents, model the company's
clothes.
   The Eckers have part-time help these days _ enough so that
notices about workmen's compensation and labor laws are posted
alongside the kids' photos.
   But the company's toll-free number is generally answered by the
Eckers, even if it wakes them up at 2 a.m.
   All of this came of that single baseball cap that Ecker received
five years ago, and of the cap's popularity.
   Every time Ecker wore it to the beach ``another belly came up to
me and asked where I got the hat. They wanted it for their
husbands,'' Ecker said.
   For Ecker, who had spent his life selling toilet paper, the
inspiration couldn't have come at a better time: ``Toilet paper was
losing its glamour. I used to tell people I was working my way up
to tissues,'' said Ecker.
   Armed with his sense of humor and marketing skills, the Eckers
took their talents to a hidden market _ the relatives of the
baby-to-be. And to jazz it up, they replaced the ``be'' in ``father
to be'' with a yellow bumblebee.
   When Ecker first took samples of his hats and shirts to
retailers, small maternity shops were his best customers; he found
that the people who bought the items were not men, but moms-to-be.
   Department stores were uninterested and remain indifferent. They
have no departments for men's maternity items.
   Ecker's road trips and mail-order advertising in maternity
magazines paid off. He abandoned the toilet paper trade in 1984 to
devote himself to Beegotten Creations and expanded the family line
to include grandmas, grandpas, sisters and brothers.
   While relatives provided a fresh market for the Eckers' novelty
items, the Eckers soon realized that the ``real money'' was in
maternity clothes.
   So now, the garage-warehouse stocks nursing shirts reading,
``I'd rather be sleeping,'' maternity underwear with the slogan,
``Oh, to be thin again,'' and T-shirts and nightshirts from ``Prego
State'' and ``Camp Prego.''
   The company boasts 54 different items and more to come, with a
new focus on the actual baby _ shirts, bibs and stretchies bearing
such prophetic sayings as ``Princess to Bee,'' ``Trouble to Bee,''
``Doctor to Bee'' and ``Extremely Complex to Bee.''
   If Susan was the center of attention during her pregnancies,
Lloyd plays the starring role at Beegotten Creations. He's the
company's president, says Susan, because ``it's hard to live with a
6-foot-4 poutty man.''
   Last year, Ecker tried to start a new business. When a woman
found out she was pregnant, she would call Ecker. He would don a
bumblebee outfit and went to the husband's office. There,
resplendent in his yellow-and-black finery, he would announce that
the husband was a father-to-be.
   After a dozen or so such calls, the ``Bee-Man'' went into
semi-retirement because of cold weather. It's unclear whether
summer will witness the revival of the 6-foot-4 walking insect.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
