<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ESOPRevisited Adv20   06-15 0888</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-ESOP Revisited, Adv 20,0914</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday June 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Employee-Owned Company Looks Back After Three Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhoto
^By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEYMOUR, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Klimovich paused, looked at his boss
and made sure he wasn't revealing any secrets when he talked about
his toughest decision since becoming a director at Seymour
Specialty Wire.
   Given the go-ahead, Klimovich told about his vote approving a
consultant's plan that has resulted in the elimination of 13 jobs
at the 110-year-old mill bought three years ago by its employees.
   Klimovich's position was the same as that of eight other
directors, but he was more vulnerable to criticism. He is president
of United Auto Workers Local 1827, and as such, is trusted with
protecting the company's blue-collar workers.
   ``When push comes to shove, decisions are made for the best
interest of the company. It's not easy sometimes,'' said Klimovich.
``It's been on-the-job experience. From the day we decided to to
this it's been an education.''
   The company's employees bought the plant from National
Distillers & Chemical Corp. a little more than three years ago, on
April 17, 1985, for a reported $10 million. They established an
employee stock ownership plan, or ESOP, under which each employee
owns a piece of the company.
   Seymour Wire is the largest employee-owned company in
Connecticut, and has a management team unlike any other in the
country, according to President Carl Drescher.
   The company is run by nine directors that include the company
president, the union president, five elected employees and two
outside members selected by the other seven.
   The arrangement has led to a democratically run company that
often finds its members wearing more than one hat making some
difficult choices.
   The company has been profitable for its roughly 220 employees,
55 of whom are salaried. It doesn't make its finances public, but
it will be free of creditors in about five years.
   About 60 percent of the stock is still held by those who loaned
money for the buyout, Drescher said from his office overlooking the
mill and the nearby Naugatuck River.
   Drescher, a 58-year-old Woodbury resident, was plant manager
when the employees made their buyout offer. He had been at the
company for 11 years at the time and fully supported the move
because the mill was profitable.
   National Distillers had decided to sell the wire mill simply
because it wanted out of the metals business.
   Freed from a corporate parent, Seymour Wire has learned to
handle its own insurance and pension plans, and monitor its
finances with existing staff, said Drescher.
   ``We had to put in a computer and take care of all these other
functions,'' Drescher said. ``But the other thing is we are more
free to do what needs to be done. We don't have a hierarchy to go
through. We make up our own minds here.''
   Given its success, Seymour Wire has been visited by people from
across this country and as far away as China. Drescher said it can
be distracting and he tries to limit company tours. But he does
have some advice for others considering a similar course of action.
   ``If it's a unionized operation, it's important that there has
been good union relations beforehand,'' he said. ``You've also got
to have a viable operation. I think some ESOPs have been tried
where perhaps they shouldn't have been. This was not a last-gasp
effort to save jobs.''
   Drescher has put his experience at the plant to good use, but he
also continues to gain more business know-how. His most recent
learning experience was the negotiation of a new three-year
contract with the blue-collar employees.
   The previous contract had been negotiated when the plant was
sold, and a new one was put in place on the the company's third
anniversary.
   ``The board is controlled by employees. It was a difficult
position for union officials to be directors,'' Drescher said.
``They have to represent the interests of the union and
shareholders.''
   The contract took about two weeks to negotiate, and Klimovich
said it was unique because all employees know the company's
finances.
   ``I knew what the company could do, and it helped,'' said
Klimovich, who at age 43 has worked at the plant for 17 years. His
father worked at the plant for more than 40 years.
   The unionized workers earn an average of about $25,000 a year
and receive shares of the stock based upon their earnings, said
Drescher. The company has a turnover of about 12 employees a year,
which helped the company implement the consultant's recommendations
that troubled Klimovich.
   The consultant said the company needed to reorganize its work
schedules to become more efficient. Seymour Wire decided to make
the schedule change and adjust to the subsequent loss of 13 jobs
through attrition rather than layoffs. That process is now nearly
complete.
   Drescher and Klimovich said the labor-management problems
encountered at the company are no different than when it was owned
by National Distillers. Employees, however, are more willing to
voice their opinions and suggestions.
   ``It's beneficial for them to say something. They point out
things that need to be addressed,'' Drescher said.
   ``The grumblers are grumblers. There are people who are going to
grumble no matter waht you do,'' said Klimovich.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday June 20</NOTE>
