<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-GasRoyalties     06-15 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Gas Royalties,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas Laws Apply To Five-State Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas courts may apply that state's laws in a
natural gas royalties dispute between an oil company and mineral
rights owners from five states, the Supreme Court ruled today.
   The justices, by a 6-2 vote, ruled that applying Kansas law to
claims against Sun Oil Co. by people in other states is valid.
   The decision, carried in an opinion by Justice Antonin Scalia,
upheld a Kansas Supreme Court ruling that Sun is liable for
interest on some previously suspended gas royalties.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor dissented, and Justice Anthony M. Kennedy did not
participate.
   The controversy began in 1979 when property owners in Kansas
sued Sun in state court to recover royalties for higher gas rates
charged to the company's customers.
   Some 3,100 owners of natural gas leases in Texas, Oklahoma,
Louisiana, New Mexico and Mississippi were represented in the class
action lawsuit.
   Sun had suspended payment of some royalties while awaiting
approval of the higher gas rates by the Federal Power Commission.
   After the rates were approved, the leaseholders sought to
recover not only the higher royalties but also the interest they
said they were owed for Sun's use of their money.
   The Kansas Supreme Court ruled last year Sun owed interest on
the increased royalties based on rates prevailing in Kansas during
the time the suit was pending.
   The interest rates ranged from 10.5 percent to 16.5 percent.
   The Kansas court also ruled the state's statute of limitations,
imposing a five-year deadline for filing such suits, applied to all
claims against Sun, regardless of what state the gas rights are
located.
   The nation's highest court agreed last October to hear Sun's
appeal, and today it ruled against the company.
   The case is Sun Oil vs. Wortman, 87-352.
</TEXT>
