<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   06-15 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overall Trade Deficit Widens, Retail Sales Weak, Industrial
Production Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to incorporate reports of first-quarter trade
deficit and industrial production. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America's overall trade deficit widened unexpectedly in the
first quarter of the year, the government said today in an ominous
report about the U.S. economic future.
   The Commerce Department release came one day after stocks and
bonds rallied powerfully in reaction to another report that the
April merchandise trade deficit shrank to $9.89 billion, the best
showing in more than three years.
   But the department said today the broadest measure of U.S.
trade, which includes services and investment earnings as well as
merchandise, showed a $39.8 billion deficit in the first quarter,
vs. a $33.5 billion deficit the previous quarter. The rise was from
a decline in investment earnings abroad.
   This figure is considered important because it is a key
reflection of how the United States has been transformed from the
world's largest creditor nation six years ago into the world's
largest debtor now.
   It means America's wealth must now be transferred abroad to
service its debt and the only way the total debt will be reduced is
for the country to start running surpluses in merchandise, which
experts do not expect soon.
   Many economists have warned the debt service burden will
eventually lower Americans' standard of living, the price the
United States will have to pay for living beyond its means in the
1980s.
   The latest trade news and fear of a Midwestern drought combined
to have a sobering effect on Wall Street. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrial stocks, which surged 25 points to a post-crash high
Tuesday, was off 5.87 points at 2,118.60 by midday. Bond prices
also eased after a strong showing Tuesday.
   Other government reports released today suggested a mixed
picture of the economy.
   The Commerce Department said retail sales, restrained by lagging
car purchases, rose a scant 0.1 percent in May, evidence of weak
consumer demand and a possible economic slowdown.
   On the other hand, the Federal Reserve said production at the
nation's factories, mines and utilities rose a moderate 0.4 percent
in May, the eighth consecutive month without a decline.
   With the latest growth, overall industrial production now stands
6.1 percent higher than it was a year ago, a further sign of the
resurgence of the U.S. manufacturing sector.
   In other news Tuesday, oil prices rose after the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries decided to prolong an
output-restraint pact until the end of the year.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, rose 40 cents to
settle at $16.83 per barrel.
   Elsewhere, major automakers said sales of domestically built
cars and light trucks fell 4.1 percent in early June from last
year's levels for the same period. But industry analysts attributed
the decline largely to buying incentives that inflated sales in the
year-earlier period.
   Car sales were down for all domestic makers except Toyota Motor
Corp., which was just beginning U.S. production last year, and
Mazda Motor Corp., which began U.S. production in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
