<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AudiRuling 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Audi Ruling, 1st Ld-Writethru,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Audi AG Wins Lawsuit Claiming Sudden Acceleration Killed Boy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to RECAST to show that unintended
acceleration is an allegation only. PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `John
and ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has rejected a $48 million suit filed
by a couple who said their Audi 5000 car surged forward and killed
their 6-year-old son.
   The federal jury deliberated three hours Tuesday before finding
in favor of Audi AG of West Germany and its parent, Volkswagen of
America, in one of numerous suits alleging Audis are subject to
sudden, unintended acceleration.
   John and Kristi Bradosky of Jackson Township near Canton, had
said their son Joshua was pinned between the car and their garage
wall in 1986.
   Mrs. Bradosky said the engine was running and that she had
shifted from park into drive and gently placed her foot on the
accelerator when the car surged forward and would not stop despite
pressure on the brake pedal.
   The family sought $24 million in compensatory damages each from
Audi and Volkswagen. They also asked for $36 million in punitive
damages from Volkswagen, but U.S. District Judge David Dowd had
barred such an award.
   The judge had instructed the jurors to find for the defendants
if they were unable to name a defect that caused the accident.
   ``The jury found no defect in the vehicle,'' said Ian Ceresney,
an attorney for Audi. ``I think it vindicates our case. It
demonstrated that the jury found the vehicle did not cause the
accident.''
   Bradosky said he had not decided whether to appeal. ``I think
the jury has made a decision, and we think it was a wrong
decision,'' he said. ``They made a critical error in judgment.''
   The Center for Auto Safety, a consumer group based in
Washington, contends at least 1,646 accidents resulting in 402
injuries and five deaths have been linked to sudden acceleration
when the Audi 5000 was shifted into gear.
   Investigators have been unable to find any defect common to the
vehicles that would cause the problem.
   Audi last week offered to settle a class-action lawsuit in
Chicago that could affect as many as 300,000 Audi owners
nationwide. Under the proposed settlement, the company would pay up
to $2,000 to past and current owners of Audi 5000s who buy a new
Audi. The automaker did not admit fault.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
