<HEAD>Dollar And Gold Rise Overseas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar strengthened in Europe on
Wednesday amid market optimism about the currency's direction,
foreign exchange dealers said. Gold prices also rose.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7848 late Wednesday,
cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7925.
   Other late rates in Europe Wednesday compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.7535 West German marks, up from
1.7460; 1.4675 Swiss francs, up from 1.4615; 5.9137 French francs,
up from 5.8840; 1.9690 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9600; 1,300.62
Italian lire, up from 1,292.50; 1.2170 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2162.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 126.32 Japanese yen, up
from 125.05 late Tuesday. In London late Wednesday the dollar
traded at 126.25 yen.
   Gold bullion closed in London, the major European trading
cventer, at a bid price of $452.60 a troy ounce, up from Tuesday's
$448. The Zurich late bid price was $453, up from $448.
   Gold dealers said their market was sluggish but the price rose
because of mostly speculative dealings.
   The Hong Kong gold market was closed for a holiday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $7.14 bid a troy ounce,
up from $6.91.
</TEXT>
