<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     06-15 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0498</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market tentatively flirted with plus
territory today but retreated to lower levels after Tuesday's sharp
rally touched off a bout of profit-taking.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which surged 25 points
to a post-crash high on Tuesday, was down 3.56 points at 2,210.91
an hour before the closing bell.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 123.88 million shares. Losers
outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 8 with 682 up, 766 down and 510
unchanged as of 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   In midafternoon, the Dow was up nearly a point but then pulled
back.
   Traders said there was some uncertainty in the market today
following Tuesday's rally, which was sparked by a
better-than-expected trade report for April.
   Stocks were off slightly throughout the session mirroring the
bond market, where prices were depressed partly because of
inflation fears generated by sharply higher grain and other
commodity prices.
   ``Corn and soybeans were up the limit,'' noted Charles Jensen,
chief technical analyst at MKI Securities Corp.
   But Alfred Goldman, director of technical market analysis at
A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis, said traders used the
activity in the commodity markets as an excuse to sell.
   ``Whenever the market gets overbought, traders look for an
excuse to take profits,'' he said.
   Most observers remain optimistic that the market is just taking
a breather after the Dow's 200-point runup over the past two weeks.
   ``We're overdue for a pretty nice correction,'' Jensen said.
``Any setback would be the normal thing to expect.''
   Analysts expect some momentum to be generated by money managers
pressured to increase the equities in their portfolios supported
the market. With an unusually high amount of cash on hand, they are
looking to beef up their portfolios as the second quarter draws to
a close.
   As one trader said, ``They want to hop aboard the train before
it leaves the station.''
   Dealers said the market had little interest in government
reports that showed retail sales rose 0.1 percent and industrial
production rose 0.4 percent, both seasonally adjusted, in May.
   Among actively traded issues, Texaco was down ~ at 49{. The oil
giant said its lawsuit against Carl Icahn charges the raider with
trying to purchase Texaco stock without making the required
disclosures.
   Zenith was up 2\ at 26|. The International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers said it is interested in bidding for some or all
of the company's consumer electronics division through an employee
stock ownership plan.
   Elsewhere, IBM was down [ at 118|, Upjohn was up 1{ at 34\,
Hewlett Packard was off 1} at 53| and Chrysler was down [ at 25.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.44 to 154.08. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 0.64 at 308.24.
</TEXT>
