<FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EEC-Steel     06-15 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Steel,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Proposes Scrapping Remaining Steel Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
proposed Wednesday that steel production quotas in the 12-nation
trading bloc be eliminated on June 30.
   The EEC Commission said an improvement in demand and prices in
the European steel market would allow the quotas to be dropped
after eight years. The quota system was set up in 1980 to allow the
steel companies time to restructure their operations in face of a
worldwide surplus in steel production capacity.
   Despite the upturn in the steel industry, the commission said
its plan to return the steel sector to free competition would lead
to the loss of about 55,000 jobs over the next three years.
   The commission's proposal, which is to be discussed by industry
ministers on June 24, followed an informal agreement in May that
quotas for hot-rolled coil, which is used in the automobile
industry, and cold-rolled sheet should be abolished.
   The commission went further in proposing to also scrap quotas
for heavy plate, used mainly in shipbuilding, and for heavy
sections, sold to the construction industry.
   The quotas now prop up prices for about 40 percent of the bloc's
steel output, which amounted to 126.5 million metric tons in 1987.
   The commission said its plan to end the quotas also was in
response to the failure of the European steel industry to come
forward with cuts in production capacity amounting to about 15
million metric tons.
   Last December, the trade bloc extended the quotas for at least
six months on the condition steel companies make firm commitments
to shut down excess production capacity.
   The commission said the industry had not made any major
commitments to close 7.5 million tons of capacity for production of
hot-rolled coil and cold-rolled sheet as decided last December.
   This implied there ``was not a crisis in these sectors,'' the
commission said, noting that EEC steel mills were operating at a
high 77 percent of capacity and that prices were rising regularly.
   In the other two sectors _ heavy plate and heavy sections _
commitments to close capacity fell far short of the 6.9 million
tons earmarked in December, the commission said.
   However, it said capacity cuts in those two sectors were still
necessary as mills operated at a low 60 percent despite a rise in
prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880615-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     06-15 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0191</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished mixed today but
appeared to have recovered from a bout of profit-taking on the
heels of Tuesday's rally.
   Traders said there was some uncertainty in the market following
the sharp runup in the previous session, which was sparked by a
better-than-expected trade report for April.
   Stocks were off slightly throughout most of the session, but
most observers said the market was merely taking a breather.
   ``We're overdue for a pretty nice correction,'' said Charles
Jensen, chief technical analyst at MKI Securities Corp., who noted
that the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials has climbed 200 points
in the past few weeks.
   ``Any setback would be the normal thing to expect,'' he said.
   Overall, however, the tone in the market was optimistic. Traders
said that money managers, who have an unusually high amount of cash
on hand, are under pressure to purchase equities for their
portfolios before the end of the quarter.
   The momentum they create is likely to sustain a moderate rally,
analysts say.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
