<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Takeshita Bjt   06-15 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Takeshita, Bjt,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeshita Promises To Assert New Economic Strength At Toronto
Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said Wednesday
Japan has now gained the status of an economic power, and it is his
responsibility to assert that role at the upcoming economic summit
in Toronto.
   Takeshita said his goals at the summit, which begins next week,
are to discuss cooperation on trade, resolving the problems of
international debt and restoring self-sustained growth to
developing countries.
   In advance of the meeting, which President Reagan and leaders of
five other nations will attend, Takeshita sounded unconcerned about
trade problems with the United States and ongoing talks to resolve
them. The prime minister said it is natural for the two countries
to occasionally disagree.
   ``We have come to share this deep relationship bilaterally and
it is natural that we should face a greater number of frictions,''
he said. ``As friction arises, we should address and resolve those
problems jointly.''
   However, he said ``all countries concerned, ourselves as well as
our trade partners, should be careful so that individual issues
will not lead to an unreasonable nationalism.''
   U.S. and Japanese officials have been haggling for months on
trade issues, including a prolonged dispute over opening Japanese
markets to more imports of American beef and oranges.
   The United States wants the total removal of the beef and citrus
import quotas it had accepted in a 1984 agreement that expired in
March. Japan has balked at the demand.
   Nearly two weeks ago, during a Reagan-Takeshita meeting in
London, U.S. officials praised Japan for the progress the country
has made in opening up its markets to American goods and boosting
domestic demand in its economy to narrow its trade surplus.
   The prime minister said Wednesday he is pleased with Japan's
growth rate, and noted that unemployment and inflation have been
kept down.
   ``Seen from the international perspective, it's fit that Japan
has gained the status of an economic power,'' Takeshita said,
adding, ``It is my responsibility to assert that strength'' at the
Toronto meeting.
   Leaders from West Germany, Canada, Britain, France and Italy
also will be at the summit.
   Takeshita said that at the gathering, he wants to discuss his
concerns about Asia's newly industrialized economies _ Hong Kong,
Singapore, Taiwan and South Korea _ and regional problems such as
Cambodia and the Philippines.
   He said Japan is considering further debt relief to
underdeveloped countries and would like to improve cooperation with
international financial institutions.
   Japan is the world's largest donor of overseas economic aid. In
the fiscal year ended March 31, it gave $7.4 billion to developing
countries.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno said last week the government would
increase overseas aid if other nations need it.
</TEXT>
