<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ZenithPlant     06-15 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenith Plant,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Protests Bidding Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Zenith Electronics Corp.'s
Springfield television manufacturing plant want to buy the factory,
but Zenith is blocking their bid, the employees' union charged
Wednesday.
   ``Zenith is actively talking with other bidders, including
foreign firms, but so far refuses even to provide its employees
with the financial information necessary to structure a bid,'' said
J.J. Barry, president of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
   Zenith spokesman John Taylor, reached by telephone at company
headquarters in Glenview, Ill., said he was aware of the IBEW's
charges but had no further comment. He would not confirm that the
Springfield plant is for sale.
   ``The management of Zenith has known of the employees's interest
(in buying the plant) since the beginning of April,'' Barry said.
``Now they have informed us that if allowed to bid, we will be
given less than one week to prepare an offer ....''
   Barry said corporate bidders have been negotiating with Zenith
since May. He asked Zenith to give the union more time to prepare
its own bid or a joint bid with another party.
   ``The employees should be given a fair opportunity to
participate in a process that will have an enormous effect on their
lives and welfare,'' Barry said.
   The Springfield plant is the only American manufacturer of
television sets. It employs more than 1,600 hourly workers.
   Zenith has suffered losses as a result of heavy foreign
competition. In an effort to save the Springfield plant last year,
members of IBEW Local 1453 approved a five-year contract that
called for an 8 percent cut in hourly pay.
</TEXT>
