<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank of NY Boosts Bid For Irving</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf ``Wall Street ...'' to UPDATE with closing
stock prices. Picks up 9th graf pvs ``Bank of New York ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. sweetened its offer for
rival Irving Bank Corp. on Wednesday, slightly raising the stock
portion of the bid and adding other shareholder incentives,
including a special cash dividend.
   But some banking analysts predicted Irving management would
continue to snub its persistent suitor in favor of a friendly
merger with the state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's
second-largest bank.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady valued the revised bid for
all of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding at around $1.4
billion, about 25 percent higher than the existing hostile $1.1
billion tender offer which remains in place.
   The new proposal is subject to approval from Irving's board of
directors and redemption of its anti-takeover ``poison pill,''
which would make an unsolicited merger prohibitively expensive.
   Irving had no comment on the latest bid, except to say that its
board of directors would consider it at its next meeting June 21.
The bid was presented during a 40-minute meeting Wednesday morning
between Irving Chairman Joseph Rice and Bank of New York Chairm J.
Carter Bacot.
   The meeting was scheduled after New York State Supreme Court
Justice Herman Cahn suggested the two banks attempt to bridge their
differences. Bank of New York has gone to court to invalidate
Irving's poison pill and overturn the results of a proxy battle in
which shareholders recently chose Irving's incumbent board over
Bank of New York's nominees.
   Bacot maintained that Bank of New York's new bid ``is clearly
superior'' to the Banca Commerciale offer, which has a blended
value of as much as much as $76.50 per share.
   Wall Street also acted positively. In trading on the New York
Stock Exchange, Irving jumped $3.87{ a share to $70.12{, while Bank
of New York fell 75 cents to $33.
   Bank of New York said its new offer, worth around $76 a share,
includes $15 in cash, 1.675 shares of its stock, a one-time $2.50
cash dividend and securities valued at up to $2.50 per share. The
securities promise to disburse profits from the sale of Irving's
Wall Street headquarters.
   The existing tender offer, which expires later this month, is
for $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of Bank of New York stock, or
around $64 a share.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $80 a share for 51 percent of
Irving, or about $760 million. The proposal is part of a complex
defensive restructuring plan that includes, among other things,
sale of Irving assets, cost-cutting measures and a special cash
dividend.
   Analysts weren't surprised Bank of New York upped the stakes in
the 9-month-old takeover saga since its existing hostile bid was
having little success with shareholders and management. But some
questioned whether it would do any good.
   ``Just reading through the lines the fact that Irving's formal
response was that its board of directors would meet next week seems
to indicate they're somewhat cool to the offer,'' said Michael
Starr, of Duff & Phelps Inc. in Chicago. ``If they were truly
interested, they would have looked into it much sooner than that.''
   Virginia Adair of Merrill & Lynch Co. agreed that Irving
remained committed to keeping its current management intact, which
would happen through a merger with Banca Commerciale, not Bank of
New York.
   ``I think Irving will be hoping BCI will raise its offer,'' she
said.
   But Starr said, ``At this point in time I don't see any reason
for BCI to increase its offer. However, if some of those court
cases are won by Bank of New York, BCI would have to increase its
offer to remain competitive.''
   He said on the surface, Bank of New York's bid appears slightly
more attractive because it offers shareholders tax advantages that
Banca Commerciale doesn't and already has received regulatory
approval.
</TEXT>
