<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-15 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Narrowly Mixed; Gold Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed narrowly mixed Wednesday as it
picked up some strength from Tuesday's positive trade deficit news
but also began to mark time in advance of next week's economic
summit.
   Gold prices were slightly higher. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a bid price of $451.75 for a troy ounce of gold, up
from $450.15 late Tuesday.
   Trading was quiet on the foreign-exchange markets, but a bullish
sentiment about the dollar remained following Tuesday's trade
report, said Dan Holland, a trader with Discount Corp.
   ``Most people believe the dollar has bottomed,'' Holland said.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the nation's
merchandise trade deficit narrowed in April to $9.89 billion, the
lowest monthly deficit in more than three years. The report set off
a strong rally in the dollar on Tuesday.
   On Wednesday, the government reported that the deficit in the
broadest measure of U.S. foreign trade, the current account,
widened in the first three months of the year to $39.75 billion.
The news had no effect on dollar trading, Holland said.
   The current account includes merchandise trade and trade in
services, which reflects primarily the flow of investment earnings
between countries.
   Varick Martin, a vice president at Union Bank of Switzerland's
New York office, said the dollar was expected to remain at its
current levels or perhaps drift through the end of the economic
summit in Toronto.
   No new developments were expected from the gathering, which will
bring together President Reagan and the leaders of six other major
industrial nations, Martin said.
   ``Everything's been reached ...,'' he said. ``They're pleased
with the dollar's stability.''
   The dollar turned in a mixed performance against the Japanese
yen Wednesday. It closed at 126.32 yen in Tokyo, up from 125.05
late Tuesday, but it slipped in later London trading to 126.25 yen.
In New York, it edged down to 126.35 yen from 126.54 yen late
Tuesday.
   The British pound slipped against the dollar in London. It cost
$1.7848 late Wednesday, cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late
$1.7925. But the pound gained slightly against the dollar in New
York, where sterling was quoted at $1.7868, up from $1.7863.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's prices, included: 1.75425 West German marks, up from
1.74955; 1.46785 Swiss francs, up from 1.4626; 5.9110 French
francs, up from 5.8970; 1,298.50 Italian lire, up from 1,297.50;
and 1.2150 Canadian dollars, down from 1.21825.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's rates,
included: 1.7535 West German marks, up from 1.7460; 1.4675 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4615; 5.9137 French francs, up from 5.8840;
1.9690 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9600; 1,300.62 Italian lire, up
from 1,292.50; 1.2170 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2162.
   Gold closed at $451.90 a troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange in
New York, up from $450.15 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, gold bullion closed in London, the major European
trading center for the metal, at a bid price of $452.60 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $448. In Zurich, Switzerland, the late bid
price was $453, up from $448.
   The Hong Kong gold market was closed for a holiday.
   Silver bullion closed at $7.129 a troy ounce on the Commodity
Exchange, up from $7.0420 late Tuesday. Silver traded late in
London at a bid price of $7.14 a troy ounce, up from $6.91.
</TEXT>
