<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-88 1832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Patlex-Borman     06-15 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patlex-Borman,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Eastern Chief to Head Laser-Patent Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Borman, a former astronaut and Eastern
Airlines president, on Wednesday was named chairman and chief
executive officer of Patlex Corp., a high-technology manufacturer
and laser company.
   Borman, 60, was appointed as Patlex announced plans to spin off
its manufacturing operations into a new company. Borman, who flew
Gemini and Apollo missions for NASA and went on to head Eastern
until its sale to Texas Air Corp. two years ago, has been a member
of the Patlex board of directors.
   Patlex has a 64 percent interest in laser patents held by its
vice president, Gordon Gould, inventor of the technology. Those
patent rights, gained through litigation begun in 1979, cover a
significant percentage of the lasers used in the United States, the
company said.
   To be spun off are Oram Electric Industries Ltd., which makes
transformers for the telecommunications, defense and computer
industries; Reshef Defense Technologies Ltd., which produces
electronic gear for the military; and Apollo Lasers Inc., which
makes scientific and small systems lasers.
   The manufacturing group had $13 million in sales last year,
while laser royalties brought in $4.5 million, said Yaron Eitan,
Patlex executive vice president.
   Patlex shareholders would receive one share of stock in the new
company for each two shares of Patlex stock they hold.
   The spin-off is intended to separate the laser patent licensing
activity from the manufacturing business, which requires additional
capital to finance growth, said Richard Samuel, the former Patlex
chairman and chief executive officer who will be chairman of the
new company. Samuel will be Patlex president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
