<2ND_LINE>AM-Lower-Risk Cigarette,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company to Begin Making Lower-Risk Cigarettes in August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Keeney Tobacco Corp. will begin making a
new risk-reducing cigarette on Aug. 1, the company announced
Wednesday.
   ``We need all the help we can get,'' said L. Douglas Keeney,
chairman and chief executive officer of Keeney, a subsidiary of CA.
Blockers Inc. ``A lot of people are suffering illnesses as a result
of the risks of smoking, our surgeon general says.''
   Keeney said the company expects to produce 2 billion cigarettes
during its first manufacturing phase, a figure that has doubled due
to an increase in firm orders.
   The cigarette contains an additive called N-BLOCTIN, a cleansing
alcohol that absorbs and eliminates the undesirable nitrosamines in
the smokestream.
   The cigarette reduces the risks for both the smoker and those
breathing the smoke, Keeney said.
   ``We learned how to make the cigarette back in December,''
Keeney said. ``And I'll tell you, we made a vile cigarette.
   ``Our mandate ... was it must conform to the behavioral form and
to the sensory pleasures smokers seek in smoking.''
   The company, which offers contract production for generic brand
and private label cigarettes, will make the risk-reducing cigarette
at its manufacturing plant in Petersburg, Va., according to a news
release.
   Keeney Tobacco will manufacture the risk-reducing cigarette for
Optima Ltd. of Jerusalem and Cigarretta La Moderna of Monterrey,
Mexico.
   The company has not yet disclosed its plans for U.S.
distribution, Keeney said in an interview.
   ``International tobacco sales are up 40 percent for the first
quarter of 1988,'' Keeney said in the statement. ``It's obvious
that the key overseas marketing is the `Made in U.S.A.' label. Our
fundamental strategy is to maximize our profits in this area.''
</TEXT>
