<DOCNO> AP880615-0343 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-06-15-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WPPSSSuit     06-15 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WPPSS Suit,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Says Too Many Questions Remain To Approve $276 Million
Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Wednesday took under
advisement a request to delay a proposed $276 million settlement of
a giant lawsuit resulting from the Washington Public Power Supply
System's default on $2.25 billion in bonds.
   U.S. District Judge William Browning took the matter under
advisement after hearing arguments from an attorney representing
investors holding more than $40 million in bonds that the proposal
failed to show how the settlement would be divided.
   ``It's not unnatural for a holder to wonder what a holder is
going to obtain in a settlement,'' said Ann Acker of Chicago,
representing two institutional investors and a bank holding the
bonds issued to finance two abandoned nuclear plants.
   But other attorneys for plaintiffs and defendants said the
proposed settlement was fair and would provide 27,000 bondholders
and claimants a payoff after years of waiting, while allowing
defendants to escape further litigation.
   ``We hope to buy peace,'' said Herbert Wachtell of New York,
representing bond underwriters, who would pay $92 million of the
$276 million.
   Ms. Acker, of the law firm of Chapman and Cutler, told the court
that a delay was proper because there had been no discussion on how
the settlement proceeds would be allocated among the different
classes of plaintiffs, including original investors and speculators
who bought bonds at reduced rates after the 1983 default, or how
much legal fees would be.
   Defendants tentatively settling so far include more than 50
utilities, underwriters, a legal adviser to WPPSS and WPPSS
directors.
   Trial against the remaining defendants is scheduled to begin
Sept. 7 in Tucson, Ariz., and could last two years. Remaining
defendants include utilities holding 80 percent interest in the
plants, engineers, WPPSS advisers and the supply system itself.
   Though the defaulted bonds totaled $2.25 billion in value,
claims by bondholders and by former bondholders with fraud claims
cover only about $1.5 billion of the bonds.
   Ms. Acker, representing Kemper Financial Services, Continental
Assurance and First Midwest Bancorp, was the only attorney arguing
against the partial settlement.
   Paul Bernstein of New York, a lead counsel for plaintiffs, said
the settlement was fair. He said Browning could decide on legal
fees when lawyers submitted their proposed bills to him.
   Browning has ruled that under state securities law the plaintiff
attorneys must prove defendants intended to defraud investors, and
were not simply negligent.
   However, the judge also has said plaintiffs would be allowed to
claim fraud and negligent misrepresentation, a lesser standard of
proof, under state common law.
   The supply system attempted to build five nuclear power plants
in the 1970s, including the two abandoned plants.
   One operating plant started up in late 1984, while two others
were mothballed while only partially complete. Those three plants
are being paid for through regional power rates levied by the
federal Bonneville Power Administration.
   The abandoned plants, over which the suits were filed, were not
included in the financial arrangement with BPA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
